{"title_page": "Sea of Thieves", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 action-adventure game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sea of Thieves\n| image =Sea of thieves cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Rare (company)|Rare]]\n| publisher = [[Microsoft Studios]]\n| director = [[Gregg Mayles]]\n| producer =  Joe Neate\n| designer = Mike Chapman\n| programmer = Peter Campbell\n| artist = Ryan Stevenson\n| writer = {{ubl|Chris Allcock|Mike Chapman}}\n| composer = [[Robin Beanland]]\n| engine = [[Unreal Engine 4]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released = 20 March 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Sea of Thieves''''' is a 2018 [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[Rare (company)|Rare]] and published by [[Microsoft Studios]]. The player assumes the role of a pirate who completes voyages from different trading companies to become the ultimate pirate legend. ''Sea of Thieves'' is a [[first-person perspective|first-person]] [[cooperative gameplay|multiplayer]] game in which a group of players [[cooperative gameplay|cooperates]] with each other to explore an [[open world]] via a pirate ship. The game is described as a \"shared world adventure game\", which means groups of players will encounter each other regularly during their adventures.\n\nMost of Rare's employees worked on the title and the game was first conceptualized in 2014. The game was inspired by players of [[personal computer|PC]] games such as ''[[Eve Online]]'', ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'', who used the tools provided by these games to create their own personal stories. The company explored different settings for the game, such as vampires and dinosaurs, though it eventually settled on the pirate theme, drawing inspirations from films including ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[The Goonies]]''. The game features a progression system that only unlocks cosmetic items as the development team wanted to encourage both casual and experienced players to play together. Compared to Rare's other games, ''Sea of Thieves''{{'s}} development process was more transparent, with Rare inviting fans to test the game's early builds.\n\nMicrosoft released the game in March 2018 for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] and [[Xbox One]]; it was also one of the earliest [[first-party]] games released for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers. The game received generally mixed reviews upon release, with critics praising the game's ship combat, multiplayer gameplay, visuals, and game physics. Criticisms were directed at the game's lack of content, progression, and shallow gameplay. Rare envisioned the title as a \"[[game as a service]]\" and released numerous content updates after the game's release. The game is a commercial success and has attracted more than 10 million players as of January 2020. Microsoft declared the game the most successful new [[intellectual property]] (IP) they have released in the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|generation]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Sea of Thieves gameplay screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|In this gameplay screenshot, the player is firing cannonballs at a hostile pirate ship, which is controlled by another group of players.]]\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' is a [[first-person (video games)|first-person]] [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game. At the beginning of the game, the player selects their [[procedurally generated]] player avatar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kg5ny/rare-give-me-a-little-control-in-making-my-sea-of-thieves-character|title=Rare, Give Me a Little Control in Making My 'Sea of Thieves' Character|first=Austin|last=Walker|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The game is set in a shared world, which means groups of players will encounter each other throughout their adventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jun/22/sea-of-thieves-pirate-adventure-rare-game-developer|title=Sea of Thieves \u2013 the pirate adventure that heralds the return of Rare|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Solo players pilot a [[sloop]] while players playing in a group control a [[galleon]] cooperatively by assuming different roles such as steering the ship, hoisting sails, navigating using the [[compass]], managing the [[anchor]], and [[navigation|scouting]] from the [[crow's nest]].<ref name=\"sailing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-sailing-terms-sail-into-the-wind-ship-combat-5001|title=Sea of Thieves sailing - how to sail into the wind, win ship combat and sailing terms explained|first=Chris|last=Tapsail|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17144806/ships-sloop-galleon-map-barrels-canonballs-bananas-planks-chests-ammo-clothing-vanity-equipment|title=Sea of Thieves ships guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Occasionally players may encounter hostile players who may attack them with [[cannonball]]s or [[Naval boarding|board]] their ship.<ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/116340/7-more-things-we-want-in-sea-of-thieves|title=7 more things we want in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If areas under the deck take damage, water will flow in and cause the ship to gradually sink. Players need to patch up the holes with [[Plank (wood)|plank]]s of wood and bail out water using buckets.<ref name=\"sailing\"/> [[Alliance]]s can be established with other parties of players. They will receive [[gold]] bonuses when a group in the same alliance completes a voyage. Forming an alliance does not prevent players from attacking each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/106528/how-to-form-an-alliance-in-sea-of-thieves|title=How to form an alliance in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=3 August 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If the player dies, they are sent to a [[ghost ship]] known as the Ferry of the Damned where they wait until they can [[respawn]].<ref name=\"25 tips\"/> A competitive multiplayer mode named \"Arena\" was introduced in the ''Anniversary'' update; it allows four teams of players to compete against each other by gathering silver in smaller maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-new-arena-mode-is-all-the-good-and-bad-1834515034|title=Sea of Thieves New Arena Mode Is All The Good (And Bad) Of Sea of Thieves|first=Heather|last=Alexander|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can complete [[quest|voyage]]s offered by the game's three [[clan (video games)|faction]]s: Gold Hoarders, Order of Souls, and the Merchant Alliance. In the quests offered by Gold Hoarders, players are given a [[treasure map]] or a riddle to locate the treasure. The voyages offered by the Order of Souls are mainly combat challenges.  Merchant Alliance's missions demand players to deliver goods such as live animals to vendors within a limited time.<ref name=\"factions\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17142984/quest-voyage-rank-map-gold-hoarders-order-of-souls-merchant-alliance-rank|title=Sea of Thieves guide to quests and voyages|first=Russ|last=Frushtick|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> When players collect a treasure chest, they need to deliver them to the representatives of the quest-giving faction, though the one holding the chest are defenseless and may have it be taken by other players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-guide-voyages-quests-factions-kraken-skeleton-forts/|title=Sea of Thieves beginner's guide: voyages, factions, and making money|first=Tyler|last=Wilde|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing voyages earns players [[gold]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-how-to-get-started-in-sea-of-thieves-how-to-start-your-first-voyage-controls-explained|title=How to get Started in Sea of Thieves - How to Begin Your First Voyage - Step by Step Guide to Setting Sail, Controls Explained|first=Tom|last=Orry|work=[[USgamer]]|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> which can be spent on buying new customization items or enhancements from merchants, [[bladesmith|weaponsmith]]s, and [[shipbuilding|shipwright]]s.<ref name=\"shops\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143940/shop-vendor-clothing-equipment-weaponsmith-shipwright-trading-companies|title=Sea of Thieves shop guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Items such as [[pet]]s can also be purchased using [[microtransaction|real-world currency]] by accessing the Pirate Emporium store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/09/14/sea-of-thieves-microtransactions/|title=Sea Of Thieves gets a microtransaction store|first=Emily|last=Gera|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=14 September 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> [[Doubloon]]s, earned through completing commendations from the Blige Rats, the fourth trading company that distributes quests, challenges, and cosmetics added to the game via post-launch updates, can be traded for gold or reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/sea-of-thieves-guide/2019/5/24/18629418/events-gold-doubloons-bilge-rats-duke-cosmetics|title=Sea of Thieves events and doubloons guide|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ''Anniversary'' update adds Tall Tales, which are a series of structured narrative missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/13/18617975/sea-of-thieves-tall-tales-review-story-mode-characters|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Tall Tales is the star feature of the anniversary update|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing quests also earns the player reputation points, which unlock more complicated quests from each faction and additional purchasable items.<ref name=\"factions\"/><ref name=\"shops\"/> When players reach rank 50 with all the factions and solve all the riddles, they will earn the title of \"pirate legend\", which grants players new cosmetic items and access to a pirate hideout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-pirate-legend-mysterious-stranger-riddle-solution-rewards-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Pirate Legend and Mysterious Stranger explained - riddle solution, rewards, and how to become Pirate Legend|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can freely explore the game's [[open world]] on their own or with other players.<ref name=\"exploration\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/13/17003856/sea-of-thieves-game-preview|title=Sea of Thieves is huge, fun, and just what the Xbox One needs|first=Tom|last=Warren|work=[[The Verge]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-island-map-locations-shapes-names-5001|title=Sea of Thieves map - Island locations, names, shapes and how to find every island|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> When exploring a new location, players can retrieve items such as [[banana]]s, which restore their [[health (game terminology)|health]], wood planks, and cannonballs. [[Ammo]] can be resupplied using the ammo chest in the Captain's Quarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/03/09/sea-of-thieves-open-beta-tips-guide-treasure/|title=Sea of Thieves open beta tips: sailing, treasure, combat and the puke bucket weapon|first=Matt|last=Martin|work=[[VG 247]]|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Weapons including [[cutlass]]es, [[pistol]]s, [[blunderbuss]]es, and [[sniper rifle]]s can be used to defeat hostile enemies like [[skeleton]]s.<ref name=\"25 tips\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-tips/|title=25 essential Sea of Thieves tips to know before you play|first=Sam|last=Loveridge|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\"/> When players are sailing the sea, they may sometimes face adverse weather conditions such as thunderstorms<ref name=\"sailing\"/> or encounter shipwrecks, messages in bottles, and monsters such as the [[megalodon]] and the [[kraken]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/sea-of-thieves-shrouded-spoils-release-date|title=You\u2019ll finally get rewards for killing giant monsters in today\u2019s Sea of Thieves expansion|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"exploration\"/> Skull clouds indicate the locations of Skeleton Forts, which are [[Raid (military)|raid]]s that can be completed by players in the same server.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-skeleton-forts-skull-clouds-stronghold-keys-fort-assaults-explained-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Skeleton Forts - Skull Clouds, Stronghold Keys and how to defeat the raids|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Players can interact with each other using [[emotes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/sea-of-thieves-to-get-pets-emotes-and-new-cosmetics-in-forthcoming-update|title=Sea of Thieves to get pets, emotes and new cosmetics in forthcoming update|first=Imogen|last=Donavan|work=VideoGamer|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> They can also play [[musical instrument]]s together and drink at [[tavern]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/banjo|title=Sea of Thieves is adding banjos to the musical mix|first=Ian|last=Boudrea|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-rare-is-already-immortalising-players-most-memorable-achievements-in-sea-of-thieves-world|title=Rare is already immortalising players' most memorable achievements in Sea of Thieves' world|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The ''Anniversary'' update allows players to engage in leisure activities like [[fishing]], hunting, and cooking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was developed by the UK-based developer [[Rare (company)|Rare]].  Almost all of Rare's 200 staff members worked on the game.<ref name=\"Watchable game\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-will-sea-of-thieves-resurrect-rare|title=Sea of Thieves and the Rare revival|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team began conceptualizing the game in 2014 and wanted to create a title where players can create stories together. The team took five months to create the game's playable prototype named ''Athena'' using the [[Unity (engine)|Unity]] [[game engine]].<ref name=\"no secret\"/> After playing the prototype, Microsoft's executives including [[Phil Spencer]] and Kudo Tsunoda agreed to [[green-light]] the game's development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/7-things-you-didnt-know-about-sea-of-thieves|title=7 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Sea of Thieves|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-09-sea-of-thieves-early-protoypes-looked-very-different|title=Sea of Thieves' early prototypes looked very different|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare employees also provided the voice for all of the [[non-player character|non-playable character]]s.<ref name=\"voice\"/> ''Sea of Thieves'' marked Rare's shift from using its own proprietary engine to using [[Unreal Engine 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2018-sea-of-thieves-tech-analysis|title=How Sea of Thieves' tech creates a unique gaming experience|first=John|last=Linneman|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=25 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRare was often considered to be a secretive studio. Since ''Sea of Thieves'' is a multiplayer-focused game, the studio adopted a more transparency approach to the game's development to ensure that the game's content would resonate with players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/sea-of-thieves-rare-developer-interview-how-players-are-helping-with-design|title=Sea of Thieves is using a unique dev tool: you|first=Stephen|last=Farrelly|work=[[Red Bull]]|date=9 November 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"no secret\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/11/17/how-rare-cast-away-its-developmental-process-for-sea-of-thieves.aspx|title=How Rare Cast Away Its Developmental Process For Sea Of Thieves|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> The team allowed fans to take part in the game's development by joining the Insider's Program, which granted players access to an early build of the game. The program allowed Rare to experiment with different features while collecting players' feedback. The participants could also discuss with the developers in a private forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-22-sea-of-thieves-insider-programme-offers-chance-at-testing-early-builds|title=Sea of Thieves Insider Programme offers chance at testing early builds|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> More than 30,000 players joined the program.<ref name=\"art\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/06/21/how-microsofts-rare-imagined-the-pirate-world-of-sea-of-thieves/|title=How Microsoft\u2019s Rare imagined the pirate world of Sea of Thieves|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Through the program, Rare learnt more about how players interact with each other and used the information to help the team make gameplay decisions;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/sea-thieves-interview-rare-studio-head-craig-duncan-bold-new/|title=Sea of Thieves interview: Rare studio head Craig Duncan on a bold new direction for the legendary British developer |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> for instance, the team decided to include solo play after many players from the Insider's Program requested it.<ref name=\"solo play\"/>\n\n===Influences and setting===\n{{quotebox|quote=\"I love the idea of things happening in the world that literally can shape the ongoing fabric and lore of ''Sea of Thieves''. The [[Black Beard]] of ''Sea of Thieves'' being a real player in a real crew with a real name - that's really hard to do if you've already painted everyone down a path you want them to go through\"|source= \u2014 Joe Neate, executive producer of Rare<ref name=\"friendliest\"/>|width=33%}}\nStudio director Craig Duncan described ''Sea of Thieves'' as the \"friendliest\" multiplayer game.<ref name=\"friendliest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-13-the-sea-of-thieves-endgame-sounds-super-cool|title=The Sea of Thieves endgame sounds super cool|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> While Rare is traditionally a console game developer, it realized how players from [[personal computer|PC]] [[survival game]]s like ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'', and [[simulation video game|simulation game]]s such as ''[[Eve Online]]'' crafted their own stories by using the tools provided in the game. However, Rare remarked that these games are often very punishing in nature, and the team aspired to create a more light-hearted and accessible version of these games.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/sea-of-thieves-return-to-form-for-rare-studi/|title=Who cares about loot? For \u2018Sea of Thieves,\u2019 Rare hid the real fun in the hijinks|first=Will|last=Fulton|work=Digital Trends|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Sea of Thieves'' was designed to be a \"light canvass of a world\" where players create their own stories.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> The game did not feature any narrative component at launch because the team felt that by offering players a structured narrative, they would only be playing an experience that was handcrafted for them. Joe Neate, the game's executive director, described the game as an \"improv\" comedy, and added that the game is about going \"off-script\".<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> Rare shaped the world and the game's lore to reflect players' actions, including various [[Easter egg (media)|easter egg]]s to celebrate their actions or achievements. The team believed that if a narrative campaign is included, incorporating players' actions into the game's lore would become difficult.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/>\n\nThe company explored different settings for the game, such as [[vampire]]s and [[dinosaur]]s, though it eventually settled on the [[piracy|pirate]] theme because it matched the game's core concept which encourages cooperation. Rare also saw less competition in the market.{{efn|Duncan elaborated that the team was thankful that they did not chose dinosaur as the setting due to the release of ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]'' (2017)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/19/rare-considered-vampire-dinosaur-themes-for-sea-of-thieves-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Considered Vampire, Dinosaur Themes for Sea of Thieves \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The pirate theme allows players to have the freedom to do what they want in the game's world and decide freely how they want to play and behave. The team looked at various sources for inspiration, including ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[Black Sails (TV series)|Black Sails]]''. Designer Mike Chapman believed a lot of parallels can be drawn between ''Sea of Thieves'' and ''[[The Goonies]]'', in which a group of friends bond together while they search for treasure, creating a journey that all of them would fondly remember.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Neate added that the game's goal was to evoke \"[a] sense of travel and exploration and discovery\".<ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/22/17971710/sea-of-thieves-lore-forsaken-shores-cursed-sails-worldbuilding|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 lore is surprisingly deep, silly and refreshing|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team implemented the \"infinite pirate generator\" instead of allowing players to customize their avatar as they feared that some players would create \"abominations\" that would not have fit the game's visual style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/317084/How_Rare_designed_Sea_of_Thieves_infinite_pirate_generator.php|title=How Rare designed Sea of Thieves' infinite pirate generator|first=Jack|last=Yarwood|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=27 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game features a stylized visual style with hand-painted textures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gdcvault.com/play/1025015/Visual-Adventures-on-Sea-of|title=Visual Adventures on 'Sea of Thieves'|work=GDC Vault|first=Ryan|last=Stevenson|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Duncan added that the team chose this painted art style because they wanted it to be \"timeless\" and reflect the  \"joyful\" and \"delightful\" game world.<ref name=\"art\"/>\n\n===Gameplay design===\n\nRare noticed that in many multiplayer games, experienced players would focus on grinding for endgame content instead of playing with other players, while novice players would worry about their progression lagging significantly behind more experienced players. Therefore, the team introduced \"horizontal progression\", in which players would only earn cosmetic items as they achieve a higher rank; all items have the same attributes, so endgame content would not confer gameplay bonuses to experienced players. This progression system encourages more experienced players to assist novice players when they are completing voyages, and reduce the gap between the two experience levels.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-has-fully-embraced-power-levelling-according-to-the-design-director-its-not-what-you-think/|title=Sea of Thieves 'fully embraces' power levelling, according to the design director (it's not what you think)|first=Connor|last=Sheridan|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> As a \"shared world\" adventure game, Rare opted to maintain the distance between each player group in a server rather than limiting the number of players a server can accommodate, so that players get to encounter other players regularly but not too frequently.{{efn|Chapman estimated that a player will see another player-controlled ships every 15 minutes to half an hour.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-doesnt-have-a-maximum-or-minimum-server-size|title=Sea of Thieves Has a Very Smart Approach to Server Size|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay was designed to test the player's [[soft skills]]. Players need to exercise their [[common sense]] in order to solve the challenges: for instance, players need to learn to read maps. To encourage players to develop these skills, the game does not feature a beginner's [[tutorial]] as the team wanted players to discover the game's mechanics by themselves.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> The team also intentionally avoided setting gameplay rules to encourage players to utilize their creativity.<ref name=\"solo play\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/when-we-made-sea-of-thieves/|title=When We Made\u2026 Sea of Thieves|first=Marie|last=Dealessandri|work=[[MCVUK]]|date=20 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Despite this, Rare also included [[emergent gameplay]] in a more systemic manner by introducing shipwrecks and fonts that players can discover. Chapman described these locations of interest as the \"catalyst for stories\" which draw different players together, fostering cooperation or competition. Being attacked by [[sea monster]]s also add a layer of unpredictability to the game as these encounters are random.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Due to the emergent gameplay, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also considered as a \"watachable and sharable game\", and the team hoped that this will lure players who watched the game on [[video game live streaming]] platforms such as [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] or [[Mixer (service)|Mixer]] to purchase it.<ref name=\"Watchable game\"/>\n\nWhile the game allows solo play, the game is designed to be a multiplayer game in which players cooperate with each other. Chapman added that [[cooperative gameplay]] enhances the experience because \"it makes sense in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/06/14/sea-of-thieves-lets-you-captain-your-pirate-ship-solo-but-at-a-cost/|title=Sea of Thieves lets you captain your pirate ship solo \u2014 but at a cost|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=14 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game does not feature any [[character class]] or specialization to encourage players to adopt different roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-01-10-sea-of-thieves-devs-explain-how-its-design-encourages-cooperation|title=Sea of Thieves devs explain how its design encourages cooperation|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The maximum crew size is four as Rare felt that if the group is too large, it does not reflect a sense of \"intimate friendship\" and players may splinter off and hinder inter-player communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-dev-explains-why-the-maximum-crew-size-is-4-players|title=Sea of Thieves Dev Explains Why the Maximum Crew Size Is 4 Players|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Neate described the game as a \"friendship creation tool\" and hoped that the game could become a platform where players can befriend strangers.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> Rare further added that they felt they have the responsibility to create a \"positive online social space\".<ref name=\"online space\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rare-on-sea-of-thieves-online-we-have-a-responsibility-as-game-creators-to-make-a-positive-social-space/|title=Rare on Sea of Thieves: 'We have a responsibility to make a positive online social space'|first=Joe|last=Donnelly|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Design changes were made to champion the concept of cooperation and friendship. For instance, players cannot hurt others in the same crew,<ref name=\"online space\"/> and all rewards are shared equally among crew members.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> In one of the game's early prototypes, players in the same crew can betray each other, though the feature was scrapped because the team felt that the experience was \"horrible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/275112/How_emotional_psychology_and_The_Goonies_inspired_Sea_of_Thieves.php?|title=How emotional psychology and The Goonies inspired Sea of Thieves|first=Kris|last=Graft|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=16 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Neate added that the game provided \"literally no reason or motivation to do anything other that cooperate\".<ref name=\"online space\"/> Rare incorporated several anti-toxicity measures. For instance, players can vote to lock a disruptive player into a [[jail cell|brig]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17153164/sea-of-thieves-toxic-brig-scuttle-ship-code-of-conduct|title=Sea of Thieves team put anti-toxicity strategies into game\u2019s core design|first=Julia|last=Alexander|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was announced by publisher [[Xbox Game Studios|Microsoft Studios]] during its press conference at [[E3 2015]], with Duncan describing the game as the \"most ambitious project\" from Rare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/rare-announces-most-ambitious-project-yet-sea-of-thieves-294014.phtml|title=Rare announces 'most ambitious project yet,' Sea of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=MacGregor Burleson|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=15 June 2015|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Initially set to be released in 2017, the game was delayed to early 2018 to allow additional development time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2017-sea-of-thieves-delayed-until-2018/1100-6450690/|title=E3 2017: Sea Of Thieves Delayed Until 2018|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft marketed the game extensively. Players who pre-ordered the game received the Black Dog Pack, which included exclusive cosmetic content and access to a closed [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]]. Players could also purchase a separate ''Sea of Thieves''-themed Xbox [[wireless controller]], and anyone who purchased the [[Xbox One X]] console from 18 to 24 March would receive a free digital copy of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/you-can-still-buy-an-xbox-one-x-and-get-sea-of-thi/1100-6457467/|title=You Can Still Buy An Xbox One X And Get Sea Of Thieves Free For A Limited Time|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/17/a-complete-guide-to-sea-of-thievess-preorder-bonuses|title=A Complete Guide to Sea of Thieves' Preorder Bonuses|first=Chris|last=Reed|work=[[IGN]]|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft's Australian branch partnered with music band Captain Hellfire & The Wretched Brethren for a two-day event in which the pirate band sang different [[sea shanty|sea shanties]] requested by players. The program was broadcast via [[Facebook]], Mixer, and Twitch from 24 to 25 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/xbox-partners-with-an-australian-pirate-band-for-a/1100-6457517/|title=Xbox Partners With An Australian Pirate Band For A Cool Sea Of Thieves Promo|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft also launched \"The Quest\", an [[alternative reality game]] where players needed to solve different riddles. The winners would receive one of four golden bananas (each valued at \u00a320,000) as rewards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/10/sea-of-thieves-global-digital-treasure-hunt-features-golden-banana-prize|title=Sea of Thieves Global Digital Treasure Hunt Features Golden Banana Prize|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also hosted a competition which tasked fans to create [[Achievement (video games)|achievement]]s for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-01-24-can-you-come-up-with-a-sea-of-thieves-achievement|title=Can you come up with a Sea of Thieves Achievement?|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Several [[stress testing (software)|stress test]]s and betas were released ahead of the game's official launch on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-09-sea-of-thieves-final-beta-is-here-open-to-everyone-on-xbox-one-and-pc|title=Sea of Thieves' Final Beta is here, open to everyone on Xbox One and PC|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/08/sea-of-thieves-release-date-announced|title=Sea of Thieves Release Date Announced|first=Lucy|last=O'Brien|work=[[IGN]]|date=8 December 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>  At launch, many players reported that they could not log into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-issue-status-cinnamonbeard-server-e/1100-6457547/|title=Sea Of Thieves Issue Status: CinnamonBeard Server Error, Not Getting Gold, More|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Duncan said that Rare underestimated the server capacity as the number of people logging in to play the game during the launch period was unexpectedly high. Various fixes have been released to improve the game's online infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-dev-details-how-itll-address-server/1100-6457590/|title=Sea Of Thieves Dev Details How It'll Address Server And Performance Issues|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=23 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a retail release, ''Sea of Thieves'' is an [[Xbox Play Anywhere]] title and the game was made available for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/sea-of-thieves-rare-xbox-one-microsoft|title=Sea of Thieves is Rare\u2019s riskiest voyage yet, but it\u2019s a huge success|first=Matt|last=Kamen|work=[[Wired.co.uk]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-17-these-are-the-first-xbox-play-anywhere-games|title=These are the first Xbox Play Anywhere games|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> However, [[cross-platform play|crossplay]] between PC and Xbox One players was made optional in February 2019 to ensure that all players feel that \"they have a level playing field\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-cross-play-will-be-made-optional-be/1100-6464703/|title=Sea Of Thieves Cross-Play Will Be Made Optional Between Xbox One And PC|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=4 February 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> On PC, the game was initially only available through Xbox Game Pass and [[Microsoft Store]] before Microsoft announced a release for [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-finally-coming-to-steam/1100-6475560/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Finally Coming To Steam|first=Steven|last=T. Wright|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Players began to set rules, develop their own sets of challenges, and host their own events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/25/17258750/sea-of-thieves-community-rules-agreements-parley|title=Sea of Thieves fans are setting their own rules in the pirate sandbox|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-07-26-meet-the-pirate-who-created-a-racing-league-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Meet the pirate who created a racing league in Sea of Thieves|first=Imogen|last=Beckhelling|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> To further encourage these players, Rare announced plans to incorporate [[private server]]s into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-will-have-private-servers-to-support-creative-community-events/|title=Sea of Thieves will have private servers to support creative community events|first=Fraser|last=Brown|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Downloadable content===\nRare envisioned ''Sea of Thieves'' to be a \"[[games as a service|game as a service]]\" and expected it to continue receiving updates for 10 years.<ref name=\"updates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2018/feb/13/rare-sea-of-thieves-multiplayer-pirates|title=A pirate's life for me: Rare's ambitious plans for Sea of Thieves revealed|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-next-game-you-play-may-never-end/|title=The next big video game you play may never end|first=Ian|last=Sherr|work=[[CNET]]|date=17 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> After the team had fixed most of the technical issues, they began looking at players' feedback and identified that players were complaining that there were not enough activities for them to participate in. Chapman stated that the team's strategy was to give players what they want, ensure that they fit within the ''Sea of Thieves'' universe, and \"surprise\" players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rare-plans-to-give-sea-of-thieves-players-what-the/1100-6460067/|title=Rare Plans To Give Sea Of Thieves Players What They Want|first=Alexandro|last=Fillari|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare has four teams of employees working in parallel to create the game's various expansions so that large content update can be released frequently while ensuring that sufficient development time can be given to each team.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/05/01/sea-of-thieves-developer-rare-has-3-teams-making-major-updates/|title=Sea of Thieves developer Rare has 3 teams making major updates|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team hoped to a large content update every 6 weeks to 2 months, and used \"Bilge Rat Adventures\", which are time-limited challenges to fill the gap between each expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/interview/2018/07/04/rare-on-rpg-elements-battle-royale-potential-and-the-future-of-sea-of-thieves|title=Rare On RPG Elements, Battle Royale Potential, And The Future Of Sea Of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=Hilliard|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=4 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ultimate goal was to make the game \"as big and successful as it can be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/22/rare-studio-head-on-sea-of-thieves-post-launch-plans-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Studio Head on Sea of Thieves Post-Launch Plans \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The first major expansion, ''The Hungering Deep'', was developed within 2 months. The second expansion, ''Cursed Sails'', introduced skeleton ships controlled by [[artificial intelligence]] (AI). Despite being adamant about not doing so prior to the game's launch, the team decided to implement the feature as it was one of the biggest fan requests.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/> The ''Anniversary'' update that added both Tall Tales and Arena mode was so massive that it was described as a \"relaunch\" for the game.<ref name=\"second launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-04-10-the-second-launch-of-sea-of-thieves|title=The second launch of Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> All the expansions are free of charge as they did not want to divide the player base.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-08-06-keeping-sea-of-thieves-afloat|title=Keeping Sea of Thieves afloat|first=James|last=Batchelor|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=7 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Major expansion packs\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:16%;\"| Release date\n! style=\"width:70%;\"| Notes\n|-\n| ''The Hungering Deep''\n| 20 May 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-17-sea-of-thieves-first-proper-content-update-the-hungering-deep-gets-a-teaser-trailer|title=Sea of Thieves' first proper content update, The Hungering Deep, gets a teaser trailer|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| ''The Hungering Deep'' introduced new tools such as the Speaking Trumpet and a narrative campaign featuring the [[megalodon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-sea-of-thieves-hungering-deep-guide/megalodon-shark-guide|title=Sea of Thieves Megalodon Guide - How to Find the Megalogon, How to Defeat the Hungering One|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Cursed Sails''\n| 31 July 2018<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\"/>\n| ''Cursed Sails'' introduced AI ships, a new story campaign, the [[brigantine]] which can accommodate three players, and the \"alliance\" mechanic.<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-cursed-sails-update-now-live-4-things-you-need-to-know/|title=Sea of Thieves' Cursed Sails update now live - 4 things you need to know|first=Sam|last=Prell|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Forsaken Shores''\n| 27 September 2018\n| ''Forsaken Shores'' introduced new cosmetic items, a new volcanic region named Devil's Roar, a new type of voyage named \"Cargo Run\", a [[rowboat]], and a narrative campaign centered on Forsaken Shores Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-25-heres-everything-happening-in-this-weeks-sea-of-thieves-forsaken-shores-update|title=Here's everything happening in this week's Sea of Thieves Forsaken Shores update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Shrouded Spoils''\n| 28 November 2018\n| ''Shrouded Spoils'' introduced [[fog]] into the game, changed the AI behavior of both the kraken and the megalodon, and altered some of the existing gameplay systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-28-sea-of-thieves-big-shrouded-spoils-update-is-here-and-the-waters-never-been-deadlier|title=Sea of Thieves' big Shrouded Spoils update is here, and the water's never been deadlier|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Anniversary''\n| 30 April 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/111488/what-time-does-the-sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-start|title=What time does the Sea of Thieves Anniversary Update start?|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=30 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The ''Anniversary'' update introduced a separate player-versus-player (PvP) competitive multiplayer mode named ''Arena'', the first narrative-based Tall Tales campaign named ''Shores of Gold'' which consists of nine chapters, and the ''Hunter's Call'', which added fishing, cooking, and hunting into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update/|title=Sea of Thieves' anniversary update finally makes the game reach its full potential|first=Samuel|last=Roberts|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Black Powder Staches''\n| 17 July 2019\n| ''Black Power Staches'' includes a series of missions that task players to collect gunpowder barrels and then sold them to various factions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-black-powder-stashes-update-is-live/|title=Sea of Thieves' Black Powder Stashes update is live|first=Christopher|last=Livington|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Dark Relics''\n| 15 August 2019\n| ''Dark Relics'' introduces new voyages, cosmetic items, new commendations, and rowboats mounted with [[harpoon gun]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-dark-relics-update-is-here-with-new-voyages/|title=Sea of Thieves' Dark Relics update is here with new voyages|first=Jordan|last=Gerblick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=15 August 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Smuggler's Fortune''\n| 11 September 2019\n| The update adds the Pirate Emporium, a new store that supports [[microtransaction]]s. A new type of currency named \"Ancient Coins\" can be purchased from both the Xbox store and in-game. Players can also buy [[monkey]]s and [[parrot]]s as pets from the Pirate Emporium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/9/11/20860753/sea-of-thieves-smugglers-fortune-update-pets|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Smuggler\u2019s Fortune update is now live, and it adds pets|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Fort of the Damned''\n| 16 October 2019\n| ''Fort of the Damned'' introduced several [[Halloween]]-themed cosmetics, a new skeleton font, and a new type of enemy named Shadow Skeletons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-gets-spooky-with-new-fort-of-the-da/1100-6470608/|title=Sea Of Thieves Gets Spooky With New Fort Of The Damned Update|first=Jordan|last=Ramee|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=16 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''The Seabound Soul''\n| 20 November 2019\n| ''The Seabound Soul'' introduced fire into the game with the fiery cannonball and a new Tall Tale which has players partner with adventurer Sir Arthur Pendragon as they embark on a journey to seek a \"feared ship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-the-seabound-soul-update-now-live/1100-6471606/|title=Sea Of Thieves' The Seabound Soul Update Now Live|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Festival of Giving''\n| 11 December 2019\n| ''Festival of Giving'' introduced several [[Christmas]]-themed cosmetic items and a mission that tasks the players to assist Stitcher Jim to retrieve a shipment of gifts lost at sea. A new tutorial mode named Maiden Voyage was also added into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-holiday-event-adds-gift-seeker-voyages-and-tutorial-mode/|title=Sea of Thieves' holiday event adds Gift Seeker Voyages and tutorial mode|first=Jordan|last=Gerbick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Legends of the Sea''\n| 15 January 2020\n| ''Legends of the Sea'' celebrated the game's most notable players by tasking players to embark on a quest to seek various easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/legends-of-the-sea-release-date|title=Sea of Thieves: Legends of the Sea makes you part of the lore|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Crews of Rage''\n| 19 February 2020\n| ''Crews of Rage'' brought players back to Devil's Roar to complete Bounty Voyages, which involves acquiring a new chest known as the Chest of Rage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2020/02/19/crews-of-rage-sea-of-thieves-free-update-released/|title=The latest free update to Sea of Thieves is Crews of Rage|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|work=[[VG 247]]|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Heart of Fire''\n| 11 March 2020\n| ''Heart of Fire'' introduced the chain-shot and the blunderbomb, a throwable explosive, and included more Tall Tales missions which continue the story started in ''The Seabound Soul''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-03-04-sea-of-thieves-enters-the-trap-laden-heart-of-fire-in-next-weeks-big-update|title=Sea of Thieves enters the trap-laden Heart of Fire in next week's big update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=4 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' saw frequent collaborations with other Microsoft franchises. The Bird and Bear Figurehead, based on Rare's own ''[[Banjo-Kazooie (series)|Banjo-Kazooie]]'' series, was released in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/07/05/sea-of-thieves-new-item-is-a-lovely-banjo-kazooie-reference|title=Sea of Thieves: New Item Is a Lovely Banjo-Kazooie Reference|first=Alex|last=Gilyadov|work=[[IGN]]|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Ships based on the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' series and the ''[[Gears of War]]'' franchise were released in June and November 2019 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/10/halo-spartan-ship-set-announced-for-sea-of-thieves-e3-2019|title=Halo Spartan Ship Set Announced for Sea of Thieves - E3 2019|first=Colin|last=Stevens|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-is-giving-away-a-gears-of-war-inspired-ship-set-for-a-week/|title=Sea of Thieves is giving away a Gears of War-inspired ship set for a week|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also expanded ''Sea of Thieves'' to other media. It had partnered with [[Mongoose Publishing]] to release a [[tabletop role-playing game|tabletop]] game titled ''Sea of Thieves Roleplaying Game'' in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-31-theres-a-sea-of-thieves-tabletop-rpg-on-the-way|title=There's a Sea of Thieves tabletop RPG on the way|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Comics]] debuted a comic series written by [[Jeremy Whitley]] in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-comic-series-announced-check-out-so/1100-6455724/|title=Sea Of Thieves Comic Series Announced, Check Out Some Art|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=18 December 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Books]] also worked with Rare to publish an art book named ''Tales from the Sea of Thieves''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/xbox/2018/3/20/17140292/sea-of-thieves-lore-artbook-preview-tales-from-the-sea-of-thieves-book|title=Tales From the Sea of Thieves is a deep dive into a pirate lore ocean|first=Susana|last=Polo|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 66/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><br>(XONE) 69/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 6.5/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web |last=Devore |first=Jordan |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sea-of-thieves-495603.phtml |title=Review: Sea of Thieves |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| EuroG = Recommended<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-27-sea-of-thieves-review|title=Sea of Thieves review|first=Christian|last=Donlan|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite web |last=Hilliard |first=Kyle |date=23 March 2018 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sea_of_thieves/b/xboxone/archive/2018/03/23/game-informer-sea-of-thieves-xbox-one-review.aspx |title=Fun In A Shallow Pool - Sea of Thieves - Xbox One |work=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web |last=Tamburro |first=Paul |date=26 March 2018 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/377727-sea-of-thieves-review-rarely-exciting-xbox-one |title=Sea of Thieves Review \u2013 Rarely Exciting (Xbox One) |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref name=\"GSpotRev\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=27 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sea-of-thieves-review-set-sail-with-trepidation/1900-6416887/ |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web |last=Loveridge |first=Sam |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review: Doesn\u2019t have the (sea)legs for longevity |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10 (2020)<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Jagneaux|first=David |date= 20 March 2020 |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-review-2020 |title=Sea of Thieves Review (2020) |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate= 25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Poly = 6.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=Frushtick |first=Russ |date=22 March 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17151248/sea-of-thieves-review-xbox-one-pc |title=Sea of Thieves review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 72/100<ref name=\"PCGRev\">{{cite magazine |last=Wilde |first=Tyler |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-pc-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' received \"mixed or average\" reviews from critics according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/> Most critics agreed that the game has potential to be great but lamented that the game suffered from a lack of content and doubted Rare's decision to release it as a full-priced product.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"DestructRev\"/><ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> The game's graphics and the [[game physics]] also received acclaim.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"PCGRev\"/>\n\nThe multiplayer portion of the game was well-received. Jordan Devore from ''[[Destructoid]]'' noted that with a full crew, the game could get chaotic and situations could turn volatile very quickly. He added that cooperation with strangers could create unforgettable experiences for players which could be deeply satisfying.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Peter Brown from ''[[GameSpot]]'' also enjoyed coordinating with other players and goofing around, though he remarked that some players were [[trolling]] others which caused the experience to be frustrating.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Jeff Grubb from ''[[VentureBeat]]'' also enjoyed the game, saying that playing with strangers often created numerous hilarious moments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/03/20/sea-of-thieves-is-mesmerizing-and-hilarious/|title=Sea of Thieves is mesmerizing and hilarious|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Kyle Hilliard from ''[[Game Informer]]'' stated that each session \"results in a story\" due to the emergent gameplay, and praised Rare for successfully creating an excellent \"pirate simulator\" and \"manufacturing a digital playground that is fun to explore\".<ref name=\"GIRev\"/>  Sam Loveridge from ''[[GamesRadar]]'' likewise commented that the game is \"an anecdote generator at its very best\" due to its emergent storytelling.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Brandin Tyrrel from ''[[IGN]]'' stated that \"''Sea of Thieves'' works well when treated like a [[chat room]] or a [[party game]], where it serves as catalyst for having a good time with the people you\u2019re with\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Tyrell |first=Brandin |date=27 March 2018 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/28/sea-of-thieves-review |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay received generally negative reviews. Devore felt that the quests were repetitive and that the world did not have a lot of interesting things to do.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Paul Tamburro from ''[[Game Revolution]]'' agreed, remarking that the quests had little variety and did not allow room for creativity. While he praised the [[sandbox game|sandbox]] format, he felt that there were not enough secrets or stories players could discover in the world.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/> Loverdige called the voyages \"elaborated [[fetch quest]]s\". He lamented that there was no option to turn off PvP and players could not customize their own characters.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Russ Frushtick from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' remarked that misbehaving players may make the experience frustrating because PvP could never be disabled. However, he remarked that the game offered no incentive for players who wanted to engage in PvP combat.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Hilliard felt that the game did not have enough content to keep players engaged, and remarked that the combat felt bland. Many critics commented that players would not be motivated to complete quests because only cosmetic items are unlocked.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/><ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/> Tyrrel praised the ship combat, though he felt that the respawn system was too forgiving.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Christian Donlan from ''[[Eurogamer]]'' likewise called the ship combat \"thrilling\" and the general combat \"crunchy, pleasantly basic\".<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Tyler Wilde from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' liked exploring the shipwrecks, believing that exploration evokes a sense of discovery, though he commented that he wished more emergent events would happen in the ocean.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Solo play received mixed opinions. Some critics thought that it was more difficult,<ref name=\"polysolo\"/> boring,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-is-no-fun-by-yourself-1823934837|title=Sea Of Thieves Is No Fun By Yourself|first=Mike|last=Fahey|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and maddening,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/03/21/sea-of-thieves-solo-play/|title=Sea of Thieves solo is maddening and brutal - as it should be|first=Alec|last=Meer|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while some remarked that it was entertaining,<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> satisfying,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\"/> and relaxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-01-why-i-love-sailing-alone-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Why I love sailing alone in Sea of Thieves|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"polysolo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17150830/playing-sea-of-thieves-solo-experience|title=The case for sailing solo in Sea of Thieves|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year of updates, the game received more positive reviews from critics. Following the ''Anniversary'' update, ''IGN'' stated that players should give the game a second chance and that it was the \"perfect time\" to return to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/why-now-is-a-great-time-to-return-to-sea-of-thieves|title=Why Now Is a Great Time to Return to Sea of Thieves|first=Mark|last=Merlinda|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> One of its writers, David Jagneaux, praised the Tall Tales and its riddles in his second review, which he described as \"brain teasers that really challenge [player's] detective skills\".<ref name = \"IGN\"/> In his summary, he wrote that the game is a \"pirate fantasy sandbox with an enormous amount of things to do, made unpredictable and exciting by the addition of other players\".<ref name = \"IGN\"/> Nicole Carpenter from ''Polygon'' praised the post-launch updates for making the title more \"curated\" with more structure and direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' named ''Sea of Thieves'' the Best Ongoing Game of 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/best-ongoing-game-2019-sea-of-thieves/|title=Best Ongoing Game 2019: Sea of Thieves|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while ''[[Gameindustry.biz]]'' declared the title one of their [[Game of the Year|Games of the Year]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-12-15-game-of-the-year-2019-sea-of-thieves|title=Games of the Year 2019: Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Sea of Thieves'' is a commercial success. The title attracted more than 1 million players two days after it released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-seeing-unprecedented-demand-passes-/1100-6457743/|title=Sea Of Thieves Seeing \"Unprecedented\" Demand, Passes 1 Million Players|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> It was the best-selling retail game in the UK in its week of release<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-26-sea-of-thieves-lands-uk-chart-number-one|title=Sea of Thieves lands UK chart number one|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and it became the second best-selling game in the US in March 2018 behind ''[[Far Cry 5]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/far-cry-5-sea-of-thieves-march-npd/|title=Far Cry 5 and Sea of Thieves best-selling games in US during March, according to NPD|first=James|last=Billcliffe|work=[[VG 247]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 28 March 2018, Microsoft declared the game as the fast-selling new IP released for the Xbox One.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-microsofts-fastest-selling-new-i/1100-6457750/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Microsoft's Fastest-Selling New IP On Xbox One|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-11-quantum-break-uks-best-selling-boxed-game |title=Quantum Break UK's best-selling boxed game |first=Wesley |last=Yin-Poole |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=11 April 2016 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> Rare attributed the game's success to the title releasing for Xbox Game Pass subscribers at launch, which enabled the game to achieved Rare's sales target for three months in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-06-18-sea-of-thieves-hit-three-month-target-in-a-single-day|title=Sea of Thieves hit three month target in a single day|first=Matthew|last= Handrahan|work=[[Gameindustry.biz]]|date=18 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Game Pass contributed to half of the game's sales,<ref name=\"second launch\"/> though Microsoft added that the game also sold well in both retail and digital formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/315909/Microsoft_says_Sea_of_Thieves_sold_well_even_without_counting_Game_Pass_copies.php|title=Microsoft says Sea of Thieves sold well, even without counting Game Pass copies|first=Alissa|last=McAloon|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game passed five million players in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-08-01-sea-of-thieves-sloops-past-5m-players|title=Sea of Thieves passes 5m players|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, Rare declared the game was \"the most successful IP [Microsoft has] released in the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|generation]]\", with it amassing more than 10 million players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-now-xboxs-most-successful-new-ip/1100-6472598/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Now Xbox's \"Most Successful\" New IP Of The Generation|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In addition to good sales, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also popular with viewers, with the title being ranked as one of the most watched titles on Twitch in January 2019 following the ''Shrouded Spoils'' update.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-has-unexpectedly-become-one-of-twitchs-b-1831997645|title=Sea Of Thieves Has Unexpectedly Become One Of Twitch's Biggest Games|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=23 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/1/22/18193421/sea-of-thieves-twitch-ninja-dr-disrespect-summit1g|title=Sea of Thieves is enjoying a resurgence on Twitch|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2016\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best of Show\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2016nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2016 (2016 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Gamescom]] 2016\n| Best Xbox One Game\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamelibrarian.com/best-of-gamescom-2016-winners-selected-by-gamescom-committee/|title=Best of Gamescom 2016 Winners Selected by Gamescom Committee|publisher=The Video Game Librarian|date=19 August 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Online Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2016 voting now open to the public|website=[[Digital Spy]]|author=Sam Loveridge|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Game Critics Awards\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2017nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2017 (2017 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Golden Joystick Awards\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2017 Nominees|publisher=Best in Slot|first=Eri|last=Gaito|date=13 November 2017|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"16\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Develop (magazine)|Develop Awards]]\n| Animation\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/announcing-the-develop-awards-2018-nominations-shortlist|title=Announcing the Develop Awards 2018 nominations shortlist|magazine=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]|author=MCV staff|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Visual Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Music Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Sound Design \n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Gameplay Innovation\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[The Independent Game Developers' Association]] Awards 2018\n| Best Action and Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/tiga-announces-games-industry-awards-2018-finalists|title=TIGA Announces Games Industry Awards 2018 Finalists|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|author=Suzi Stephenson|date=19 September 2018|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/awards/2018-winners|title=2018 Winners|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|date=1 November 2018|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Creativity Award\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Visual Design\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/news/golden-joysticks-2018-nominees-announced-voting-open-now/|title=Golden Joysticks 2018 nominees announced, voting open now|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Tom Hoggins|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/golden-joystick-awards-2018-winners/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2018 winners: God of War wins big but Fortnite gets Victory Royale|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|author=Connor Sheridan|date=16 November 2018|accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Co-operative Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Xbox Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2018]]\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/game-awards-tga/2018/12/6/18130000/the-game-awards-winners-2018|title=The Game Awards 2018: Here are all the winners|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|author=Christopher Grant|date=6 December 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]]\n| Best Artistic Design\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|title=Titanium Awards 2018|website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]]|accessdate=7 November 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707230958/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|archivedate=7 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-10-red-dead-redemption-2-wins-best-game-at-fun-and-serious-festival-awards|title=Red Dead Redemption 2 wins Best Game at Fun & Serious Festival Awards|website=GamesIndustry.biz|author=Matthew Handrahan|date=10 December 2018|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Family Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Australian Games Awards\n| Multiplayer/Online Title of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.australiangamesawards.com/news/|title=Your 2018 Winners|publisher=Australian Games Awards|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"9\" | 2019\n| [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Online Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/god-of-war-spider-man-lead-dice-awards-heres-all-t/1100-6464345/|title=God Of War, Spider-Man Lead DICE Awards; Here's All The Nominees|website=[[GameSpot]]|author=Eddie Makuch|date=10 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Design, New IP\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3566/|title=Nominee List for 2018|publisher=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]|date=11 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Game, Original Action\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[15th British Academy Games Awards]]\n| Evolving Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/gaming/news/british-academy-games-awards-2019-nominees-1203163369/|title=\u2018God of War,\u2019 \u2018Red Dead 2\u2019 Lead BAFTA Game Awards Nominations|author=Stefanie Fogel|date=14 March 2019|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Italian Video Game Awards\n| Innovation Award\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://italianvideogameawards.com/awards|title=Italian Video Game Awards Nominees and Winners|website=Italian Video Game Awards|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ivor Novello Awards]]\n| Best Original Video Game Score\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8513011/2019-ivor-novello-awards-winners-list|title=Mariah Carey and The 1975 Win 2019 Ivor Novello Awards|author=Gil Kaufman|date=24 May 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| The Independent Game Developers' Association Awards 2019\n| Best Social Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/tiga-announces-games-industry-awards-2019-finalists|title=TIGA Announces Games Industry Awards 2019 Finalists|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|author=Suzi Stephenson|date=19 September 2019|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Game Expansion (''Anniversary Update'')\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards|author=Stephen Tailby|date=20 September 2019|website=Push Square|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seaofthieves.com/}}\n\n{{Rare}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kraken in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer vehicle operation games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Persistent worlds]]\n[[Category:Rare (company) games]]\n[[Category:Unreal Engine games]]\n[[Category:Video games about pirates]]\n[[Category:Video games with downloadable content]]\n[[Category:Video games with cross-platform play]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Robin Beanland]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring protagonists of selectable gender]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox Play Anywhere games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 action-adventure game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sea of Thieves\n| image =Sea of thieves cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Rare (company)|Rare]]\n| publisher = [[Microsoft Studios]]\n| director = [[Gregg Mayles]]\n| producer =  Joe Neate\n| designer = Mike Chapman\n| programmer = Peter Campbell\n| artist = Ryan Stevenson\n| writer = {{ubl|Chris Allcock|Mike Chapman}}\n| composer = [[Robin Beanland]]\n| engine = [[Unreal Engine 4]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released = 20 March 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Sea of Thieves''''' is a 2018 [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[Rare (company)|Rare]] and published by [[Microsoft Studios]]. The player assumes the role of a pirate who completes voyages from different trading companies to become the ultimate pirate legend. ''Sea of Thieves'' is a [[first-person perspective|first-person]] [[cooperative gameplay|multiplayer]] game in which a group of players [[cooperative gameplay|cooperates]] with each other to explore an [[open world]] via a pirate ship. The game is described as a \"shared world adventure game\", which means groups of players will encounter each other regularly during their adventures.\n\nMost of Rare's employees worked on the title and the game was first conceptualized in 2014. The game was inspired by players of [[personal computer|PC]] games such as ''[[Eve Online]]'', ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'', who used the tools provided by these games to create their own personal stories. The company explored different settings for the game, such as vampires and dinosaurs, though it eventually settled on the pirate theme, drawing inspirations from films including ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[The Goonies]]''. The game features a progression system that only unlocks cosmetic items as the development team wanted to encourage both casual and experienced players to play together. Compared to Rare's other games, ''Sea of Thieves''{{'s}} development process was more transparent, with Rare inviting fans to test the game's early builds.\n\nMicrosoft released the game in March 2018 for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] and [[Xbox One]]; it was also one of the earliest [[first-party]] games released for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers. The game received generally mixed reviews upon release, with critics praising the game's ship combat, multiplayer gameplay, visuals, and game physics. Criticisms were directed at the game's lack of content, progression, and shallow gameplay. Rare envisioned the title as a \"[[game as a service]]\" and released numerous content updates after the game's release. The game is a commercial success and has attracted more than 10 million players as of January 2020. Microsoft declared the game the most successful new [[intellectual property]] (IP) they have released in the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|generation]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Sea of Thieves gameplay screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|In this gameplay screenshot, the player is firing cannonballs at a hostile pirate ship, which is controlled by another group of players.]]\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' is a [[first-person (video games)|first-person]] [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game. At the beginning of the game, the player selects their [[procedurally generated]] player avatar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kg5ny/rare-give-me-a-little-control-in-making-my-sea-of-thieves-character|title=Rare, Give Me a Little Control in Making My 'Sea of Thieves' Character|first=Austin|last=Walker|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The game is set in a shared world, which means groups of players will encounter each other throughout their adventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jun/22/sea-of-thieves-pirate-adventure-rare-game-developer|title=Sea of Thieves \u2013 the pirate adventure that heralds the return of Rare|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Solo players pilot a [[sloop]] while players playing in a group control a [[galleon]] cooperatively by assuming different roles such as steering the ship, hoisting sails, navigating using the [[compass]], managing the [[anchor]], and [[navigation|scouting]] from the [[crow's nest]].<ref name=\"sailing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-sailing-terms-sail-into-the-wind-ship-combat-5001|title=Sea of Thieves sailing - how to sail into the wind, win ship combat and sailing terms explained|first=Chris|last=Tapsail|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17144806/ships-sloop-galleon-map-barrels-canonballs-bananas-planks-chests-ammo-clothing-vanity-equipment|title=Sea of Thieves ships guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Occasionally players may encounter hostile players who may attack them with [[cannonball]]s or [[Naval boarding|board]] their ship.<ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/116340/7-more-things-we-want-in-sea-of-thieves|title=7 more things we want in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If areas under the deck take damage, water will flow in and cause the ship to gradually sink. Players need to patch up the holes with [[Plank (wood)|plank]]s of wood and bail out water using buckets.<ref name=\"sailing\"/> [[Alliance]]s can be established with other parties of players. They will receive [[gold]] bonuses when a group in the same alliance completes a voyage. Forming an alliance does not prevent players from attacking each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/106528/how-to-form-an-alliance-in-sea-of-thieves|title=How to form an alliance in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=3 August 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If the player dies, they are sent to a [[ghost ship]] known as the Ferry of the Damned where they wait until they can [[respawn]].<ref name=\"25 tips\"/> A competitive multiplayer mode named \"Arena\" was introduced in the ''Anniversary'' update; it allows four teams of players to compete against each other by gathering silver in smaller maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-new-arena-mode-is-all-the-good-and-bad-1834515034|title=Sea of Thieves New Arena Mode Is All The Good (And Bad) Of Sea of Thieves|first=Heather|last=Alexander|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can complete [[quest|voyage]]s offered by the game's three [[clan (video games)|faction]]s: Gold Hoarders, Order of Souls, and the Merchant Alliance. In the quests offered by Gold Hoarders, players are given a [[treasure map]] or a riddle to locate the treasure. The voyages offered by the Order of Souls are mainly combat challenges.  Merchant Alliance's missions demand players to deliver goods such as live animals to vendors within a limited time.<ref name=\"factions\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17142984/quest-voyage-rank-map-gold-hoarders-order-of-souls-merchant-alliance-rank|title=Sea of Thieves guide to quests and voyages|first=Russ|last=Frushtick|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> When players collect a treasure chest, they need to deliver them to the representatives of the quest-giving faction, though the one holding the chest are defenseless and may have it be taken by other players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-guide-voyages-quests-factions-kraken-skeleton-forts/|title=Sea of Thieves beginner's guide: voyages, factions, and making money|first=Tyler|last=Wilde|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing voyages earns players [[gold]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-how-to-get-started-in-sea-of-thieves-how-to-start-your-first-voyage-controls-explained|title=How to get Started in Sea of Thieves - How to Begin Your First Voyage - Step by Step Guide to Setting Sail, Controls Explained|first=Tom|last=Orry|work=[[USgamer]]|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> which can be spent on buying new customization items or enhancements from merchants, [[bladesmith|weaponsmith]]s, and [[shipbuilding|shipwright]]s.<ref name=\"shops\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143940/shop-vendor-clothing-equipment-weaponsmith-shipwright-trading-companies|title=Sea of Thieves shop guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Items such as [[pet]]s can also be purchased using [[microtransaction|real-world currency]] by accessing the Pirate Emporium store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/09/14/sea-of-thieves-microtransactions/|title=Sea Of Thieves gets a microtransaction store|first=Emily|last=Gera|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=14 September 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> [[Doubloon]]s, earned through completing commendations from the Blige Rats, the fourth trading company that distributes quests, challenges, and cosmetics added to the game via post-launch updates, can be traded for gold or reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/sea-of-thieves-guide/2019/5/24/18629418/events-gold-doubloons-bilge-rats-duke-cosmetics|title=Sea of Thieves events and doubloons guide|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ''Anniversary'' update adds Tall Tales, which are a series of structured narrative missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/13/18617975/sea-of-thieves-tall-tales-review-story-mode-characters|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Tall Tales is the star feature of the anniversary update|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing quests also earns the player reputation points, which unlock more complicated quests from each faction and additional purchasable items.<ref name=\"factions\"/><ref name=\"shops\"/> When players reach rank 50 with all the factions and solve all the riddles, they become a \"pirate legend\", a status which grants players new cosmetic items and access to a pirate hideout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-pirate-legend-mysterious-stranger-riddle-solution-rewards-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Pirate Legend and Mysterious Stranger explained - riddle solution, rewards, and how to become Pirate Legend|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can freely explore the game's [[open world]] on their own or with other players.<ref name=\"exploration\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/13/17003856/sea-of-thieves-game-preview|title=Sea of Thieves is huge, fun, and just what the Xbox One needs|first=Tom|last=Warren|work=[[The Verge]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-island-map-locations-shapes-names-5001|title=Sea of Thieves map - Island locations, names, shapes and how to find every island|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> When exploring a new location, players can retrieve items such as [[banana]]s, which restore their [[health (game terminology)|health]], wood planks, and cannonballs. [[Ammo]] can be resupplied using the ammo chest in the Captain's Quarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/03/09/sea-of-thieves-open-beta-tips-guide-treasure/|title=Sea of Thieves open beta tips: sailing, treasure, combat and the puke bucket weapon|first=Matt|last=Martin|work=[[VG 247]]|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Weapons including [[cutlass]]es, [[pistol]]s, [[blunderbuss]]es, and [[sniper rifle]]s can be used to defeat hostile enemies like [[skeleton]]s.<ref name=\"25 tips\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-tips/|title=25 essential Sea of Thieves tips to know before you play|first=Sam|last=Loveridge|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\"/> When players are sailing the sea, they may sometimes face adverse weather conditions such as thunderstorms<ref name=\"sailing\"/> or encounter shipwrecks, messages in bottles, and monsters such as the [[megalodon]] and the [[kraken]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/sea-of-thieves-shrouded-spoils-release-date|title=You\u2019ll finally get rewards for killing giant monsters in today\u2019s Sea of Thieves expansion|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"exploration\"/> Skull clouds indicate the locations of Skeleton Forts, which are [[Raid (military)|raid]]s that can be completed by players in the same server.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-skeleton-forts-skull-clouds-stronghold-keys-fort-assaults-explained-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Skeleton Forts - Skull Clouds, Stronghold Keys and how to defeat the raids|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Players can interact with each other using [[emotes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/sea-of-thieves-to-get-pets-emotes-and-new-cosmetics-in-forthcoming-update|title=Sea of Thieves to get pets, emotes and new cosmetics in forthcoming update|first=Imogen|last=Donavan|work=VideoGamer|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> They can also play [[musical instrument]]s together and drink at [[tavern]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/banjo|title=Sea of Thieves is adding banjos to the musical mix|first=Ian|last=Boudrea|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-rare-is-already-immortalising-players-most-memorable-achievements-in-sea-of-thieves-world|title=Rare is already immortalising players' most memorable achievements in Sea of Thieves' world|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The ''Anniversary'' update allows players to engage in leisure activities like [[fishing]], hunting, and cooking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was developed by the UK-based developer [[Rare (company)|Rare]].  Almost all of Rare's 200 staff members worked on the game.<ref name=\"Watchable game\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-will-sea-of-thieves-resurrect-rare|title=Sea of Thieves and the Rare revival|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team began conceptualizing the game in 2014 and wanted to create a title where players can create stories together. The team took five months to create the game's playable prototype named ''Athena'' using the [[Unity (engine)|Unity]] [[game engine]].<ref name=\"no secret\"/> After playing the prototype, Microsoft's executives including [[Phil Spencer]] and Kudo Tsunoda agreed to [[green-light]] the game's development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/7-things-you-didnt-know-about-sea-of-thieves|title=7 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Sea of Thieves|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-09-sea-of-thieves-early-protoypes-looked-very-different|title=Sea of Thieves' early prototypes looked very different|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare employees also provided the voice for all of the [[non-player character|non-playable character]]s.<ref name=\"voice\"/> ''Sea of Thieves'' marked Rare's shift from using its own proprietary engine to using [[Unreal Engine 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2018-sea-of-thieves-tech-analysis|title=How Sea of Thieves' tech creates a unique gaming experience|first=John|last=Linneman|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=25 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRare was often considered to be a secretive studio. Since ''Sea of Thieves'' is a multiplayer-focused game, the studio adopted a more transparency approach to the game's development to ensure that the game's content would resonate with players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/sea-of-thieves-rare-developer-interview-how-players-are-helping-with-design|title=Sea of Thieves is using a unique dev tool: you|first=Stephen|last=Farrelly|work=[[Red Bull]]|date=9 November 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"no secret\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/11/17/how-rare-cast-away-its-developmental-process-for-sea-of-thieves.aspx|title=How Rare Cast Away Its Developmental Process For Sea Of Thieves|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> The team allowed fans to take part in the game's development by joining the Insider's Program, which granted players access to an early build of the game. The program allowed Rare to experiment with different features while collecting players' feedback. The participants could also discuss with the developers in a private forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-22-sea-of-thieves-insider-programme-offers-chance-at-testing-early-builds|title=Sea of Thieves Insider Programme offers chance at testing early builds|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> More than 30,000 players joined the program.<ref name=\"art\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/06/21/how-microsofts-rare-imagined-the-pirate-world-of-sea-of-thieves/|title=How Microsoft\u2019s Rare imagined the pirate world of Sea of Thieves|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Through the program, Rare learnt more about how players interact with each other and used the information to help the team make gameplay decisions;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/sea-thieves-interview-rare-studio-head-craig-duncan-bold-new/|title=Sea of Thieves interview: Rare studio head Craig Duncan on a bold new direction for the legendary British developer |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> for instance, the team decided to include solo play after many players from the Insider's Program requested it.<ref name=\"solo play\"/>\n\n===Influences and setting===\n{{quotebox|quote=\"I love the idea of things happening in the world that literally can shape the ongoing fabric and lore of ''Sea of Thieves''. The [[Black Beard]] of ''Sea of Thieves'' being a real player in a real crew with a real name - that's really hard to do if you've already painted everyone down a path you want them to go through\"|source= \u2014 Joe Neate, executive producer of Rare<ref name=\"friendliest\"/>|width=33%}}\nStudio director Craig Duncan described ''Sea of Thieves'' as the \"friendliest\" multiplayer game.<ref name=\"friendliest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-13-the-sea-of-thieves-endgame-sounds-super-cool|title=The Sea of Thieves endgame sounds super cool|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> While Rare is traditionally a console game developer, it realized how players from [[personal computer|PC]] [[survival game]]s like ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'', and [[simulation video game|simulation game]]s such as ''[[Eve Online]]'' crafted their own stories by using the tools provided in the game. However, Rare remarked that these games are often very punishing in nature, and the team aspired to create a more light-hearted and accessible version of these games.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/sea-of-thieves-return-to-form-for-rare-studi/|title=Who cares about loot? For \u2018Sea of Thieves,\u2019 Rare hid the real fun in the hijinks|first=Will|last=Fulton|work=Digital Trends|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Sea of Thieves'' was designed to be a \"light canvass of a world\" where players create their own stories.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> The game did not feature any narrative component at launch because the team felt that by offering players a structured narrative, they would only be playing an experience that was handcrafted for them. Joe Neate, the game's executive director, described the game as an \"improv\" comedy, and added that the game is about going \"off-script\".<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> Rare shaped the world and the game's lore to reflect players' actions, including various [[Easter egg (media)|easter egg]]s to celebrate their actions or achievements. The team believed that if a narrative campaign is included, incorporating players' actions into the game's lore would become difficult.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/>\n\nThe company explored different settings for the game, such as [[vampire]]s and [[dinosaur]]s, though it eventually settled on the [[piracy|pirate]] theme because it matched the game's core concept which encourages cooperation. Rare also saw less competition in the market.{{efn|Duncan elaborated that the team was thankful that they did not chose dinosaur as the setting due to the release of ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]'' (2017)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/19/rare-considered-vampire-dinosaur-themes-for-sea-of-thieves-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Considered Vampire, Dinosaur Themes for Sea of Thieves \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The pirate theme allows players to have the freedom to do what they want in the game's world and decide freely how they want to play and behave. The team looked at various sources for inspiration, including ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[Black Sails (TV series)|Black Sails]]''. Designer Mike Chapman believed a lot of parallels can be drawn between ''Sea of Thieves'' and ''[[The Goonies]]'', in which a group of friends bond together while they search for treasure, creating a journey that all of them would fondly remember.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Neate added that the game's goal was to evoke \"[a] sense of travel and exploration and discovery\".<ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/22/17971710/sea-of-thieves-lore-forsaken-shores-cursed-sails-worldbuilding|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 lore is surprisingly deep, silly and refreshing|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team implemented the \"infinite pirate generator\" instead of allowing players to customize their avatar as they feared that some players would create \"abominations\" that would not have fit the game's visual style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/317084/How_Rare_designed_Sea_of_Thieves_infinite_pirate_generator.php|title=How Rare designed Sea of Thieves' infinite pirate generator|first=Jack|last=Yarwood|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=27 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game features a stylized visual style with hand-painted textures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gdcvault.com/play/1025015/Visual-Adventures-on-Sea-of|title=Visual Adventures on 'Sea of Thieves'|work=GDC Vault|first=Ryan|last=Stevenson|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Duncan added that the team chose this painted art style because they wanted it to be \"timeless\" and reflect the  \"joyful\" and \"delightful\" game world.<ref name=\"art\"/>\n\n===Gameplay design===\n\nRare noticed that in many multiplayer games, experienced players would focus on grinding for endgame content instead of playing with other players, while novice players would worry about their progression lagging significantly behind more experienced players. Therefore, the team introduced \"horizontal progression\", in which players would only earn cosmetic items as they achieve a higher rank; all items have the same attributes, so endgame content would not confer gameplay bonuses to experienced players. This progression system encourages more experienced players to assist novice players when they are completing voyages, and reduce the gap between the two experience levels.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-has-fully-embraced-power-levelling-according-to-the-design-director-its-not-what-you-think/|title=Sea of Thieves 'fully embraces' power levelling, according to the design director (it's not what you think)|first=Connor|last=Sheridan|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> As a \"shared world\" adventure game, Rare opted to maintain the distance between each player group in a server rather than limiting the number of players a server can accommodate, so that players get to encounter other players regularly but not too frequently.{{efn|Chapman estimated that a player will see another player-controlled ships every 15 minutes to half an hour.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-doesnt-have-a-maximum-or-minimum-server-size|title=Sea of Thieves Has a Very Smart Approach to Server Size|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay was designed to test the player's [[soft skills]]. Players need to exercise their [[common sense]] in order to solve the challenges: for instance, players need to learn to read maps. To encourage players to develop these skills, the game does not feature a beginner's [[tutorial]] as the team wanted players to discover the game's mechanics by themselves.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> The team also intentionally avoided setting gameplay rules to encourage players to utilize their creativity.<ref name=\"solo play\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/when-we-made-sea-of-thieves/|title=When We Made\u2026 Sea of Thieves|first=Marie|last=Dealessandri|work=[[MCVUK]]|date=20 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Despite this, Rare also included [[emergent gameplay]] in a more systemic manner by introducing shipwrecks and fonts that players can discover. Chapman described these locations of interest as the \"catalyst for stories\" which draw different players together, fostering cooperation or competition. Being attacked by [[sea monster]]s also add a layer of unpredictability to the game as these encounters are random.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Due to the emergent gameplay, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also considered as a \"watachable and sharable game\", and the team hoped that this will lure players who watched the game on [[video game live streaming]] platforms such as [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] or [[Mixer (service)|Mixer]] to purchase it.<ref name=\"Watchable game\"/>\n\nWhile the game allows solo play, the game is designed to be a multiplayer game in which players cooperate with each other. Chapman added that [[cooperative gameplay]] enhances the experience because \"it makes sense in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/06/14/sea-of-thieves-lets-you-captain-your-pirate-ship-solo-but-at-a-cost/|title=Sea of Thieves lets you captain your pirate ship solo \u2014 but at a cost|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=14 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game does not feature any [[character class]] or specialization to encourage players to adopt different roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-01-10-sea-of-thieves-devs-explain-how-its-design-encourages-cooperation|title=Sea of Thieves devs explain how its design encourages cooperation|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The maximum crew size is four as Rare felt that if the group is too large, it does not reflect a sense of \"intimate friendship\" and players may splinter off and hinder inter-player communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-dev-explains-why-the-maximum-crew-size-is-4-players|title=Sea of Thieves Dev Explains Why the Maximum Crew Size Is 4 Players|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Neate described the game as a \"friendship creation tool\" and hoped that the game could become a platform where players can befriend strangers.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> Rare further added that they felt they have the responsibility to create a \"positive online social space\".<ref name=\"online space\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rare-on-sea-of-thieves-online-we-have-a-responsibility-as-game-creators-to-make-a-positive-social-space/|title=Rare on Sea of Thieves: 'We have a responsibility to make a positive online social space'|first=Joe|last=Donnelly|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Design changes were made to champion the concept of cooperation and friendship. For instance, players cannot hurt others in the same crew,<ref name=\"online space\"/> and all rewards are shared equally among crew members.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> In one of the game's early prototypes, players in the same crew can betray each other, though the feature was scrapped because the team felt that the experience was \"horrible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/275112/How_emotional_psychology_and_The_Goonies_inspired_Sea_of_Thieves.php?|title=How emotional psychology and The Goonies inspired Sea of Thieves|first=Kris|last=Graft|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=16 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Neate added that the game provided \"literally no reason or motivation to do anything other that cooperate\".<ref name=\"online space\"/> Rare incorporated several anti-toxicity measures. For instance, players can vote to lock a disruptive player into a [[jail cell|brig]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17153164/sea-of-thieves-toxic-brig-scuttle-ship-code-of-conduct|title=Sea of Thieves team put anti-toxicity strategies into game\u2019s core design|first=Julia|last=Alexander|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was announced by publisher [[Xbox Game Studios|Microsoft Studios]] during its press conference at [[E3 2015]], with Duncan describing the game as the \"most ambitious project\" from Rare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/rare-announces-most-ambitious-project-yet-sea-of-thieves-294014.phtml|title=Rare announces 'most ambitious project yet,' Sea of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=MacGregor Burleson|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=15 June 2015|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Initially set to be released in 2017, the game was delayed to early 2018 to allow additional development time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2017-sea-of-thieves-delayed-until-2018/1100-6450690/|title=E3 2017: Sea Of Thieves Delayed Until 2018|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft marketed the game extensively. Players who pre-ordered the game received the Black Dog Pack, which included exclusive cosmetic content and access to a closed [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]]. Players could also purchase a separate ''Sea of Thieves''-themed Xbox [[wireless controller]], and anyone who purchased the [[Xbox One X]] console from 18 to 24 March would receive a free digital copy of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/you-can-still-buy-an-xbox-one-x-and-get-sea-of-thi/1100-6457467/|title=You Can Still Buy An Xbox One X And Get Sea Of Thieves Free For A Limited Time|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/17/a-complete-guide-to-sea-of-thievess-preorder-bonuses|title=A Complete Guide to Sea of Thieves' Preorder Bonuses|first=Chris|last=Reed|work=[[IGN]]|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft's Australian branch partnered with music band Captain Hellfire & The Wretched Brethren for a two-day event in which the pirate band sang different [[sea shanty|sea shanties]] requested by players. The program was broadcast via [[Facebook]], Mixer, and Twitch from 24 to 25 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/xbox-partners-with-an-australian-pirate-band-for-a/1100-6457517/|title=Xbox Partners With An Australian Pirate Band For A Cool Sea Of Thieves Promo|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft also launched \"The Quest\", an [[alternative reality game]] where players needed to solve different riddles. The winners would receive one of four golden bananas (each valued at \u00a320,000) as rewards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/10/sea-of-thieves-global-digital-treasure-hunt-features-golden-banana-prize|title=Sea of Thieves Global Digital Treasure Hunt Features Golden Banana Prize|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also hosted a competition which tasked fans to create [[Achievement (video games)|achievement]]s for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-01-24-can-you-come-up-with-a-sea-of-thieves-achievement|title=Can you come up with a Sea of Thieves Achievement?|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Several [[stress testing (software)|stress test]]s and betas were released ahead of the game's official launch on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-09-sea-of-thieves-final-beta-is-here-open-to-everyone-on-xbox-one-and-pc|title=Sea of Thieves' Final Beta is here, open to everyone on Xbox One and PC|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/08/sea-of-thieves-release-date-announced|title=Sea of Thieves Release Date Announced|first=Lucy|last=O'Brien|work=[[IGN]]|date=8 December 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>  At launch, many players reported that they could not log into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-issue-status-cinnamonbeard-server-e/1100-6457547/|title=Sea Of Thieves Issue Status: CinnamonBeard Server Error, Not Getting Gold, More|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Duncan said that Rare underestimated the server capacity as the number of people logging in to play the game during the launch period was unexpectedly high. Various fixes have been released to improve the game's online infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-dev-details-how-itll-address-server/1100-6457590/|title=Sea Of Thieves Dev Details How It'll Address Server And Performance Issues|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=23 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a retail release, ''Sea of Thieves'' is an [[Xbox Play Anywhere]] title and the game was made available for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/sea-of-thieves-rare-xbox-one-microsoft|title=Sea of Thieves is Rare\u2019s riskiest voyage yet, but it\u2019s a huge success|first=Matt|last=Kamen|work=[[Wired.co.uk]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-17-these-are-the-first-xbox-play-anywhere-games|title=These are the first Xbox Play Anywhere games|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> However, [[cross-platform play|crossplay]] between PC and Xbox One players was made optional in February 2019 to ensure that all players feel that \"they have a level playing field\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-cross-play-will-be-made-optional-be/1100-6464703/|title=Sea Of Thieves Cross-Play Will Be Made Optional Between Xbox One And PC|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=4 February 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> On PC, the game was initially only available through Xbox Game Pass and [[Microsoft Store]] before Microsoft announced a release for [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-finally-coming-to-steam/1100-6475560/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Finally Coming To Steam|first=Steven|last=T. Wright|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> Players began to set rules, develop their own sets of challenges, and host their own events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/25/17258750/sea-of-thieves-community-rules-agreements-parley|title=Sea of Thieves fans are setting their own rules in the pirate sandbox|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-07-26-meet-the-pirate-who-created-a-racing-league-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Meet the pirate who created a racing league in Sea of Thieves|first=Imogen|last=Beckhelling|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> To further encourage these players, Rare announced plans to incorporate [[private server]]s into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-will-have-private-servers-to-support-creative-community-events/|title=Sea of Thieves will have private servers to support creative community events|first=Fraser|last=Brown|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Downloadable content===\nRare envisioned ''Sea of Thieves'' to be a \"[[games as a service|game as a service]]\" and expected it to continue receiving updates for 10 years.<ref name=\"updates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2018/feb/13/rare-sea-of-thieves-multiplayer-pirates|title=A pirate's life for me: Rare's ambitious plans for Sea of Thieves revealed|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-next-game-you-play-may-never-end/|title=The next big video game you play may never end|first=Ian|last=Sherr|work=[[CNET]]|date=17 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> After the team had fixed most of the technical issues, they began looking at players' feedback and identified that players were complaining that there were not enough activities for them to participate in. Chapman stated that the team's strategy was to give players what they want, ensure that they fit within the ''Sea of Thieves'' universe, and \"surprise\" players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rare-plans-to-give-sea-of-thieves-players-what-the/1100-6460067/|title=Rare Plans To Give Sea Of Thieves Players What They Want|first=Alexandro|last=Fillari|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare has four teams of employees working in parallel to create the game's various expansions so that large content update can be released frequently while ensuring that sufficient development time can be given to each team.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/05/01/sea-of-thieves-developer-rare-has-3-teams-making-major-updates/|title=Sea of Thieves developer Rare has 3 teams making major updates|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team hoped to a large content update every 6 weeks to 2 months, and used \"Bilge Rat Adventures\", which are time-limited challenges to fill the gap between each expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/interview/2018/07/04/rare-on-rpg-elements-battle-royale-potential-and-the-future-of-sea-of-thieves|title=Rare On RPG Elements, Battle Royale Potential, And The Future Of Sea Of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=Hilliard|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=4 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ultimate goal was to make the game \"as big and successful as it can be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/22/rare-studio-head-on-sea-of-thieves-post-launch-plans-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Studio Head on Sea of Thieves Post-Launch Plans \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The first major expansion, ''The Hungering Deep'', was developed within 2 months. The second expansion, ''Cursed Sails'', introduced skeleton ships controlled by [[artificial intelligence]] (AI). Despite being adamant about not doing so prior to the game's launch, the team decided to implement the feature as it was one of the biggest fan requests.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/> The ''Anniversary'' update that added both Tall Tales and Arena mode was so massive that it was described as a \"relaunch\" for the game.<ref name=\"second launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-04-10-the-second-launch-of-sea-of-thieves|title=The second launch of Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> All the expansions are free of charge as they did not want to divide the player base.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-08-06-keeping-sea-of-thieves-afloat|title=Keeping Sea of Thieves afloat|first=James|last=Batchelor|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=7 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Major expansion packs\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:16%;\"| Release date\n! style=\"width:70%;\"| Notes\n|-\n| ''The Hungering Deep''\n| 20 May 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-17-sea-of-thieves-first-proper-content-update-the-hungering-deep-gets-a-teaser-trailer|title=Sea of Thieves' first proper content update, The Hungering Deep, gets a teaser trailer|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| ''The Hungering Deep'' introduced new tools such as the Speaking Trumpet and a narrative campaign featuring the [[megalodon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-sea-of-thieves-hungering-deep-guide/megalodon-shark-guide|title=Sea of Thieves Megalodon Guide - How to Find the Megalogon, How to Defeat the Hungering One|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Cursed Sails''\n| 31 July 2018<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\"/>\n| ''Cursed Sails'' introduced AI ships, a new story campaign, the [[brigantine]] which can accommodate three players, and the \"alliance\" mechanic.<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-cursed-sails-update-now-live-4-things-you-need-to-know/|title=Sea of Thieves' Cursed Sails update now live - 4 things you need to know|first=Sam|last=Prell|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Forsaken Shores''\n| 27 September 2018\n| ''Forsaken Shores'' introduced new cosmetic items, a new volcanic region named Devil's Roar, a new type of voyage named \"Cargo Run\", a [[rowboat]], and a narrative campaign centered on Forsaken Shores Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-25-heres-everything-happening-in-this-weeks-sea-of-thieves-forsaken-shores-update|title=Here's everything happening in this week's Sea of Thieves Forsaken Shores update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Shrouded Spoils''\n| 28 November 2018\n| ''Shrouded Spoils'' introduced [[fog]] into the game, changed the AI behavior of both the kraken and the megalodon, and altered some of the existing gameplay systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-28-sea-of-thieves-big-shrouded-spoils-update-is-here-and-the-waters-never-been-deadlier|title=Sea of Thieves' big Shrouded Spoils update is here, and the water's never been deadlier|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Anniversary''\n| 30 April 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/111488/what-time-does-the-sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-start|title=What time does the Sea of Thieves Anniversary Update start?|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=30 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The ''Anniversary'' update introduced a separate player-versus-player (PvP) competitive multiplayer mode named ''Arena'', the first narrative-based Tall Tales campaign named ''Shores of Gold'' which consists of nine chapters, and the ''Hunter's Call'', which added fishing, cooking, and hunting into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update/|title=Sea of Thieves' anniversary update finally makes the game reach its full potential|first=Samuel|last=Roberts|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Black Powder Staches''\n| 17 July 2019\n| ''Black Power Staches'' includes a series of missions that task players to collect gunpowder barrels and then sold them to various factions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-black-powder-stashes-update-is-live/|title=Sea of Thieves' Black Powder Stashes update is live|first=Christopher|last=Livington|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Dark Relics''\n| 15 August 2019\n| ''Dark Relics'' introduces new voyages, cosmetic items, new commendations, and rowboats mounted with [[harpoon gun]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-dark-relics-update-is-here-with-new-voyages/|title=Sea of Thieves' Dark Relics update is here with new voyages|first=Jordan|last=Gerblick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=15 August 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Smuggler's Fortune''\n| 11 September 2019\n| The update adds the Pirate Emporium, a new store that supports [[microtransaction]]s. A new type of currency named \"Ancient Coins\" can be purchased from both the Xbox store and in-game. Players can also buy [[monkey]]s and [[parrot]]s as pets from the Pirate Emporium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/9/11/20860753/sea-of-thieves-smugglers-fortune-update-pets|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Smuggler\u2019s Fortune update is now live, and it adds pets|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Fort of the Damned''\n| 16 October 2019\n| ''Fort of the Damned'' introduced several [[Halloween]]-themed cosmetics, a new skeleton font, and a new type of enemy named Shadow Skeletons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-gets-spooky-with-new-fort-of-the-da/1100-6470608/|title=Sea Of Thieves Gets Spooky With New Fort Of The Damned Update|first=Jordan|last=Ramee|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=16 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''The Seabound Soul''\n| 20 November 2019\n| ''The Seabound Soul'' introduced fire into the game with the fiery cannonball and a new Tall Tale which has players partner with adventurer Sir Arthur Pendragon as they embark on a journey to seek a \"feared ship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-the-seabound-soul-update-now-live/1100-6471606/|title=Sea Of Thieves' The Seabound Soul Update Now Live|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Festival of Giving''\n| 11 December 2019\n| ''Festival of Giving'' introduced several [[Christmas]]-themed cosmetic items and a mission that tasks the players to assist Stitcher Jim to retrieve a shipment of gifts lost at sea. A new tutorial mode named Maiden Voyage was also added into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-holiday-event-adds-gift-seeker-voyages-and-tutorial-mode/|title=Sea of Thieves' holiday event adds Gift Seeker Voyages and tutorial mode|first=Jordan|last=Gerbick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Legends of the Sea''\n| 15 January 2020\n| ''Legends of the Sea'' celebrated the game's most notable players by tasking players to embark on a quest to seek various easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/legends-of-the-sea-release-date|title=Sea of Thieves: Legends of the Sea makes you part of the lore|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Crews of Rage''\n| 19 February 2020\n| ''Crews of Rage'' brought players back to Devil's Roar to complete Bounty Voyages, which involves acquiring a new chest known as the Chest of Rage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2020/02/19/crews-of-rage-sea-of-thieves-free-update-released/|title=The latest free update to Sea of Thieves is Crews of Rage|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|work=[[VG 247]]|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Heart of Fire''\n| 11 March 2020\n| ''Heart of Fire'' introduced the chain-shot and the blunderbomb, a throwable explosive, and included more Tall Tales missions which continue the story started in ''The Seabound Soul''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-03-04-sea-of-thieves-enters-the-trap-laden-heart-of-fire-in-next-weeks-big-update|title=Sea of Thieves enters the trap-laden Heart of Fire in next week's big update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=4 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' saw frequent collaborations with other Microsoft franchises. The Bird and Bear Figurehead, based on Rare's own ''[[Banjo-Kazooie (series)|Banjo-Kazooie]]'' series, was released in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/07/05/sea-of-thieves-new-item-is-a-lovely-banjo-kazooie-reference|title=Sea of Thieves: New Item Is a Lovely Banjo-Kazooie Reference|first=Alex|last=Gilyadov|work=[[IGN]]|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Ships based on the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' series and the ''[[Gears of War]]'' franchise were released in June and November 2019 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/10/halo-spartan-ship-set-announced-for-sea-of-thieves-e3-2019|title=Halo Spartan Ship Set Announced for Sea of Thieves - E3 2019|first=Colin|last=Stevens|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-is-giving-away-a-gears-of-war-inspired-ship-set-for-a-week/|title=Sea of Thieves is giving away a Gears of War-inspired ship set for a week|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also expanded ''Sea of Thieves'' to other media. It had partnered with [[Mongoose Publishing]] to release a [[tabletop role-playing game|tabletop]] game titled ''Sea of Thieves Roleplaying Game'' in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-31-theres-a-sea-of-thieves-tabletop-rpg-on-the-way|title=There's a Sea of Thieves tabletop RPG on the way|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Comics]] debuted a comic series written by [[Jeremy Whitley]] in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-comic-series-announced-check-out-so/1100-6455724/|title=Sea Of Thieves Comic Series Announced, Check Out Some Art|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=18 December 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Books]] also worked with Rare to publish an art book named ''Tales from the Sea of Thieves''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/xbox/2018/3/20/17140292/sea-of-thieves-lore-artbook-preview-tales-from-the-sea-of-thieves-book|title=Tales From the Sea of Thieves is a deep dive into a pirate lore ocean|first=Susana|last=Polo|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 66/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><br>(XONE) 69/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 6.5/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web |last=Devore |first=Jordan |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sea-of-thieves-495603.phtml |title=Review: Sea of Thieves |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| EuroG = Recommended<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-27-sea-of-thieves-review|title=Sea of Thieves review|first=Christian|last=Donlan|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite web |last=Hilliard |first=Kyle |date=23 March 2018 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sea_of_thieves/b/xboxone/archive/2018/03/23/game-informer-sea-of-thieves-xbox-one-review.aspx |title=Fun In A Shallow Pool - Sea of Thieves - Xbox One |work=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web |last=Tamburro |first=Paul |date=26 March 2018 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/377727-sea-of-thieves-review-rarely-exciting-xbox-one |title=Sea of Thieves Review \u2013 Rarely Exciting (Xbox One) |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref name=\"GSpotRev\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=27 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sea-of-thieves-review-set-sail-with-trepidation/1900-6416887/ |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web |last=Loveridge |first=Sam |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review: Doesn\u2019t have the (sea)legs for longevity |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10 (2020)<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Jagneaux|first=David |date= 20 March 2020 |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-review-2020 |title=Sea of Thieves Review (2020) |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate= 25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Poly = 6.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=Frushtick |first=Russ |date=22 March 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17151248/sea-of-thieves-review-xbox-one-pc |title=Sea of Thieves review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 72/100<ref name=\"PCGRev\">{{cite magazine |last=Wilde |first=Tyler |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-pc-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' received \"mixed or average\" reviews from critics according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/> Most critics agreed that the game has potential to be great but lamented that the game suffered from a lack of content and doubted Rare's decision to release it as a full-priced product.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"DestructRev\"/><ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> The game's graphics and the [[game physics]] also received acclaim.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"PCGRev\"/>\n\nThe multiplayer portion of the game was well-received. Jordan Devore from ''[[Destructoid]]'' noted that with a full crew, the game could get chaotic and situations could turn volatile very quickly. He added that cooperation with strangers could create unforgettable experiences for players which could be deeply satisfying.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Peter Brown from ''[[GameSpot]]'' also enjoyed coordinating with other players and goofing around, though he remarked that some players were [[trolling]] others which caused the experience to be frustrating.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Jeff Grubb from ''[[VentureBeat]]'' also enjoyed the game, saying that playing with strangers often created numerous hilarious moments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/03/20/sea-of-thieves-is-mesmerizing-and-hilarious/|title=Sea of Thieves is mesmerizing and hilarious|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Kyle Hilliard from ''[[Game Informer]]'' stated that each session \"results in a story\" due to the emergent gameplay, and praised Rare for successfully creating an excellent \"pirate simulator\" and \"manufacturing a digital playground that is fun to explore\".<ref name=\"GIRev\"/>  Sam Loveridge from ''[[GamesRadar]]'' likewise commented that the game is \"an anecdote generator at its very best\" due to its emergent storytelling.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Brandin Tyrrel from ''[[IGN]]'' stated that \"''Sea of Thieves'' works well when treated like a [[chat room]] or a [[party game]], where it serves as catalyst for having a good time with the people you\u2019re with\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Tyrell |first=Brandin |date=27 March 2018 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/28/sea-of-thieves-review |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay received generally negative reviews. Devore felt that the quests were repetitive and that the world did not have a lot of interesting things to do.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Paul Tamburro from ''[[Game Revolution]]'' agreed, remarking that the quests had little variety and did not allow room for creativity. While he praised the [[sandbox game|sandbox]] format, he felt that there were not enough secrets or stories players could discover in the world.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/> Loverdige called the voyages \"elaborated [[fetch quest]]s\". He lamented that there was no option to turn off PvP and players could not customize their own characters.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Russ Frushtick from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' remarked that misbehaving players may make the experience frustrating because PvP could never be disabled. However, he remarked that the game offered no incentive for players who wanted to engage in PvP combat.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Hilliard felt that the game did not have enough content to keep players engaged, and remarked that the combat felt bland. Many critics commented that players would not be motivated to complete quests because only cosmetic items are unlocked.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/><ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/> Tyrrel praised the ship combat, though he felt that the respawn system was too forgiving.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Christian Donlan from ''[[Eurogamer]]'' likewise called the ship combat \"thrilling\" and the general combat \"crunchy, pleasantly basic\".<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Tyler Wilde from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' liked exploring the shipwrecks, believing that exploration evokes a sense of discovery, though he commented that he wished more emergent events would happen in the ocean.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Solo play received mixed opinions. Some critics thought that it was more difficult,<ref name=\"polysolo\"/> boring,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-is-no-fun-by-yourself-1823934837|title=Sea Of Thieves Is No Fun By Yourself|first=Mike|last=Fahey|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and maddening,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/03/21/sea-of-thieves-solo-play/|title=Sea of Thieves solo is maddening and brutal - as it should be|first=Alec|last=Meer|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while some remarked that it was entertaining,<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> satisfying,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\"/> and relaxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-01-why-i-love-sailing-alone-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Why I love sailing alone in Sea of Thieves|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"polysolo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17150830/playing-sea-of-thieves-solo-experience|title=The case for sailing solo in Sea of Thieves|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year of updates, the game received more positive reviews from critics. Following the ''Anniversary'' update, ''IGN'' stated that players should give the game a second chance and that it was the \"perfect time\" to return to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/why-now-is-a-great-time-to-return-to-sea-of-thieves|title=Why Now Is a Great Time to Return to Sea of Thieves|first=Mark|last=Merlinda|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> One of its writers, David Jagneaux, praised the Tall Tales and its riddles in his second review, which he described as \"brain teasers that really challenge [player's] detective skills\".<ref name = \"IGN\"/> In his summary, he wrote that the game is a \"pirate fantasy sandbox with an enormous amount of things to do, made unpredictable and exciting by the addition of other players\".<ref name = \"IGN\"/> Nicole Carpenter from ''Polygon'' praised the post-launch updates for making the title more \"curated\" with more structure and direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' named ''Sea of Thieves'' the Best Ongoing Game of 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/best-ongoing-game-2019-sea-of-thieves/|title=Best Ongoing Game 2019: Sea of Thieves|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while ''[[Gameindustry.biz]]'' declared the title one of their [[Game of the Year|Games of the Year]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-12-15-game-of-the-year-2019-sea-of-thieves|title=Games of the Year 2019: Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Sea of Thieves'' is a commercial success. The title attracted more than 1 million players two days after it released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-seeing-unprecedented-demand-passes-/1100-6457743/|title=Sea Of Thieves Seeing \"Unprecedented\" Demand, Passes 1 Million Players|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> It was the best-selling retail game in the UK in its week of release<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-26-sea-of-thieves-lands-uk-chart-number-one|title=Sea of Thieves lands UK chart number one|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and it became the second best-selling game in the US in March 2018 behind ''[[Far Cry 5]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/far-cry-5-sea-of-thieves-march-npd/|title=Far Cry 5 and Sea of Thieves best-selling games in US during March, according to NPD|first=James|last=Billcliffe|work=[[VG 247]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 28 March 2018, Microsoft declared the game as the fast-selling new IP released for the Xbox One.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-microsofts-fastest-selling-new-i/1100-6457750/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Microsoft's Fastest-Selling New IP On Xbox One|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-11-quantum-break-uks-best-selling-boxed-game |title=Quantum Break UK's best-selling boxed game |first=Wesley |last=Yin-Poole |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=11 April 2016 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> Rare attributed the game's success to the title releasing for Xbox Game Pass subscribers at launch, which enabled the game to achieved Rare's sales target for three months in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-06-18-sea-of-thieves-hit-three-month-target-in-a-single-day|title=Sea of Thieves hit three month target in a single day|first=Matthew|last= Handrahan|work=[[Gameindustry.biz]]|date=18 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Game Pass contributed to half of the game's sales,<ref name=\"second launch\"/> though Microsoft added that the game also sold well in both retail and digital formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/315909/Microsoft_says_Sea_of_Thieves_sold_well_even_without_counting_Game_Pass_copies.php|title=Microsoft says Sea of Thieves sold well, even without counting Game Pass copies|first=Alissa|last=McAloon|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game passed five million players in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-08-01-sea-of-thieves-sloops-past-5m-players|title=Sea of Thieves passes 5m players|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, Rare declared the game was \"the most successful IP [Microsoft has] released in the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|generation]]\", with it amassing more than 10 million players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-now-xboxs-most-successful-new-ip/1100-6472598/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Now Xbox's \"Most Successful\" New IP Of The Generation|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In addition to good sales, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also popular with viewers, with the title being ranked as one of the most watched titles on Twitch in January 2019 following the ''Shrouded Spoils'' update.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-has-unexpectedly-become-one-of-twitchs-b-1831997645|title=Sea Of Thieves Has Unexpectedly Become One Of Twitch's Biggest Games|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=23 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/1/22/18193421/sea-of-thieves-twitch-ninja-dr-disrespect-summit1g|title=Sea of Thieves is enjoying a resurgence on Twitch|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2016\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best of Show\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2016nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2016 (2016 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Gamescom]] 2016\n| Best Xbox One Game\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamelibrarian.com/best-of-gamescom-2016-winners-selected-by-gamescom-committee/|title=Best of Gamescom 2016 Winners Selected by Gamescom Committee|publisher=The Video Game Librarian|date=19 August 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Online Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2016 voting now open to the public|website=[[Digital Spy]]|author=Sam Loveridge|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Game Critics Awards\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2017nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2017 (2017 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Golden Joystick Awards\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2017 Nominees|publisher=Best in Slot|first=Eri|last=Gaito|date=13 November 2017|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"16\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Develop (magazine)|Develop Awards]]\n| Animation\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/announcing-the-develop-awards-2018-nominations-shortlist|title=Announcing the Develop Awards 2018 nominations shortlist|magazine=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]|author=MCV staff|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Visual Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Music Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Sound Design \n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Gameplay Innovation\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[The Independent Game Developers' Association]] Awards 2018\n| Best Action and Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/tiga-announces-games-industry-awards-2018-finalists|title=TIGA Announces Games Industry Awards 2018 Finalists|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|author=Suzi Stephenson|date=19 September 2018|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/awards/2018-winners|title=2018 Winners|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|date=1 November 2018|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Creativity Award\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Visual Design\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/news/golden-joysticks-2018-nominees-announced-voting-open-now/|title=Golden Joysticks 2018 nominees announced, voting open now|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Tom Hoggins|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/golden-joystick-awards-2018-winners/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2018 winners: God of War wins big but Fortnite gets Victory Royale|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|author=Connor Sheridan|date=16 November 2018|accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Co-operative Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Xbox Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2018]]\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/game-awards-tga/2018/12/6/18130000/the-game-awards-winners-2018|title=The Game Awards 2018: Here are all the winners|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|author=Christopher Grant|date=6 December 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]]\n| Best Artistic Design\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|title=Titanium Awards 2018|website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]]|accessdate=7 November 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707230958/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|archivedate=7 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-10-red-dead-redemption-2-wins-best-game-at-fun-and-serious-festival-awards|title=Red Dead Redemption 2 wins Best Game at Fun & Serious Festival Awards|website=GamesIndustry.biz|author=Matthew Handrahan|date=10 December 2018|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Family Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Australian Games Awards\n| Multiplayer/Online Title of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.australiangamesawards.com/news/|title=Your 2018 Winners|publisher=Australian Games Awards|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"9\" | 2019\n| [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Online Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/god-of-war-spider-man-lead-dice-awards-heres-all-t/1100-6464345/|title=God Of War, Spider-Man Lead DICE Awards; Here's All The Nominees|website=[[GameSpot]]|author=Eddie Makuch|date=10 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Design, New IP\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3566/|title=Nominee List for 2018|publisher=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]|date=11 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Game, Original Action\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[15th British Academy Games Awards]]\n| Evolving Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/gaming/news/british-academy-games-awards-2019-nominees-1203163369/|title=\u2018God of War,\u2019 \u2018Red Dead 2\u2019 Lead BAFTA Game Awards Nominations|author=Stefanie Fogel|date=14 March 2019|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Italian Video Game Awards\n| Innovation Award\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://italianvideogameawards.com/awards|title=Italian Video Game Awards Nominees and Winners|website=Italian Video Game Awards|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ivor Novello Awards]]\n| Best Original Video Game Score\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8513011/2019-ivor-novello-awards-winners-list|title=Mariah Carey and The 1975 Win 2019 Ivor Novello Awards|author=Gil Kaufman|date=24 May 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| The Independent Game Developers' Association Awards 2019\n| Best Social Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/tiga-announces-games-industry-awards-2019-finalists|title=TIGA Announces Games Industry Awards 2019 Finalists|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|author=Suzi Stephenson|date=19 September 2019|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Game Expansion (''Anniversary Update'')\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards|author=Stephen Tailby|date=20 September 2019|website=Push Square|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seaofthieves.com/}}\n\n{{Rare}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kraken in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer vehicle operation games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Persistent worlds]]\n[[Category:Rare (company) games]]\n[[Category:Unreal Engine games]]\n[[Category:Video games about pirates]]\n[[Category:Video games with downloadable content]]\n[[Category:Video games with cross-platform play]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Robin Beanland]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring protagonists of selectable gender]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox Play Anywhere games]]\n", "name_user": "OceanHok", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGameplay", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_of_Thieves"}
{"title_page": "Digital citizen", "text_new": "{{short description|Person using IT to engage in society, politics, and government}}\n[[File:Annual Federal Bullying Prevention Summit - Adam.jpg|thumb|Every year, the Federal Partners in Bullying Prevention hosts a summit to highlight its work to prevent cyberbullying, especially in schools and amongst students, in efforts to become responsible digital citizens.]]\nA '''digital citizen''' is a person using [[information technology]] (IT) in order to engage in society, politics, and government. As defined by [[Karen Mossberger]], one of the authors of ''Digital Citizenship: The Internet, Society, and Participation'', digital citizens are \"those who use the internet regularly and effectively.\" They also have a comprehensive understanding of digital citizenship, which is the appropriate and responsible behavior when using technology.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=7fNHAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA742&lpg=PA742&dq=those+who+use+the+Internet+regularly+and+effectively|title=The 19th International Conference on Industrial Engineering and Engineering|isbn=978-3-642-37270-4|page=742|accessdate=6 June 2015|last1=Qi|first1=Ershi|last2=Shen|first2=Jiang|last3=Dou|first3=Runliang|date=2013-06-03}}</ref> Since digital citizenship evaluates the quality of an individual's response to membership in a digital community, it often requires the participation of all community members, both visible and those who are less visible.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/digitalcommunity0000ohle|url-access=registration|quote=those who use the Internet regularly and effectively.|title=Digital Community, Digital Citizen|publisher=SAGE Publications|last1=Ohler|first1=Jason B.|isbn=978-1412971447|page=[https://archive.org/details/digitalcommunity0000ohle/page/25 25]|accessdate=6 June 2015|date=2010-08-31}}</ref> A large part in being a responsible digital citizen encompasses digital literacy, etiquette, [[online safety]], and an acknowledgement of private versus public information.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.virtuallibrary.info/digital-citizenship.html|title=Digital Citizenship|website=Virtual Library|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nPeople characterizing themselves as digital citizens often use IT extensively, creating [[blogs]], using [[social networks]], and participating in [[Digital journalism|online journalism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/4678631.stm|title=Have Your Say - Are you a digital citizen?|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Although digital citizenship begins when any child, teen, and/or adult signs up for an email address, posts pictures online, uses [[e-commerce]] to buy merchandise online, and/or participates in any electronic function that is [[Business-to-business|B2B]] or [[B2C]], the process of becoming a digital citizen goes beyond simple internet activity. According to [[Thomas Humphrey Marshall]], a British sociologist known for his work on social citizenship, a primary framework of citizenship comprises three different traditions: liberalism, republicanism, and ascriptive hierarchy. Within this framework, the digital citizen needs to exist in order to promote equal economic opportunities and increase political participation.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marshall|first=T. H.|chapter=The Problem Stated with the Assistance of Alfred Marshall|title=Citizenship and Social Class|editor1=T. H. Marshall|editor2=T. Bottomore|pages=3\u201351|location=London|publisher=Pluto Perspectives|isbn=978-0745304762|date=January 1987}}</ref> In this way, digital technology helps to lower the [[barriers to entry]] for participation as a citizen within a society.\n\nHolistically, digital citizenship covers both a social and political point of view, utilized at a local level in school and other [[educational system]]s while also being debated upon on a national level. There are many means of participating as a digital citizen to advocate for causes or specific issues that are controversial, and being a digital citizen encompasses a level of responsibility that includes universal goals that should be followed.\n\n== Types of digital participation ==\nThe development of digital citizen participation can be divided into two main stages, the first being through information dissemination.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080710184539/http://www.businessofgovernment.org/pdfs/HolzerReport.pdf Restoring Trust in Government: The Potential of Digital Citizen Participation]</ref> Within information dissemination, one subcategory includes '''static information dissemination''', characterized largely by citizens who utilize read-only websites where they take control of data from credible sources in order to formulate judgments or facts. Many of these websites where credible information may be found are provided by the government. Another subcategory includes '''dynamic information dissemination''', which is more interactive and involves citizens as well as public servants. Both questions and answers can be communicated, and citizens have the opportunity to engage in question-and-answer dialogues through two-way communication platforms\n\nThe second stage of digital citizen participation is citizen deliberation, which evaluates what type of participation and role that they play when attempting to ignite some sort of policy change. For '''static citizen participants''', citizens can play a role by engaging in online polls as well as through complaints and recommendations sent up, mainly toward the government who can create changes in policy decisions. '''Dynamic citizen participants''' can deliberate amongst others on their thoughts and recommendations in town hall meetings or various media sites.\n\nOne of the primary advantages of participating in online debates through digital citizenship is that it incorporates [[sense of community|social inclusion]]. In a report on [[civic engagement]], citizen-powered democracy can be initiated either through information shared through the web, direct communication signals made by the state toward the public, and social media tactics from both private and public companies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dubow|first=Talitha|date=March 2017|title=Civic Engagement: How can digital technologies underpin citizen-powered democracy?|url=https://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/conf_proceedings/CF300/CF373/RAND_CF373.pdf|journal=RAND Corporation|pages=25}}</ref> In fact, it was found that the community-based nature of social media platforms allow individuals to feel more socially included and informed about political issues that peers have also been found to engage with, otherwise known as a \"second-order effect.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Voorveld|first=Hilde A. M.|last2=van Noort|first2=Guda|last3=Muntinga|first3=Dani\u00ebl G.|last4=Bronner|first4=Fred|date=2018-01-02|title=Engagement with Social Media and Social Media Advertising: The Differentiating Role of Platform Type|journal=Journal of Advertising|volume=47|issue=1|pages=38\u201354|doi=10.1080/00913367.2017.1405754|issn=0091-3367}}</ref> Two types of opportunities rise as a result, the first being the ability to lower barriers that can make exchanges much easier. In addition, they have the chance to participate in transformative disruption, giving people who have a historically lower political engagement to mobilize in a much easier and convenient fashion.\n\nNonetheless, there are several challenges that face the presence of digital technologies in political participation. Both current as well as potential challenges can create significant risks for democratic processes. Not only is digital technology still seen as relatively ambiguous, it was also seen to have \"less inclusivity in democratic life.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fenwick|first=Tara|last2=Edwards|first2=Richard|date=2016-01-01|title=Exploring the impact of digital technologies on professional responsibilities and education|journal=European Educational Research Journal|volume=15|issue=1|pages=117\u2013131|doi=10.1177/1474904115608387|issn=1474-9041}}</ref> Demographic groups differ considerably in the use of technology, and thus, one group could potentially be more represented than another as a result of digital participation. Another primary challenge consists in the ideology of a \"[[filter bubble]]\" effect. Alongside a tremendous spread of false information, internet users could reinforce existing prejudices and assist in polarizing disagreements in the public sphere. This can lead to misinformed voting and decisions based on exposure rather than on pure knowledge. A [[communication technology]] director, Van Dijk, stated, \"Computerized information campaigns and mass public information systems have to be designed and supported in such a way that they help to narrow the gap between the 'information rich' and 'information poor' otherwise the spontaneous development of ICT will widen it.\" Access and equivalent amounts of knowledge behind digital technology must be equivalent in order for a fair system to put into place.\n[[File:2019 EITI Global Conference 2019 EITI Global Conference (48093042323).jpg|thumb|Hosted by the Government of France at the OECD Conference Centre in Paris, representatives discussed trust in data and how we can utilize data to spread openness in addressing environmental challenges.]]\nAlongside a lack of evidenced support for technology that can be proven to be safe for citizens, the [[OECD]] has identified five struggles for the online engagement of citizens:\n\n#'''Scale:''' To what extent can we allow every individual's voice to be heard, but also not be lost in the mass debate? This can be extremely challenging for the government, who may not effectively know how to listen and respond to each individual contribution.\n#'''Capacity:''' How can digital technology offer citizens with more information on public policy making? The opportunity for citizens to debate with one another is lacking for [[active citizenship]].\n#'''Coherence:''' The government is yet to design a more holistic view of policy-making cycle and the use of design technology to better prepare information from citizens in each stage of the policy-making cycle.\n#'''Evaluation:''' There is a greater need now than ever before to figure out whether or not online engagement can help meet the citizen as well as the government's objectives.\n#'''Commitment:''' Is the government committed to analyze and use citizen's public input, and how can this process be validated more regularly?\n\n== Developed states and developing countries ==\nHighly developed states possess the capacity to link their respective governments with digital sites. Such sites function in ways such as publicising recent legislation, current and future policy objectives; lending agency toward political candidates; and/or allowing citizens to voice themselves in a political way. Likewise, the emergence of these sites has been linked to increased voting advocacy. Lack of access to technology can be a serious obstacle in becoming a digital citizen, since many elementary procedures such as tax report filing, birth registration, and use of websites to support candidates in political campaigns ([[e-democracy]]) have become available solely via the internet. Furthermore, many cultural and commercial entities only publicize information on web pages. Non-digital citizens will not be able to retrieve this information, and this may lead to [[social isolation]] or [[economic stagnation]].\n\nThe gap between digital citizens and non-digital citizens is often referred as the [[digital divide]]. In [[developing countries]], digital citizens are fewer. They consist of the people who use technology to overcome local obstacles including development issues, corruption, and even military conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/products/gear/2005-08-28-cell-banks-africa_x.htm|title=Africa's cell phone boom creates a base for low-cost banking|work=usatoday.com}}</ref> Examples of such citizens include users of [[Ushahidi]] during the [[2007\u201308 Kenyan crisis|2007 disputed Kenyan election]] and protesters in the [[Arab Spring]] movements who used media to document repression of protests. Currently, the digital divide is a subject of academic debate as access to the internet has increased in these developing countries, but the place in which it is accessed (work, home, public library, etc.) has a significant effect on how such access will be used, if even in a manner related to citizenry. Recent scholarship has correlated the desire to be technologically proficient with greater belief in computer access equity, and thus, digital citizenship (Shelley, et al.).\n\nOn the other side of the divide, one example of a highly-developed digital technology program in a wealthy state is the [[e-Residency of Estonia]]. This form of digital residency allows both citizens and non-citizens of the state to pursue business opportunities in a digital business environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e-resident.gov.ee/become-an-e-resident/|title=e-Residency Benefits {{!}} Digital Nomad, Freelancer, Startup Company|website=e-Residency|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> The application is simple; residents can fill out a form with their passport and photograph alongside the reason for applying. Following a successful application, the \"e-residency\" will allow them to register a company, sign documents, make online banking declarations, and file medical prescriptions online, though they will be tracked through financial footprints. The project plans to cover over 10 million e-residents by 2025 and {{as of|2019|04|lc=y|post=,}} there were over 54,000 participants from over 162 countries that have expressed an interest, contributing millions of dollars to the country's economy and assisting in access to any public service online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ninaangelovska/2019/04/25/estonias-e-residency-contributed-e14m-to-its-economy-e-residency-2-0-will-be-a-true-forerunner/|title=Estonia's E-Residency Contributed \u20ac14M To Its Economy--'E-Residency 2.0 Will Be A True Forerunner'|last=Angelovska|first=Nina|website=Forbes|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> Other benefits include hassle-free administration, lower business costs, access to the European Union market, and a broad range of e-services. Though the programme is designed for entrepreneurs, Estonia hopes to value transparency and resourcefulness as a cause for other companies to implement similar policies domestically.\n\nNonetheless, Estonia's e-Residency system has been subject to criticism. Many have pointed out that [[tax treaties]] within their own countries will play a major role in preventing this idea from spreading to more countries. Another risk is politically for governments to sustain \"funding and legislative priorities across different coalitions of power.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kotka|first=Taavi|date=September 2015|title=Estonian e-Residency: Redefining the Nation-State in the Digital Era|url=https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/materials/publications/14883/workingpaperno3kotkavargaskorjus.pdf|journal=Cyber Studies Programme}}</ref> Most importantly, the threat of [[cyberattack]]s may disrupt the seemingly optimal idea of having a platform for eIDs, as Estonia suffered its own massive cyberattack in 2007 by Russian [[hacktivism|hacktivists]]. Today, the protection of digital services and databases is essential to national security, and many countries are still hesitant to take the next step forward to promote a new system that will change the scale of politics with all its citizens.\n\n== Other forms of digital divide ==\nWithin developed countries, the digital divide, other than economic differences, is attributed to educational levels. A study conducted by the United States [[National Telecommunications and Information Administration]] determined that the gap in computer usage and internet access widened 7.8% and 25% between those with the most and least education, and it has been observed that those with college degrees or higher are 10 times more likely to have internet access at work when compared with those with only a high school education.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bezuidenhout|first=Louise M.|last2=Leonelli|first2=Sabina|last3=Kelly|first3=Ann H.|last4=Rappert|first4=Brian|date=2017-08-01|title=Beyond the digital divide: Towards a situated approach to open data|journal=Science and Public Policy|volume=44|issue=4|pages=464\u2013475|doi=10.1093/scipol/scw036|issn=0302-3427}}</ref>\n\nA digital divide often extends along specific racial lines as well. The difference in computer usage grew by 39.2% between White and Black households and by 42.6% between White and Hispanic households only three years ago.{{when?|date=March 2020}} Race can also affect the number of computers at school, and as expected, gaps between racial groups narrow at higher income levels while widening among households at lower economic levels. [[Racial disparities in education|Racial disparities]] have been proven to exist irrespective of income, and in a cultural study to determine reasons for the divide other than income, in accordance to the Hispanic community, computers were seen as a luxury, not a need. Participants collectively stated that computer activities isolated individuals and took away valuable time from family activities. In the African-American community, it was observed that they historically have had negative encounters with technological innovations, and with Asian-Americans, education was emphasized, and thus, there was a larger number of people who embraced the rise in [[Innovation|technological advances.]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dijk|first=Jan|date=August 2017|title=Digital Divide Research, Achievements, and Shortcomings|journal=Poetics|pages=34}}</ref>\n\nAn educational divide also takes place as a result of differences in the use of daily technology. In a report analyzed by the [[ACT (test)|ACT]] Center for Equity in Learning, \"85% of respondents reported having access to anywhere from two to five devices at home. The remaining one percent of respondents reported having access to no devices at home.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moore|first=Raeal|date=August 2018|title=The Digital Divide and Educational Equity|url=https://www.act.org/content/dam/act/unsecured/documents/R1698-digital-divide-2018-08.pdf|journal=ACT Center for Equity in Learning}}</ref> For the 14% of respondents with one device at home, many of them reported the need to share these devices with other household members, facing challenges that are often overlooked. The data all suggests that wealthier families have access to more devices. In addition, out of the respondents that only used one device at home, 24% of them lived in rural areas, and over half reported that this one device was a smartphone; this could make completing schoolwork assignments more difficult. The ACT recommended that underserved students need access to more devices and higher-quality networks, and educators should do their best to ensure that students can find as many electronic materials through their phones to not place a burden on family plans. \n\n==Engagement of youth==\n[[File:Inclusion Convention.jpg|thumb|At the 2018 Institutional Convention, Shola Mos-Shogbamimu, founder of the Convention, discusses the role of digital media in preventing the spread of sexual harassment and what measures can be taken to stop the spread of negativity in youth.]]\nA recent survey revealed that teenagers and young adults spend more time on the internet than watching TV. This has raised a number of concerns about how internet use could impact cognitive abilities.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mills |first1=Kathryn |title=Possible Effects of Internet Use on Cognitive Development in Adolescence |journal=Media and Communication |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=4 |doi=10.17645/mac.v4i3.516 |year=2016}}</ref> According to a study by Wartella et al., teens are concerned about how digital technologies may have an impact on their health.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wartella |first1=Ellen |last2=Rideout |first2=Vicky |last3=Montague |first3=Heather |last4=Beaudoin-Ryan |first4=Leanne |last5=Lauricella |first5=Alexis |title=Teens, Health and Technology: A National Survey |journal=Media and Communication |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=13 |doi=10.17645/mac.v4i3.515 |year=2016}}</ref> Digital youth can generally be viewed as the test market for the next generation's digital content and services. Sites such as [[Myspace]] and [[Facebook]] have come to the fore in sites where youth participate and engage with others on the internet. However, due to the lack of popularity of MySpace in particular, more young people are turning to websites such as [[Snapchat]], [[Instagram]], and [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/11/03/health/teens-tweens-media-screen-use-report/|title=Teens spend 9 hours a day using media, report says |first=Kelly |last=Wallace|work=CNN|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> It was reported that teenagers spend up to nine hours a day online, with the vast majority of that time spent on social media websites from mobile devices, contributing to the ease of access and availability to young people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.socialmediatoday.com/marketing/how-much-time-do-people-spend-social-media-infographic|title=How Much Time Do People Spend on Social Media? [Infographic]|work=Social Media Today|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> Vast amounts of money are spent annually to research the demographic by hiring psychologists, sociologists and anthropologists in order to discover habits, values and fields of interest.\n\nParticularly in the United States, \"Social media use has become so pervasive in the lives of American teens that having a presence on a social network is almost synonymous with being online; 95% of all teens ages 12-17 are now online and 80% of those online teens are users of social media sites\".<ref>\"[http://www.pewinternet.org/2011/11/09/teens-kindness-and-cruelty-on-social-network-sites/ How American Teens Navigate the New World of 'digital Citizenship']\". Pew Research Center's Internet & American Life Project. Web. 23 Nov. 2011.</ref>{{Update inline|date=March 2020}} However, movements such as these appear to benefit strictly those wishing to advocate for their business towards youth. The critical time when young people are developing their civic identities is between the ages 15\u201322. During this time they develop three attributes, civic literacy, civic skills and civic attachment, that constitute civic engagement later reflected in political actions of their adult lives.\n\nFor youth to fully participate and realize their presence on the internet, a quality level of reading comprehension is required. \"The average government web site, for example, requires an eleventh-grade level of reading comprehension, even though about half of the U.S. population reads at an eighth-grade level or lower\".<ref name=\"mossberger-digital-citizenship\">{{cite book|title=Digital Citizenship - The Internet, Society & Participation|last1=Mossberger|first1=Karen|last2=Tolbert|first2=Caroline J.|last3=McNeal|first3=Ramona S. |author-link2=Caroline Tolbert|date=October 2007|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|isbn=978-0262633536}}</ref> So despite the internet being a place irrespective of certain factors such as race, religion, and class, education plays a large part in a person's capacity to present themselves online in a formal manner conducive towards their citizenry. Concurrently, education also affects people's motivation to participate online.\n\nStudents should be encouraged to utilize technology with responsibility and ethical digital citizenship promoted. Education on harmful viruses and other [[malware]] must be emphasized to protect resources. A student can be a successful digital citizen with the help of educators, parents, and school counselors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationworld.com/a_tech/responsible-student-technology-use.shtml|title=Help Kids Become Responsible Digital Citizens|publisher=educationworld.com}}</ref>\n\n==Limits on the use of data==\nInternational [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]] guidelines state that \"personal data should be relevant to the purposes for which they are to be used, and to the extent necessary for those purposes should be accurate, complete, and kept up to date\". Article 8 prevents subjects to certain exceptions. Meaning that certain things cannot be published online revealing race, ethnicity, religion, political stance, health, and sex life. in the United States, this is enforced generally by the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC)- but very generally. For example, the FTC brought an action against Microsoft for failing to properly protect customers' personal information.<ref>[http://docs.law.gwu.edu/facweb/dsolove/Digital-Person/text/Digital-Person-CH1.pdf ''The Digital Person - Technology and Privacy in the Information Age'' - Chapter 1]</ref> In addition, many have described the United States as being in a [[cyberwarfare|cyberwar]] with Russia, and several Americans have credited Russia to their country's downfall in transparency and declining trust in the government. With several foreign users posting anonymous information through social media in order to gather a following, it is difficult to understand whom to target and what affiliation or root cause they may have of performing a particular action aimed to sway public opinion.\n\nThe FTC does play a significant role in protecting the digital citizen. However, individuals' public records are increasingly useful to the government and highly sought after. This material can help the government detect a variety of crimes such as fraud, drug distribution rings, terrorist cells. it makes it easier to properly profile a suspected criminal and keep an eye on them. Although there are a variety of ways to gather information on an individual through credit card history, employment history, and more, the internet is becoming the most desirable information gatherer thanks to its fa\u00e7ade of security and the amount of information that can be stored on the internet. [[Internet anonymity|Anonymity]] has proven to be very rare online as [[Internet service provider|ISP]]s can keep track of an individual's activity online.<ref>[http://docs.law.gwu.edu/facweb/dsolove/Digital-Person/text/Digital-Person-CH9.pdf ''The Digital Person - Technology and Privacy in the Information Age'' - Chapter 9]</ref> Furthermore, an open internet as delegated by a state's government is necessary to instill a sense of trust, legitimacy, and participation in the state's citizenry. [[WikiLeaks]] represents an occurrence where particular political actors have criticized and taken citizen action toward revealing the government's unnecessary clandestine activity online. As stated by the a representative from the ''World Heritage Encyclopedia'', \"The benefit of transparency isn't just catching red-handed bastards. It's also about collaborating and coming together with a more engaged citizenry,\" and many critics have stated that the process in doing so will still take several years.\n\n==Three principles of digital citizenship==\nDigital citizenship is a term used to define the appropriate and responsible use of technology among users. Three principles were developed by Mark Ribble to teach digital users how to responsibly use technology to become a digital citizen: respect, educate, and protect.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.iste.org/explore/articleDetail?articleid=535|title=Digital citizenship is more important than ever|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref> Each principle contains three of the nine elements of digital citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalcitizenship.net/nine-elements.html|title=Nine Elements|website=Digital Citizenship|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref>\n# '''Respect:''' the elements of etiquette, access, and law are used to respect other digital users.\n# '''Educate:''' the elements of literacy, communication, and commerce are used to learn about the appropriate use of the digital world.\n# '''Protect:''' the elements of rights and responsibilities, security, and health and wellness are used to remain safe in the digital and non-digital world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iste.org/explore/Lead-the-way/Digital-citizenship-is-more-important-than-ever?articleid=535|title=Digital citizenship is more important than ever {{!}} ISTE|website=www.iste.org|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\nWithin these three core principles, there are nine elements to also be considered in regards to digital citizenship. According to digitalcitizenship.net, these nine theme include:<ref>[http://www.digitalcitizenship.net/nine-elements.html Nine Themes of Digital Citizenship], digitalcitizenship.net</ref>\n\n#'''Digital access''': This is perhaps one of the most fundamental blocks to being a digital citizen. However, due to socioeconomic status, location, and other disabilities, some individuals may not have digital access. Recently, schools have been becoming more connected with the internet, often offering computers, and other forms of access. This can be offered through kiosks, community centers, and open labs. This most often is associated with the digital divide and factors associated with such. Digital access is available in many remote countries via cyber caf\u00e9s and small coffee shops.<ref>[http://www.iste.org/docs/excerpts/DIGCI2-excerpt.pdf Digital Citizenship in Schools - Excerpt]</ref>\n#'''[[Digital commerce]]''': This is the ability for users to recognize that much of the economy is regulated online. It also deals with the understanding of the dangers and benefits of online buying, using credit cards online, and so forth. As with the advantages and legal activities- there is also dangerous activities such as illegal downloads, gambling, drug deals, pornography, plagiarism, and so forth.\n#'''Digital communication''': This element deals with understanding the variety of online communication mediums such as email, instant messaging, Facebook messenger, the variety of apps, and so forth. There is a standard of etiquette associated with each medium.\n#'''[[Digital literacy]]''': This deals with the understanding of how to use various digital devices. For example, how to properly search for something on a search engine versus a database. How to use various online logs. Oftentimes many educational institutions will help form an individual's digital literacy.\n#'''[[Etiquette in technology|Digital etiquette]]''': As discussed in the third element, digital communication, this is the expectation that various mediums require a variety of etiquette. Certain mediums demand more appropriate behavior and language than others.\n#'''Digital law''': This is where enforcement occurs for illegal downloads, plagiarizing, hacking, creating viruses, sending spam, identity theft, [[cyberbullying]], and so forth.\n#'''Digital rights and responsibilities''': This is the set of rights digital citizens have such as privacy and free speech.\n#'''Digital health''': Digital citizens must be aware of the physical stress placed on their bodies by internet usage. They must be aware to not become overly dependent on the internet causing problems such as eye strain, headaches, and stress.\n#'''Digital security''': This simply means that citizens must take measures to be safe by practicing using secure passwords, virus protection, backing up data, and so forth.\n\n== Digital citizenship in education ==\nAccording to Mike Ribble, an author who has worked on the topic of digital citizenship for more than a decade, digital access is the first element that is prevalent in today's educational curriculum. He cited a widening gap between the impoverished and the wealthy, as 41% of African Americans and Hispanics use computers in the home when compared to 77% of white students. Other crucial digital elements include digital commerce, digital communication, digital literacy, and digital etiquette. He also emphasized that educators must understand that technology is important for all students, not just those who already have access to it, in order to decrease the digital divide that currently exists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://choraltech.wordpress.com/nine-elements-of-digital-citizenship-mike-ribble/|title=Nine Elements of Digital Citizenship \u2013 Mike Ribble|date=2017-09-10|website=Choraltech|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in research brought up by [[Common Sense Media]], approximately six out of 10 US K-12 teachers used some type of digital citizenship curriculum, and seven out of ten taught some sort of competency skill utilizing digital citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://d1e2bohyu2u2w9.cloudfront.net/education/sites/default/files/tlr_component/common_sense_education_digital_citizenship_research_backgrounder.pdf|title=Teaching Digital Citizenship In Today's World|last=Steyer|first=Jim|date=Summer 2019|website=Common Sense K-12 Digital Citizenship Curriculum|url-status=live}}</ref> Many of the sections that these teachers focused in on included hate speech, cyberbullying, and digital drama. A problem with digital technology that still exists is that over 35% of students were observed to not possess the proper skills to critically evaluate information online, and these issues and statistics increased as the grade levels rose. Online videos such as those found on YouTube and Netflix have been used approximately by 60% of the K-12 teachers in classrooms, while educational tools such as Microsoft Office and Google G Suite have been used by around half of the teachers. Social media was used the least, at around 13% in comparison to other digital methods of education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/sites/default/files/uploads/research/2019-educator-census-inside-the-21st-century-classroom_1.pdf|title=The Common Sense Census: Inside the 21st-Century Classroom |last1=Vega |first1=Vanessa |first2=Michael B. |last2=Robb |date=2019 |website=Common Sense Media |url-status=live}}</ref> When analyzing the social class differences between schools, it was found that Title I schools were more likely to utilize digital citizenship curricula than teachers in more affluent schools.\n\nIn the past two years, there has been a major shift to move students from digital citizenship to digital leadership in order to make a greater impact on online interactions. Though digital citizens take a responsible approach to act ethically, digital leadership is a more proactive approach, encompassing the \"use of internet and social media to improve the lives, well-being, and circumstances of others\" as part of one's daily life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthought.com/the-future-of-learning/moving-students-from-digital-citizenship-to-digital-leadership/|title=Moving Students From Digital Citizenship To Digital Leadership|date=2018-11-19|website=TeachThought|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> On February 2018, after the Valentine's Day shooting in [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|Parkland, Florida]], students became dynamic digital citizens, using social media and other web platforms to engage proactively on the issue and push back against cyberbullies and misinformation. Students from [[Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School]] specifically rallied against gun violence, engaging in live tweeting, texting, videoing, and recording the attack as it happened, utilizing onside digital tools to not only witness what was happening at the time but to allow the world to witness it as well. This allowed the nation to see and react, and as a result, students built a webpage and logo for their new movement.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dillenbourg|first=Pierre|date=2016-06-01|title=The Evolution of Research on Digital Education|journal=International Journal of Artificial Intelligence in Education|volume=26|issue=2|pages=544\u2013560|doi=10.1007/s40593-016-0106-z|issn=1560-4306}}</ref> They gave interviews to major media outlets and at rallies and protects and coordinated a nationwide march online on March 24 against elected officials at meetings and town halls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iste.org/explore/Digital-citizenship/Students-use-grief,-passion,-technology-to-create-a-movement|title=Students use grief, passion, technology to create a movement {{!}} ISTE|website=iste.org|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> The idea of this shift in youth is to express empathy beyond one's self, and moving to seeing this self in the digital company of others.\n\nNonetheless, several critics state that just as empathy can be spread to a vast number of individuals, hatred can be spread as well. Though the United Nations and groups have been establishing fronts against hate speech, there is no legal definition of hate speech used internationally, and more research needs to be done on its impact.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guterres|first=Antonio|date=May 2019|title=United Nations Strategy and Plan of Action on Hate Speech|url=https://www.un.org/en/genocideprevention/documents/UN%20Strategy%20and%20Plan%20of%20Action%20on%20Hate%20Speech%2018%20June%20SYNOPSIS.pdf|journal=United Nations}}</ref>\n\nAlong with educational trends, there are overlapping goals of digital citizenship education, and they include:<ref>[http://digcit.us/ About Digital Citizenship Conversations], digcit.us</ref>\n\n#'''[[Digital footprint]]:''' An acknowledgment that posting and receiving information online can be tracked, customized, and marketed for users to click and follow. Not only the internet use but individuals' digital footprints can lead to both beneficial and negative outcomes, but the ability to manage one's digital footprints can be a sub-part of digital literacy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Micheli|first=Marina|date=June 2018|title=Digital Footprints: An Emerging Dimension of Digital Inequality|journal=Journal of Information Communication and Ethics in Society|pages=7}}</ref> Digital footprints do not simply consist of the active participation of content production as well as sharing of ideas on different media sites, but they can also be generated by other internet users (both active and passive forms of digital participation).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://net-ref.com/white-paper-fostering-digital-citizenship-in-the-classroom/|title=Digital Natives - Fostering Digital Citizenship in the Classroom|last=NetRef|date=2016-04-04|website=NetRef|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> Examples of digital footprints includes liking, favoriting, following, or commenting on a certain online content creation, or other data can be found by searching through history, purchases, and searches.\n#'''Digital literacy:''' Almost twenty years ago, Gilster (1997) defined [[digital literacy]] as \"the ability to understand and use information in multiple formats from a wide range of sources when it is presented via computers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Digital Literacy for the 21st Century|last=Casey|first=Paul|publisher=Information Resources Management Association, US|date=January 2017}}</ref> Digital literacy includes the locating and consumption of content online, the creation of content, and the way that this content is communicated amongst a group of people.\n#'''Information literacy:''' The American Library Association defines [[information literacy]] as the overall ability for an individual to target information that is valuable, being able to find it, evaluate it, and utilize it. This can be through information creation, research, scholarly conversations, or simply plugging in keywords into a search engine.\n#'''Copyright, intellectual property respect, attribution:''' By knowing who published sources and whether or not content creation is credible, users can be better educated as to what and what not to believe when engaging in digital participation.\n#'''Health and wellness:''' A healthy community allows for an interactive conversation to take place between educated citizens who are knowledgeable about their environment.\n#'''Empowering student voice, agency, advocacy:''' Utilizing nonprofits as well as government-affiliated organizations in order to empower students to speak up for policy changes that need to be made. Currently, more than 10 different [[mobile applications]] aim to allow students the opportunity to speak up and advocate for rights online.\n#'''Safety, security and privacy:''' Addressing freedoms extended to everyone in a digital world and the balance between the [[right to privacy]] and the safety hazards that go along with it. This area of digital citizenship includes the assistance of students to understand when they are provided the right opportunities, including the proper access to the internet and products that are sold online. It is on the part of educators to assist students in understanding that it is crucial to protect others online.\n#'''Character education and ethics:''' Knowing that ethically speaking, everyone will come with different viewpoints online and it is crucial to remain balanced and moral in [[Targeted advertising|online behavior]].\n#'''Parenting:''' Emphasizing the efforts of educators, many want to continue preaching rules and policies addressing issues related to the online world. Cyberbullying, sexting, and other negative issues that are brought up are regulated by the School Resource Officers and other school counsel.\n\nAltogether, nine of these facets contribute to one another in the development of a healthy and effective education for digital technology and communication.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Civic technology]]\n* [[E-government]]\n* [[Open government]]\n* [[Service design]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/take-the-fbis-safe-online-surfing-internet-challenge Take the Safe Online Surfing Internet Challenge] ([[FBI]])\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Digital Citizen}}\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:Digital technology]]\n[[Category:Internet governance]]\n[[Category:Information revolution]]\n[[Category:Digital divide]]\n[[Category:Internet ethics]]\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n[[Category:Youth-led media]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Person using IT to engage in society, politics, and government}}\n[[File:Annual Federal Bullying Prevention Summit - Adam.jpg|thumb|Every year, the Federal Partners in Bullying Prevention hosts a summit to highlight its work to prevent cyberbullying, especially in schools and amongst students, in efforts to become responsible digital citizens.]]\nA '''digital citizen''' is a person using [[information technology]] (IT) in order to engage in society, politics, and government. As defined by [[Karen Mossberger]], author of ''Digital Citizenship: The Internet, Society, and Participation'', digital citizens are \"those who use the internet regularly and effectively.\" They also have a comprehensive understanding of digital citizenship, which is the appropriate and responsible behavior when using technology.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=7fNHAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA742&lpg=PA742&dq=those+who+use+the+Internet+regularly+and+effectively|title=The 19th International Conference on Industrial Engineering and Engineering|isbn=978-3-642-37270-4|page=742|accessdate=6 June 2015|last1=Qi|first1=Ershi|last2=Shen|first2=Jiang|last3=Dou|first3=Runliang|date=2013-06-03}}</ref> Since digital citizenship evaluates the quality of an individual's response to membership in a digital community, it often requires the participation of all community members, both visible and those who are less visible.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/digitalcommunity0000ohle|url-access=registration|quote=those who use the Internet regularly and effectively.|title=Digital Community, Digital Citizen|publisher=SAGE Publications|last1=Ohler|first1=Jason B.|isbn=978-1412971447|page=[https://archive.org/details/digitalcommunity0000ohle/page/25 25]|accessdate=6 June 2015|date=2010-08-31}}</ref> A large part in being a responsible digital citizen encompasses digital literacy, etiquette, [[online safety]], and an acknowledgement of private versus public information.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.virtuallibrary.info/digital-citizenship.html|title=Digital Citizenship|website=Virtual Library|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nPeople characterizing themselves as digital citizens often use IT extensively, creating [[blogs]], using [[social networks]], and participating in [[Digital journalism|online journalism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/4678631.stm|title=Have Your Say - Are you a digital citizen?|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Although digital citizenship begins when any child, teen, and/or adult signs up for an email address, posts pictures online, uses [[e-commerce]] to buy merchandise online, and/or participates in any electronic function that is [[Business-to-business|B2B]] or [[B2C]], the process of becoming a digital citizen goes beyond simple internet activity. According to [[Thomas Humphrey Marshall]], a British sociologist known for his work on social citizenship, a primary framework of citizenship comprises three different traditions: liberalism, republicanism, and ascriptive hierarchy. Within this framework, the digital citizen needs to exist in order to promote equal economic opportunities and increase political participation.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marshall|first=T. H.|chapter=The Problem Stated with the Assistance of Alfred Marshall|title=Citizenship and Social Class|editor1=T. H. Marshall|editor2=T. Bottomore|pages=3\u201351|location=London|publisher=Pluto Perspectives|isbn=978-0745304762|date=January 1987}}</ref> In this way, digital technology helps to lower the [[barriers to entry]] for participation as a citizen within a society.\n\nHolistically, digital citizenship covers both a social and political point of view, utilized at a local level in school and other [[educational system]]s while also being debated upon on a national level. There are many means of participating as a digital citizen to advocate for causes or specific issues that are controversial, and being a digital citizen encompasses a level of responsibility that includes universal goals that should be followed.\n\n== Types of digital participation ==\nThe development of digital citizen participation can be divided into two main stages, the first being through information dissemination.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080710184539/http://www.businessofgovernment.org/pdfs/HolzerReport.pdf Restoring Trust in Government: The Potential of Digital Citizen Participation]</ref> Within information dissemination, one subcategory includes '''static information dissemination''', characterized largely by citizens who utilize read-only websites where they take control of data from credible sources in order to formulate judgments or facts. Many of these websites where credible information may be found are provided by the government. Another subcategory includes '''dynamic information dissemination''', which is more interactive and involves citizens as well as public servants. Both questions and answers can be communicated, and citizens have the opportunity to engage in question-and-answer dialogues through two-way communication platforms\n\nThe second stage of digital citizen participation is citizen deliberation, which evaluates what type of participation and role that they play when attempting to ignite some sort of policy change. For '''static citizen participants''', citizens can play a role by engaging in online polls as well as through complaints and recommendations sent up, mainly toward the government who can create changes in policy decisions. '''Dynamic citizen participants''' can deliberate amongst others on their thoughts and recommendations in town hall meetings or various media sites.\n\nOne of the primary advantages of participating in online debates through digital citizenship is that it incorporates [[sense of community|social inclusion]]. In a report on [[civic engagement]], citizen-powered democracy can be initiated either through information shared through the web, direct communication signals made by the state toward the public, and social media tactics from both private and public companies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dubow|first=Talitha|date=March 2017|title=Civic Engagement: How can digital technologies underpin citizen-powered democracy?|url=https://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/conf_proceedings/CF300/CF373/RAND_CF373.pdf|journal=RAND Corporation|pages=25}}</ref> In fact, it was found that the community-based nature of social media platforms allow individuals to feel more socially included and informed about political issues that peers have also been found to engage with, otherwise known as a \"second-order effect.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Voorveld|first=Hilde A. M.|last2=van Noort|first2=Guda|last3=Muntinga|first3=Dani\u00ebl G.|last4=Bronner|first4=Fred|date=2018-01-02|title=Engagement with Social Media and Social Media Advertising: The Differentiating Role of Platform Type|journal=Journal of Advertising|volume=47|issue=1|pages=38\u201354|doi=10.1080/00913367.2017.1405754|issn=0091-3367}}</ref> Two types of opportunities rise as a result, the first being the ability to lower barriers that can make exchanges much easier. In addition, they have the chance to participate in transformative disruption, giving people who have a historically lower political engagement to mobilize in a much easier and convenient fashion.\n\nNonetheless, there are several challenges that face the presence of digital technologies in political participation. Both current as well as potential challenges can create significant risks for democratic processes. Not only is digital technology still seen as relatively ambiguous, it was also seen to have \"less inclusivity in democratic life.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fenwick|first=Tara|last2=Edwards|first2=Richard|date=2016-01-01|title=Exploring the impact of digital technologies on professional responsibilities and education|journal=European Educational Research Journal|volume=15|issue=1|pages=117\u2013131|doi=10.1177/1474904115608387|issn=1474-9041}}</ref> Demographic groups differ considerably in the use of technology, and thus, one group could potentially be more represented than another as a result of digital participation. Another primary challenge consists in the ideology of a \"[[filter bubble]]\" effect. Alongside a tremendous spread of false information, internet users could reinforce existing prejudices and assist in polarizing disagreements in the public sphere. This can lead to misinformed voting and decisions based on exposure rather than on pure knowledge. A [[communication technology]] director, Van Dijk, stated, \"Computerized information campaigns and mass public information systems have to be designed and supported in such a way that they help to narrow the gap between the 'information rich' and 'information poor' otherwise the spontaneous development of ICT will widen it.\" Access and equivalent amounts of knowledge behind digital technology must be equivalent in order for a fair system to put into place.\n[[File:2019 EITI Global Conference 2019 EITI Global Conference (48093042323).jpg|thumb|Hosted by the Government of France at the OECD Conference Centre in Paris, representatives discussed trust in data and how we can utilize data to spread openness in addressing environmental challenges.]]\nAlongside a lack of evidenced support for technology that can be proven to be safe for citizens, the [[OECD]] has identified five struggles for the online engagement of citizens:\n\n#'''Scale:''' To what extent can we allow every individual's voice to be heard, but also not be lost in the mass debate? This can be extremely challenging for the government, who may not effectively know how to listen and respond to each individual contribution.\n#'''Capacity:''' How can digital technology offer citizens with more information on public policy making? The opportunity for citizens to debate with one another is lacking for [[active citizenship]].\n#'''Coherence:''' The government is yet to design a more holistic view of policy-making cycle and the use of design technology to better prepare information from citizens in each stage of the policy-making cycle.\n#'''Evaluation:''' There is a greater need now than ever before to figure out whether or not online engagement can help meet the citizen as well as the government's objectives.\n#'''Commitment:''' Is the government committed to analyze and use citizen's public input, and how can this process be validated more regularly?\n\n== Developed states and developing countries ==\nHighly developed states possess the capacity to link their respective governments with digital sites. Such sites function in ways such as publicising recent legislation, current and future policy objectives; lending agency toward political candidates; and/or allowing citizens to voice themselves in a political way. Likewise, the emergence of these sites has been linked to increased voting advocacy. Lack of access to technology can be a serious obstacle in becoming a digital citizen, since many elementary procedures such as tax report filing, birth registration, and use of websites to support candidates in political campaigns ([[e-democracy]]) have become available solely via the internet. Furthermore, many cultural and commercial entities only publicize information on web pages. Non-digital citizens will not be able to retrieve this information, and this may lead to [[social isolation]] or [[economic stagnation]].\n\nThe gap between digital citizens and non-digital citizens is often referred as the [[digital divide]]. In [[developing countries]], digital citizens are fewer. They consist of the people who use technology to overcome local obstacles including development issues, corruption, and even military conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/products/gear/2005-08-28-cell-banks-africa_x.htm|title=Africa's cell phone boom creates a base for low-cost banking|work=usatoday.com}}</ref> Examples of such citizens include users of [[Ushahidi]] during the [[2007\u201308 Kenyan crisis|2007 disputed Kenyan election]] and protesters in the [[Arab Spring]] movements who used media to document repression of protests. Currently, the digital divide is a subject of academic debate as access to the internet has increased in these developing countries, but the place in which it is accessed (work, home, public library, etc.) has a significant effect on how such access will be used, if even in a manner related to citizenry. Recent scholarship has correlated the desire to be technologically proficient with greater belief in computer access equity, and thus, digital citizenship (Shelley, et al.).\n\nOn the other side of the divide, one example of a highly-developed digital technology program in a wealthy state is the [[e-Residency of Estonia]]. This form of digital residency allows both citizens and non-citizens of the state to pursue business opportunities in a digital business environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e-resident.gov.ee/become-an-e-resident/|title=e-Residency Benefits {{!}} Digital Nomad, Freelancer, Startup Company|website=e-Residency|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> The application is simple; residents can fill out a form with their passport and photograph alongside the reason for applying. Following a successful application, the \"e-residency\" will allow them to register a company, sign documents, make online banking declarations, and file medical prescriptions online, though they will be tracked through financial footprints. The project plans to cover over 10 million e-residents by 2025 and {{as of|2019|04|lc=y|post=,}} there were over 54,000 participants from over 162 countries that have expressed an interest, contributing millions of dollars to the country's economy and assisting in access to any public service online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ninaangelovska/2019/04/25/estonias-e-residency-contributed-e14m-to-its-economy-e-residency-2-0-will-be-a-true-forerunner/|title=Estonia's E-Residency Contributed \u20ac14M To Its Economy--'E-Residency 2.0 Will Be A True Forerunner'|last=Angelovska|first=Nina|website=Forbes|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> Other benefits include hassle-free administration, lower business costs, access to the European Union market, and a broad range of e-services. Though the programme is designed for entrepreneurs, Estonia hopes to value transparency and resourcefulness as a cause for other companies to implement similar policies domestically.\n\nNonetheless, Estonia's e-Residency system has been subject to criticism. Many have pointed out that [[tax treaties]] within their own countries will play a major role in preventing this idea from spreading to more countries. Another risk is politically for governments to sustain \"funding and legislative priorities across different coalitions of power.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kotka|first=Taavi|date=September 2015|title=Estonian e-Residency: Redefining the Nation-State in the Digital Era|url=https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/materials/publications/14883/workingpaperno3kotkavargaskorjus.pdf|journal=Cyber Studies Programme}}</ref> Most importantly, the threat of [[cyberattack]]s may disrupt the seemingly optimal idea of having a platform for eIDs, as Estonia suffered its own massive cyberattack in 2007 by Russian [[hacktivism|hacktivists]]. Today, the protection of digital services and databases is essential to national security, and many countries are still hesitant to take the next step forward to promote a new system that will change the scale of politics with all its citizens.\n\n== Other forms of digital divide ==\nWithin developed countries, the digital divide, other than economic differences, is attributed to educational levels. A study conducted by the United States [[National Telecommunications and Information Administration]] determined that the gap in computer usage and internet access widened 7.8% and 25% between those with the most and least education, and it has been observed that those with college degrees or higher are 10 times more likely to have internet access at work when compared with those with only a high school education.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bezuidenhout|first=Louise M.|last2=Leonelli|first2=Sabina|last3=Kelly|first3=Ann H.|last4=Rappert|first4=Brian|date=2017-08-01|title=Beyond the digital divide: Towards a situated approach to open data|journal=Science and Public Policy|volume=44|issue=4|pages=464\u2013475|doi=10.1093/scipol/scw036|issn=0302-3427}}</ref>\n\nA digital divide often extends along specific racial lines as well. The difference in computer usage grew by 39.2% between White and Black households and by 42.6% between White and Hispanic households only three years ago.{{when?|date=March 2020}} Race can also affect the number of computers at school, and as expected, gaps between racial groups narrow at higher income levels while widening among households at lower economic levels. [[Racial disparities in education|Racial disparities]] have been proven to exist irrespective of income, and in a cultural study to determine reasons for the divide other than income, in accordance to the Hispanic community, computers were seen as a luxury, not a need. Participants collectively stated that computer activities isolated individuals and took away valuable time from family activities. In the African-American community, it was observed that they historically have had negative encounters with technological innovations, and with Asian-Americans, education was emphasized, and thus, there was a larger number of people who embraced the rise in [[Innovation|technological advances.]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dijk|first=Jan|date=August 2017|title=Digital Divide Research, Achievements, and Shortcomings|journal=Poetics|pages=34}}</ref>\n\nAn educational divide also takes place as a result of differences in the use of daily technology. In a report analyzed by the [[ACT (test)|ACT]] Center for Equity in Learning, \"85% of respondents reported having access to anywhere from two to five devices at home. The remaining one percent of respondents reported having access to no devices at home.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moore|first=Raeal|date=August 2018|title=The Digital Divide and Educational Equity|url=https://www.act.org/content/dam/act/unsecured/documents/R1698-digital-divide-2018-08.pdf|journal=ACT Center for Equity in Learning}}</ref> For the 14% of respondents with one device at home, many of them reported the need to share these devices with other household members, facing challenges that are often overlooked. The data all suggests that wealthier families have access to more devices. In addition, out of the respondents that only used one device at home, 24% of them lived in rural areas, and over half reported that this one device was a smartphone; this could make completing schoolwork assignments more difficult. The ACT recommended that underserved students need access to more devices and higher-quality networks, and educators should do their best to ensure that students can find as many electronic materials through their phones to not place a burden on family plans. \n\n==Engagement of youth==\n[[File:Inclusion Convention.jpg|thumb|At the 2018 Institutional Convention, Shola Mos-Shogbamimu, founder of the Convention, discusses the role of digital media in preventing the spread of sexual harassment and what measures can be taken to stop the spread of negativity in youth.]]\nA recent survey revealed that teenagers and young adults spend more time on the internet than watching TV. This has raised a number of concerns about how internet use could impact cognitive abilities.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mills |first1=Kathryn |title=Possible Effects of Internet Use on Cognitive Development in Adolescence |journal=Media and Communication |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=4 |doi=10.17645/mac.v4i3.516 |year=2016}}</ref> According to a study by Wartella et al., teens are concerned about how digital technologies may have an impact on their health.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wartella |first1=Ellen |last2=Rideout |first2=Vicky |last3=Montague |first3=Heather |last4=Beaudoin-Ryan |first4=Leanne |last5=Lauricella |first5=Alexis |title=Teens, Health and Technology: A National Survey |journal=Media and Communication |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=13 |doi=10.17645/mac.v4i3.515 |year=2016}}</ref> Digital youth can generally be viewed as the test market for the next generation's digital content and services. Sites such as [[Myspace]] and [[Facebook]] have come to the fore in sites where youth participate and engage with others on the internet. However, due to the lack of popularity of MySpace in particular, more young people are turning to websites such as [[Snapchat]], [[Instagram]], and [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/11/03/health/teens-tweens-media-screen-use-report/|title=Teens spend 9 hours a day using media, report says |first=Kelly |last=Wallace|work=CNN|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> It was reported that teenagers spend up to nine hours a day online, with the vast majority of that time spent on social media websites from mobile devices, contributing to the ease of access and availability to young people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.socialmediatoday.com/marketing/how-much-time-do-people-spend-social-media-infographic|title=How Much Time Do People Spend on Social Media? [Infographic]|work=Social Media Today|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> Vast amounts of money are spent annually to research the demographic by hiring psychologists, sociologists and anthropologists in order to discover habits, values and fields of interest.\n\nParticularly in the United States, \"Social media use has become so pervasive in the lives of American teens that having a presence on a social network is almost synonymous with being online; 95% of all teens ages 12-17 are now online and 80% of those online teens are users of social media sites\".<ref>\"[http://www.pewinternet.org/2011/11/09/teens-kindness-and-cruelty-on-social-network-sites/ How American Teens Navigate the New World of 'digital Citizenship']\". Pew Research Center's Internet & American Life Project. Web. 23 Nov. 2011.</ref>{{Update inline|date=March 2020}} However, movements such as these appear to benefit strictly those wishing to advocate for their business towards youth. The critical time when young people are developing their civic identities is between the ages 15\u201322. During this time they develop three attributes, civic literacy, civic skills and civic attachment, that constitute civic engagement later reflected in political actions of their adult lives.\n\nFor youth to fully participate and realize their presence on the internet, a quality level of reading comprehension is required. \"The average government web site, for example, requires an eleventh-grade level of reading comprehension, even though about half of the U.S. population reads at an eighth-grade level or lower\".<ref name=\"mossberger-digital-citizenship\">{{cite book|title=Digital Citizenship - The Internet, Society & Participation|last1=Mossberger|first1=Karen|last2=Tolbert|first2=Caroline J.|last3=McNeal|first3=Ramona S. |author-link2=Caroline Tolbert|date=October 2007|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|isbn=978-0262633536}}</ref> So despite the internet being a place irrespective of certain factors such as race, religion, and class, education plays a large part in a person's capacity to present themselves online in a formal manner conducive towards their citizenry. Concurrently, education also affects people's motivation to participate online.\n\nStudents should be encouraged to utilize technology with responsibility and ethical digital citizenship promoted. Education on harmful viruses and other [[malware]] must be emphasized to protect resources. A student can be a successful digital citizen with the help of educators, parents, and school counselors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationworld.com/a_tech/responsible-student-technology-use.shtml|title=Help Kids Become Responsible Digital Citizens|publisher=educationworld.com}}</ref>\n\n==Limits on the use of data==\nInternational [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]] guidelines state that \"personal data should be relevant to the purposes for which they are to be used, and to the extent necessary for those purposes should be accurate, complete, and kept up to date\". Article 8 prevents subjects to certain exceptions. Meaning that certain things cannot be published online revealing race, ethnicity, religion, political stance, health, and sex life. in the United States, this is enforced generally by the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC)- but very generally. For example, the FTC brought an action against Microsoft for failing to properly protect customers' personal information.<ref>[http://docs.law.gwu.edu/facweb/dsolove/Digital-Person/text/Digital-Person-CH1.pdf ''The Digital Person - Technology and Privacy in the Information Age'' - Chapter 1]</ref> In addition, many have described the United States as being in a [[cyberwarfare|cyberwar]] with Russia, and several Americans have credited Russia to their country's downfall in transparency and declining trust in the government. With several foreign users posting anonymous information through social media in order to gather a following, it is difficult to understand whom to target and what affiliation or root cause they may have of performing a particular action aimed to sway public opinion.\n\nThe FTC does play a significant role in protecting the digital citizen. However, individuals' public records are increasingly useful to the government and highly sought after. This material can help the government detect a variety of crimes such as fraud, drug distribution rings, terrorist cells. it makes it easier to properly profile a suspected criminal and keep an eye on them. Although there are a variety of ways to gather information on an individual through credit card history, employment history, and more, the internet is becoming the most desirable information gatherer thanks to its fa\u00e7ade of security and the amount of information that can be stored on the internet. [[Internet anonymity|Anonymity]] has proven to be very rare online as [[Internet service provider|ISP]]s can keep track of an individual's activity online.<ref>[http://docs.law.gwu.edu/facweb/dsolove/Digital-Person/text/Digital-Person-CH9.pdf ''The Digital Person - Technology and Privacy in the Information Age'' - Chapter 9]</ref> Furthermore, an open internet as delegated by a state's government is necessary to instill a sense of trust, legitimacy, and participation in the state's citizenry. [[WikiLeaks]] represents an occurrence where particular political actors have criticized and taken citizen action toward revealing the government's unnecessary clandestine activity online. As stated by the a representative from the ''World Heritage Encyclopedia'', \"The benefit of transparency isn't just catching red-handed bastards. It's also about collaborating and coming together with a more engaged citizenry,\" and many critics have stated that the process in doing so will still take several years.\n\n==Three principles of digital citizenship==\nDigital citizenship is a term used to define the appropriate and responsible use of technology among users. Three principles were developed by Mark Ribble to teach digital users how to responsibly use technology to become a digital citizen: respect, educate, and protect.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.iste.org/explore/articleDetail?articleid=535|title=Digital citizenship is more important than ever|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref> Each principle contains three of the nine elements of digital citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalcitizenship.net/nine-elements.html|title=Nine Elements|website=Digital Citizenship|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref>\n# '''Respect:''' the elements of etiquette, access, and law are used to respect other digital users.\n# '''Educate:''' the elements of literacy, communication, and commerce are used to learn about the appropriate use of the digital world.\n# '''Protect:''' the elements of rights and responsibilities, security, and health and wellness are used to remain safe in the digital and non-digital world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iste.org/explore/Lead-the-way/Digital-citizenship-is-more-important-than-ever?articleid=535|title=Digital citizenship is more important than ever {{!}} ISTE|website=www.iste.org|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\nWithin these three core principles, there are nine elements to also be considered in regards to digital citizenship. According to digitalcitizenship.net, these nine theme include:<ref>[http://www.digitalcitizenship.net/nine-elements.html Nine Themes of Digital Citizenship], digitalcitizenship.net</ref>\n\n#'''Digital access''': This is perhaps one of the most fundamental blocks to being a digital citizen. However, due to socioeconomic status, location, and other disabilities, some individuals may not have digital access. Recently, schools have been becoming more connected with the internet, often offering computers, and other forms of access. This can be offered through kiosks, community centers, and open labs. This most often is associated with the digital divide and factors associated with such. Digital access is available in many remote countries via cyber caf\u00e9s and small coffee shops.<ref>[http://www.iste.org/docs/excerpts/DIGCI2-excerpt.pdf Digital Citizenship in Schools - Excerpt]</ref>\n#'''[[Digital commerce]]''': This is the ability for users to recognize that much of the economy is regulated online. It also deals with the understanding of the dangers and benefits of online buying, using credit cards online, and so forth. As with the advantages and legal activities- there is also dangerous activities such as illegal downloads, gambling, drug deals, pornography, plagiarism, and so forth.\n#'''Digital communication''': This element deals with understanding the variety of online communication mediums such as email, instant messaging, Facebook messenger, the variety of apps, and so forth. There is a standard of etiquette associated with each medium.\n#'''[[Digital literacy]]''': This deals with the understanding of how to use various digital devices. For example, how to properly search for something on a search engine versus a database. How to use various online logs. Oftentimes many educational institutions will help form an individual's digital literacy.\n#'''[[Etiquette in technology|Digital etiquette]]''': As discussed in the third element, digital communication, this is the expectation that various mediums require a variety of etiquette. Certain mediums demand more appropriate behavior and language than others.\n#'''Digital law''': This is where enforcement occurs for illegal downloads, plagiarizing, hacking, creating viruses, sending spam, identity theft, [[cyberbullying]], and so forth.\n#'''Digital rights and responsibilities''': This is the set of rights digital citizens have such as privacy and free speech.\n#'''Digital health''': Digital citizens must be aware of the physical stress placed on their bodies by internet usage. They must be aware to not become overly dependent on the internet causing problems such as eye strain, headaches, and stress.\n#'''Digital security''': This simply means that citizens must take measures to be safe by practicing using secure passwords, virus protection, backing up data, and so forth.\n\n== Digital citizenship in education ==\nAccording to Mike Ribble, an author who has worked on the topic of digital citizenship for more than a decade, digital access is the first element that is prevalent in today's educational curriculum. He cited a widening gap between the impoverished and the wealthy, as 41% of African Americans and Hispanics use computers in the home when compared to 77% of white students. Other crucial digital elements include digital commerce, digital communication, digital literacy, and digital etiquette. He also emphasized that educators must understand that technology is important for all students, not just those who already have access to it, in order to decrease the digital divide that currently exists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://choraltech.wordpress.com/nine-elements-of-digital-citizenship-mike-ribble/|title=Nine Elements of Digital Citizenship \u2013 Mike Ribble|date=2017-09-10|website=Choraltech|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in research brought up by [[Common Sense Media]], approximately six out of 10 US K-12 teachers used some type of digital citizenship curriculum, and seven out of ten taught some sort of competency skill utilizing digital citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://d1e2bohyu2u2w9.cloudfront.net/education/sites/default/files/tlr_component/common_sense_education_digital_citizenship_research_backgrounder.pdf|title=Teaching Digital Citizenship In Today's World|last=Steyer|first=Jim|date=Summer 2019|website=Common Sense K-12 Digital Citizenship Curriculum|url-status=live}}</ref> Many of the sections that these teachers focused in on included hate speech, cyberbullying, and digital drama. A problem with digital technology that still exists is that over 35% of students were observed to not possess the proper skills to critically evaluate information online, and these issues and statistics increased as the grade levels rose. Online videos such as those found on YouTube and Netflix have been used approximately by 60% of the K-12 teachers in classrooms, while educational tools such as Microsoft Office and Google G Suite have been used by around half of the teachers. Social media was used the least, at around 13% in comparison to other digital methods of education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/sites/default/files/uploads/research/2019-educator-census-inside-the-21st-century-classroom_1.pdf|title=The Common Sense Census: Inside the 21st-Century Classroom |last1=Vega |first1=Vanessa |first2=Michael B. |last2=Robb |date=2019 |website=Common Sense Media |url-status=live}}</ref> When analyzing the social class differences between schools, it was found that Title I schools were more likely to utilize digital citizenship curricula than teachers in more affluent schools.\n\nIn the past two years, there has been a major shift to move students from digital citizenship to digital leadership in order to make a greater impact on online interactions. Though digital citizens take a responsible approach to act ethically, digital leadership is a more proactive approach, encompassing the \"use of internet and social media to improve the lives, well-being, and circumstances of others\" as part of one's daily life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachthought.com/the-future-of-learning/moving-students-from-digital-citizenship-to-digital-leadership/|title=Moving Students From Digital Citizenship To Digital Leadership|date=2018-11-19|website=TeachThought|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> On February 2018, after the Valentine's Day shooting in [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|Parkland, Florida]], students became dynamic digital citizens, using social media and other web platforms to engage proactively on the issue and push back against cyberbullies and misinformation. Students from [[Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School]] specifically rallied against gun violence, engaging in live tweeting, texting, videoing, and recording the attack as it happened, utilizing onside digital tools to not only witness what was happening at the time but to allow the world to witness it as well. This allowed the nation to see and react, and as a result, students built a webpage and logo for their new movement.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dillenbourg|first=Pierre|date=2016-06-01|title=The Evolution of Research on Digital Education|journal=International Journal of Artificial Intelligence in Education|volume=26|issue=2|pages=544\u2013560|doi=10.1007/s40593-016-0106-z|issn=1560-4306}}</ref> They gave interviews to major media outlets and at rallies and protects and coordinated a nationwide march online on March 24 against elected officials at meetings and town halls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iste.org/explore/Digital-citizenship/Students-use-grief,-passion,-technology-to-create-a-movement|title=Students use grief, passion, technology to create a movement {{!}} ISTE|website=iste.org|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> The idea of this shift in youth is to express empathy beyond one's self, and moving to seeing this self in the digital company of others.\n\nNonetheless, several critics state that just as empathy can be spread to a vast number of individuals, hatred can be spread as well. Though the United Nations and groups have been establishing fronts against hate speech, there is no legal definition of hate speech used internationally, and more research needs to be done on its impact.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guterres|first=Antonio|date=May 2019|title=United Nations Strategy and Plan of Action on Hate Speech|url=https://www.un.org/en/genocideprevention/documents/UN%20Strategy%20and%20Plan%20of%20Action%20on%20Hate%20Speech%2018%20June%20SYNOPSIS.pdf|journal=United Nations}}</ref>\n\nAlong with educational trends, there are overlapping goals of digital citizenship education, and they include:<ref>[http://digcit.us/ About Digital Citizenship Conversations], digcit.us</ref>\n\n#'''[[Digital footprint]]:''' An acknowledgment that posting and receiving information online can be tracked, customized, and marketed for users to click and follow. Not only the internet use but individuals' digital footprints can lead to both beneficial and negative outcomes, but the ability to manage one's digital footprints can be a sub-part of digital literacy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Micheli|first=Marina|date=June 2018|title=Digital Footprints: An Emerging Dimension of Digital Inequality|journal=Journal of Information Communication and Ethics in Society|pages=7}}</ref> Digital footprints do not simply consist of the active participation of content production as well as sharing of ideas on different media sites, but they can also be generated by other internet users (both active and passive forms of digital participation).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://net-ref.com/white-paper-fostering-digital-citizenship-in-the-classroom/|title=Digital Natives - Fostering Digital Citizenship in the Classroom|last=NetRef|date=2016-04-04|website=NetRef|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> Examples of digital footprints includes liking, favoriting, following, or commenting on a certain online content creation, or other data can be found by searching through history, purchases, and searches.\n#'''Digital literacy:''' Almost twenty years ago, Gilster (1997) defined [[digital literacy]] as \"the ability to understand and use information in multiple formats from a wide range of sources when it is presented via computers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Digital Literacy for the 21st Century|last=Casey|first=Paul|publisher=Information Resources Management Association, US|date=January 2017}}</ref> Digital literacy includes the locating and consumption of content online, the creation of content, and the way that this content is communicated amongst a group of people.\n#'''Information literacy:''' The American Library Association defines [[information literacy]] as the overall ability for an individual to target information that is valuable, being able to find it, evaluate it, and utilize it. This can be through information creation, research, scholarly conversations, or simply plugging in keywords into a search engine.\n#'''Copyright, intellectual property respect, attribution:''' By knowing who published sources and whether or not content creation is credible, users can be better educated as to what and what not to believe when engaging in digital participation.\n#'''Health and wellness:''' A healthy community allows for an interactive conversation to take place between educated citizens who are knowledgeable about their environment.\n#'''Empowering student voice, agency, advocacy:''' Utilizing nonprofits as well as government-affiliated organizations in order to empower students to speak up for policy changes that need to be made. Currently, more than 10 different [[mobile applications]] aim to allow students the opportunity to speak up and advocate for rights online.\n#'''Safety, security and privacy:''' Addressing freedoms extended to everyone in a digital world and the balance between the [[right to privacy]] and the safety hazards that go along with it. This area of digital citizenship includes the assistance of students to understand when they are provided the right opportunities, including the proper access to the internet and products that are sold online. It is on the part of educators to assist students in understanding that it is crucial to protect others online.\n#'''Character education and ethics:''' Knowing that ethically speaking, everyone will come with different viewpoints online and it is crucial to remain balanced and moral in [[Targeted advertising|online behavior]].\n#'''Parenting:''' Emphasizing the efforts of educators, many want to continue preaching rules and policies addressing issues related to the online world. Cyberbullying, sexting, and other negative issues that are brought up are regulated by the School Resource Officers and other school counsel.\n\nAltogether, nine of these facets contribute to one another in the development of a healthy and effective education for digital technology and communication.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Civic technology]]\n* [[E-government]]\n* [[Open government]]\n* [[Service design]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/take-the-fbis-safe-online-surfing-internet-challenge Take the Safe Online Surfing Internet Challenge] ([[FBI]])\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Digital Citizen}}\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:Digital technology]]\n[[Category:Internet governance]]\n[[Category:Information revolution]]\n[[Category:Digital divide]]\n[[Category:Internet ethics]]\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n[[Category:Youth-led media]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_citizen"}
{"title_page": "Walter Horsford", "text_new": "{{Infobox murderer\n| name        = Walter Horsford\n| image_name     = \n| image_size     = \n| image_caption  = \n| birth_date  = <!-- {{birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} if still living, use {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = 28 June 1898<!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date is first, birth date is second -->\n| death_place = [[Cambridge]] prison\n| cause          = Hanging\n| motive          =\n| charge         = \n| victims     = \n| conviction     = Murder\n| penalty        = Death\n| status         = \n| occupation     = Farmer\n| spouse         = \n| parents        =\n| children       =\n}}\n'''Walter Horsford''' was a murderer executed in June 1898 for poisoning his cousin Annie Holmes with strychnine.<ref name=cnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/history/death-penalty-execution-list-cambridge-15661672|date=13 January 2018|title=\"The 25 people executed in Cambridge since 1802|author=Nicola Gwyer|publisher=Cambridge News}}</ref><ref name=mus>{{cite web|url=https://www.stneotsmuseum.org.uk/articles/walter-horsford-and-the-case-of-the-st-neots-poisoning|title=Walter Horsford and the case of the St Neots poisoning|publisher=St Neots Museum}}</ref> He was the first person to be executed in [[Cambridge]] following the end of [[public execution]], and a dedicated building was constructed for his hanging.<ref name=sinners>{{cite book|title=The Little Book of Cambridgeshire|chapter=Sinners|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XyVnDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|publisher=The History Press|year=2018}}</ref> His conviction was notable for relying solely on circumstantial evidence.<ref name=Butte>{{cite news|work=The Butte Miner|date=30 October 1914|page=4|title=The Great Trials of History - The Trial of Walter Horsford}}</ref>\n\n==Murder of Annie Holmes==\nIn 1897 Horsford, aged 26, was a well-off farmer living in [[Spaldwick]]. He was in an intimate relationship with his cousin, Annie Holmes, a widow with three children. In October of that year, Horsford married another cousin of his, Bessie Mash. Shortly after this marriage, Holmes left Spaldwick and lodged in an inn in [[St Neots]]. In December she wrote to Horsford claiming she was pregnant.<ref name=Butte />\n\nOn 7 January 1898 Holmes received a postal packet from Horsford, and went to bed. An hour later her daughter heard Holmes screaming and found her in agony. Holmes died within a few minutes of a doctor arriving. At an inquest the following day Horsford stated he had not written to Holmes nor seen her since she left. When medical evidence pointed to strychnine poisoning, the police searched her bedroom and found two packets. One contained 30 grains of strychnine with the words \"one dose, take as told\" and the other was empty with \"take in a little water, it is quite harmless\" written on it. On 10 January Horsford was arrested for perjury at the inquest, and later that day further arrested for murder.<ref name=Butte /><ref>{{cite book|title=Bitter Nemesis: The Intimate History of Strychnine|author=John Buckingham|year=2007|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GoAUn74q-k4C&pg=PA254|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|ISBN=9781420053159|page=254}}</ref>\n\nThe trial took place on 2 June 1898. At the trial it was stated that the impression of handwriting on the packages could be traced on a blotter on a desk in Horsford's home. Horsford had also purchased strychnine from a local chemist on 28 December 1897, claiming he was overrun with rats, and signed the register with his name.<ref name=Lloyd30Jan />\n\nThe jury did not retire but returned a guilty verdict immediately after the judge's summing up. Horsford was sentenced to death and executed on 28 June in Cambridge prison.<ref name=Butte />\n\n==Other murders==\nHorsford was suspected of three other murders. The first was his former fianc\u00e9e Fanny James who died in 1890 after claiming she had become pregnant, and after receiving a letter from Horsford. According to her family her symptoms were consistent with [[strychnine]] poisoning. However the inquest at the time recorded a verdict of death through eating a hearty meal.<ref name=Lloyd30Jan>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27277561/lloyds_horsford/|title=St Neots Tragedy|date=30 January 1898|page=13|work=[[Lloyd's Weekly Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref name=Ipsw>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27278224/|title=The St Neots Poisoner|date=1 July 1898|page=5|work=The Ipswich Journal}}</ref> The second was a \"girl from Peterborough\" with whom he had been intimate, and who died after receiving a letter from him.<ref name=Ipsw /> The third case involved a man with the surname James who was a relative of Fanny James. Horsford supplied the usual beer to a group of men after working a day threshing wheat. He took James aside and gave him an extra quart, and he died in agony later that night. The inquest verdict recorded death from [[sunstroke]], apparently without seeing the body.<ref name=Guard30Jun>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27277855/horsford_other_victims/|title=The murders by Walter Horsford|date=30 June 1898|page=12|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name=Ipsw />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://gallery.nen.gov.uk/gallery1466-yhgfl.html Prisoner Case Studies: Walter Horsford -  Gallery]\n\n{{crime-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:People executed by the United Kingdom by hanging]]\n[[Category:Poisoners]]\n[[Category:Strychnine poisoning]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox murderer\n| name        = Walter Horsford\n| image_name     = \n| image_size     = \n| image_caption  = \n| birth_date  = <!-- {{birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} if still living, use {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = 28 June 1898<!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date is first, birth date is second -->\n| death_place = [[Cambridge]] prison\n| cause          = Hanging\n| motive          =\n| charge         = \n| victims     = \n| conviction     = Murder\n| penalty        = Death\n| status         = \n| occupation     = Farmer\n| spouse         = \n| parents        =\n| children       =\n}}\n'''Walter Horsford''' was a murderer executed in June 1898 for poisoning his cousin Annie Holmes with strychnine.<ref name=cnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/history/death-penalty-execution-list-cambridge-15661672|date=13 January 2018|title=\"The 25 people executed in Cambridge since 1802|author=Nicola Gwyer|publisher=Cambridge News}}</ref><ref name=mus>{{cite web|url=https://www.stneotsmuseum.org.uk/articles/walter-horsford-and-the-case-of-the-st-neots-poisoning|title=Walter Horsford and the case of the St Neots poisoning|publisher=St Neots Museum}}</ref> He was the first person to be executed in [[Cambridge]] following the end of [[public execution]], and a dedicated building was constructed for his hanging.<ref name=sinners>{{cite book|title=The Little Book of Cambridgeshire|chapter=Sinners|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XyVnDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|publisher=The History Press|year=2018}}</ref> His conviction was notable for relying soley on circumstantial evidence.<ref name=Butte>{{cite news|work=The Butte Miner|date=30 October 1914|page=4|title=The Great Trials of History - The Trial of Walter Horsford}}</ref>\n\n==Murder of Annie Holmes==\nIn 1897 Horsford, aged 26, was a well-off farmer living in [[Spaldwick]]. He was in an intimate relationship with his cousin, Annie Holmes, a widow with three children. In October of that year, Horsford married another cousin of his, Bessie Mash. Shortly after this marriage, Holmes left Spaldwick and lodged in an inn in [[St Neots]]. In December she wrote to Horsford claiming she was pregnant.<ref name=Butte />\n\nOn 7 January 1898 Holmes received a postal packet from Horsford, and went to bed. An hour later her daughter heard Holmes screaming and found her in agony. Holmes died within a few minutes of a doctor arriving. At an inquest the following day Horsford stated he had not written to Holmes nor seen her since she left. When medical evidence pointed to strychnine poisoning, the police searched her bedroom and found two packets. One contained 30 grains of strychnine with the words \"one dose, take as told\" and the other was empty with \"take in a little water, it is quite harmless\" written on it. On 10 January Horsford was arrested for perjury at the inquest, and later that day further arrested for murder.<ref name=Butte /><ref>{{cite book|title=Bitter Nemesis: The Intimate History of Strychnine|author=John Buckingham|year=2007|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GoAUn74q-k4C&pg=PA254|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|ISBN=9781420053159|page=254}}</ref>\n\nThe trial took place on 2 June 1898. At the trial it was stated that the impression of handwriting on the packages could be traced on a blotter on a desk in Horsford's home. Horsford had also purchased strychnine from a local chemist on 28 December 1897, claiming he was overrun with rats, and signed the register with his name.<ref name=Lloyd30Jan />\n\nThe jury did not retire but returned a guilty verdict immediately after the judge's summing up. Horsford was sentenced to death and executed on 28 June in Cambridge prison.<ref name=Butte />\n\n==Other murders==\nHorsford was suspected of three other murders. The first was his former fiancee Fanny James who died in 1890 after claiming she had become pregnant, and after receiving a letter from Horsford. According to her family her symptoms were consistent with [[strychnine]] poisoning. However the inquest at the time recorded a verdict of death through eating a hearty meal.<ref name=Lloyd30Jan>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27277561/lloyds_horsford/|title=St Neots Tragedy|date=30 January 1898|page=13|work=[[Lloyd's Weekly Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref name=Ipsw>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27278224/|title=The St Neots Poisoner|date=1 July 1898|page=5|work=The Ipswich Journal}}</ref> The second was a \"girl from Peterborough\" with whom he had been intimate, and who died after receiving a letter from him.<ref name=Ipsw /> The third case involved a man with the surname James who was a relative of Fanny James. Horsford supplied the usual beer to a group of men after working a day threshing wheat. He took James aside and gave him an extra quart, and he died in agony later that night. The inquest verdict recorded death from [[sunstroke]], apparently without seeing the body.<ref name=Guard30Jun>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27277855/horsford_other_victims/|title=The murders by Walter Horsford|date=30 June 1898|page=12|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name=Ipsw />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://gallery.nen.gov.uk/gallery1466-yhgfl.html Prisoner Case Studies: Walter Horsford -  Gallery]\n\n{{crime-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:People executed by the United Kingdom by hanging]]\n[[Category:Poisoners]]\n[[Category:Strychnine poisoning]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: fiancee \u2192 fianc\u00e9e, soley \u2192 solely", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Horsford"}
