{"title_page": "Urke Nachalnik", "text_new": "[[File:Urke Nachalnik.jpg|thumb|estimated to 1935, in Poland]]\n'''Urke Nachalnik''' ({{lang-yi|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05e7\u05e2 \u05e0\u05d0\u05db\u05d0\u05dc\u05e0\u05d9\u05e7}}) (June, 1897 \u2013 November 11, 1939).\n\nItzchak Baruch Farbarowicz, better known by his literary name Urke Nachalnik, a Yeshiva boy who was born to a well to do Jewish family in [[Wizna]], (a village  near the town of [[\u0141om\u017ca]], [[Poland]]), became a criminal and then a self made author and ended his life heroically on November 11 of 1939 as a leader of a small underground unit{{Citation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source; different sources claim Nachalnik was executed following saving the Tora from the burning synagogue and/or hiding the guns. No data on the underground activity at the time.|date=December 2012}} that hid Tora scrolls from destruction. The memoir of Calel Perechodnik claims that Nachalnik was among the first three victims at Otwock: he was forced to dig his own grave and then was shot along with Perechodnik's brother-in-law Wolf and Gershon Randoninski. They were buried in a Jewish cemetery and their remains were later exhumed. \n\nHis books and stories were published in [[Polish language|Polish]] and [[Yiddish]], his native tongue, and made into theater plays and serialized in newspapers.\n\nLikewise, numerous books and articles about Polish gangsters before the Second World War include sections about Urke Nachalnik. A biographical film shown in the [[Discovery Historia]] TV channel was made about him.\n\n== Books ==\nMenshen on a morgen, Polish title: Ludzie bez jutra, Wydawnictwo Herkules, Warszawa 1938;\n\n\u017byciorys w\u0142asny przest\u0119pcy\n\n\u017bywe grobowce, 1934.\n\nMilosc przest\u0119pcy\n\u05de\u05d9\u05d9\u05df \u05dc\u05e2\u05d1\u05e0\u05e1\u05d5\u05d5\u05e2\u05d2 : \u05e4\u05d5\u05df \u05d3\u05e2\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4 \u05d0\u05d5\u05df \u05ea\u05e4\u05d9\u05e1\u05d4 - \u05d1\u05d9\u05d6 \u05e6\u05d5 \u05d3\u05e2\u05e8 \u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05e2\u05e8\u05d0\u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\n\n\u05d0\u05d4\u05d1\u05d4 \u05d5\u05e0\u05e7\u05de\u05d4 : \u05e8\u05d5\u05de\u05df\n\nMayn lebens\u1e7feg : fun der yeshive un tfise biz tsu der li\u1e6dera\u1e6dur\n\n== External links ==\n* \"[http://www.gutstein.net/wizna/urke1.htm Urke Nachalnik],\" famous Polish gangster, turned noted author, who was born in Wizna, at ''Wizna, Poland'' website\n* [http://viaf.org/viaf/20088813/ Works]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nachalnik, Urke}}\n[[Category:Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Poland-bio-stub}}\n{{Crime-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Urke Nachalnik.jpg|thumb|estimated to 1935, in poland]]\n'''Urke Nachalnik''' ({{lang-yi|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05e7\u05e2 \u05e0\u05d0\u05db\u05d0\u05dc\u05e0\u05d9\u05e7}}) (June, 1897 \u2013 November 11, 1939).\n\nItzchak Baruch Farbarowicz, better known by his literary name Urke Nachalnik, a Yeshiva boy who was born to a well to do Jewish family in [[Wizna]], (a village  near the town of [[\u0141om\u017ca]], [[Poland]]), became a criminal and then a self made author and ended his life heroically on November 11 of 1939 as a leader of a small underground unit{{Citation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source; different sources claim Nachalnik was executed following saving the Tora from the burning synagogue and/or hiding the guns. No data on the underground activity at the time.|date=December 2012}} that hid Tora scrolls from destruction. The memoir of Calel Perechodnik claims that Nachalnik was among the first three victims at Otwock: he was forced to dig his own grave and then was shot along with Perechodnik's brother-in-law Wolf and Gershon Randoninski. They were buried in a Jewish cemetery and their remains were later exhumed. \n\nHis books and stories were published in [[Polish language|Polish]] and [[Yiddish]], his native tongue, and made into theater plays and serialized in newspapers.\n\nLikewise, numerous books and articles about Polish gangsters before the Second World War include sections about Urke Nachalnik. A biographical film shown in the [[Discovery Historia]] TV channel was made about him.\n\n== Books ==\nMenshen on a morgen, Polish title: Ludzie bez jutra, Wydawnictwo Herkules, Warszawa 1938;\n\n\u017byciorys w\u0142asny przest\u0119pcy\n\n\u017bywe grobowce, 1934.\n\nMilosc przest\u0119pcy\n\u05de\u05d9\u05d9\u05df \u05dc\u05e2\u05d1\u05e0\u05e1\u05d5\u05d5\u05e2\u05d2 : \u05e4\u05d5\u05df \u05d3\u05e2\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4 \u05d0\u05d5\u05df \u05ea\u05e4\u05d9\u05e1\u05d4 - \u05d1\u05d9\u05d6 \u05e6\u05d5 \u05d3\u05e2\u05e8 \u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05e2\u05e8\u05d0\u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\n\n\u05d0\u05d4\u05d1\u05d4 \u05d5\u05e0\u05e7\u05de\u05d4 : \u05e8\u05d5\u05de\u05df\n\nMayn lebens\u1e7feg : fun der yeshive un tfise biz tsu der li\u1e6dera\u1e6dur\n\n== External links ==\n* \"[http://www.gutstein.net/wizna/urke1.htm Urke Nachalnik],\" famous Polish gangster, turned noted author, who was born in Wizna, at ''Wizna, Poland'' website\n* [http://viaf.org/viaf/20088813/ Works]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nachalnik, Urke}}\n[[Category:Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Poland-bio-stub}}\n{{Crime-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: poland \u2192 Poland", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urke_Nachalnik"}
{"title_page": "Douglas Wright (murderer)", "text_new": "'''Douglas Franklin Wright''' (March 25, 1940 &ndash; September 6, 1996) was an American [[Serial killer]] and the first [[Capital punishment in Oregon|criminal executed in Oregon]] by lethal injection.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Murders==\nHe was sentenced to death on October 11, 1993 for luring three homeless men to a remote area of [[Wasco County, Oregon|Wasco County]] on the [[Warm Springs Indian Reservation]] with a false promise of work, and then killing them. Wright later admitted killing a fourth man, Anthony Nelson, a [[Makah people|Makah Indian]]. If Wright had not quit his appeal process, he would have been tried before a federal court in the Nelson case, because killing a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] on an [[Indian reservation]] is a federal crime, under the [[Major Crimes Act]].\n\nShortly before his execution, Wright confessed to the abduction and murder of [[Portland, Oregon]] 10-year-old Luke Tredway, committed in 1984.<ref name=\"defe\">{{cite web |url=http://www.crimevictimsunited.org/issues/repeatoffendersdata.htm |title=Crime Victims United of Oregon Repeat offenders}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060616183816/http://www.oregon.gov/DOC/PUBAFF/cap_punishment/history.shtml Oregon Department of Corrections]\n* [http://www.clarkprosecutor.org/html/death/usexecute.htm U.S. Executions Since 1976]\n* [http://www.crimevictimsunited.org/issues/repeatoffendersdata.htm Crime Victims United Repeat Offenders]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Douglas}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Oregon]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Oregon]]\n[[Category:People executed by Oregon by lethal injection]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Douglas Franklin Wright''' (March 25, 1940 &ndash; September 6, 1996) was an american [[Serial killer]] and the first [[Capital punishment in Oregon|criminal executed in Oregon]] by lethal injection.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Murders==\nHe was sentenced to death on October 11, 1993 for luring three homeless men to a remote area of [[Wasco County, Oregon|Wasco County]] on the [[Warm Springs Indian Reservation]] with a false promise of work, and then killing them. Wright later admitted killing a fourth man, Anthony Nelson, a [[Makah people|Makah Indian]]. If Wright had not quit his appeal process, he would have been tried before a federal court in the Nelson case, because killing a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] on an [[Indian reservation]] is a federal crime, under the [[Major Crimes Act]].\n\nShortly before his execution, Wright confessed to the abduction and murder of [[Portland, Oregon]] 10-year-old Luke Tredway, committed in 1984.<ref name=\"defe\">{{cite web |url=http://www.crimevictimsunited.org/issues/repeatoffendersdata.htm |title=Crime Victims United of Oregon Repeat offenders}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060616183816/http://www.oregon.gov/DOC/PUBAFF/cap_punishment/history.shtml Oregon Department of Corrections]\n* [http://www.clarkprosecutor.org/html/death/usexecute.htm U.S. Executions Since 1976]\n* [http://www.crimevictimsunited.org/issues/repeatoffendersdata.htm Crime Victims United Repeat Offenders]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Douglas}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Oregon]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[