{"title_page": "Jhabua nuns rape case", "text_new": "The '''Jhabua nuns rape case''' refers to the [[gang rape]] of four [[nuns]] in the [[Jhabua district]] of [[Madhya Pradesh]] in India on September 23, 1998 by tribal men.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6a84b4.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Politics by Other Means: Attacks Against Christians in India|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Around 18-26 men barged their way into the Ashram where the nuns lived and ransacked the entire ashram and some of the men gang raped the nuns.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.rediff.com/news/1998/sep/28jhab.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT: Syed Firdaus Ashraf reports from the MP village where three nuns were raped last week|website=m.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mahmood, Tahir, 1941-|title=Minorities Commission : minor role in major affairs|date=2001|publisher=Pharos Media & Pub|isbn=81-7221-018-3|edition=1st|location=New Delhi|pages=119|oclc=48508180}}</ref> \n\n== Incident ==\nThe nuns came from [[Tamil Nadu]] came to the Nawapura village in the predominantly tribal, Jhabua District at October 11,1997 to set up a Medical Clinic at the Preetisharan Ashram. Three of them were aged between 25-30 and the fourth one was aged over thirty. They soon made the village their home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/mirror-now/crime/article/madhya-pradesh-nuns-rape-case-after-21-years-gang-rape-accused-arrested-by-police/377339|title=Madhya Pradesh nuns' rape case: After 21 years, gang-rape accused arrested by police|website=www.timesnownews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The four nuns lived alone in the ashram which was looked after by two watchmen. The in-charge of the ashram was a priest, who is also their nearest neighbor, lived 500 meters away. The area also lacked street lights and its becomes entirely dark after evening.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt night, about 2 a.m on 23rd September, a group of men came to the ashram and requested the nuns to come with them claiming that a some children at a nearby village were ill. The nuns told them to call the watchmen, who were supposed to guard the ashram were asleep at the residence of the priest in-charge as the priest went to the town of [[Dahod]] for some work. The men started to force their way in by trying to break through the fold-able metal grill outside the main door. Realizing their intentions, the nuns blew whistles to get the attention of the watchmen who were asleep half a kilometer away. The men managed to break through the metal grill, the main door and to the one of the rooms the nuns locked themselves in.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Catholics protest against gang-rape of nuns|date=September 24, 1998|work=The Statesman|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The men vandalized and ransacked the entire premises, gold and silver ornaments including approximately 20,000 rupees cash was reportedly stolen.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWhen the attackers started to leave, some men stayed behind and told the others that they would join them later and later and then dragged the nuns outside the ashram and took turns to rape them. According to the police, the fourth nun was not raped because she appeared older and got beaten up for trying to stop the rape.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> While the runs stated that all four of them were raped.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/rape-of-the-innocents/206323|title=Rape Of The Innocents {{!}} Outlook India Magazine|last=|first=|date=|website=www.outlookindia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\n== Aftermath ==\nThe [[Chief Minister Of Madhya Pradesh|Chief minister of Madhya Pradesh]], [[Digvijaya Singh|Digvijay Singh]] visited the village and hinted that the attack was a plot by [[Hindutva]] groups against the Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/madhya-pradesh-jhabua-nun-rape/|title=MP: After 21 Yrs Of Jhabua Nuns Gang-Rape Case, Police Arrest Absconding Accused|last=Indian|first=The Logical|date=2019-03-06|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> He also related the incident with the chasing away of the Muslims in Godhra, Gujarat by the militant organization [[Vishva Hindu Parishad|Vishwa Hindu Parishad]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[Jhabua]] court issued a warrant against [[Digvijay Singh (politician)|Digvijay Singh]] then state chief minister and 14 others for alleged remarks on the 1998 Jhabua nuns rape case accusing Hindutva organisations of being involved in the incident, following a civil defamation suit filed by a local lawyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/sep/28jhab.htm|title=I never thought something like this could happen in our village. The nuns were so good to us|publisher=Rediff}}</ref> A [[Bhopal]] court cancelled the warrant after Digvijay appeared and furnished a surety bond for Rs. 5,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/12/27/stories/2003122711491300.htm|title=Warrant against Digvijay cancelled|publisher=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India|date=27 December 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19980930/27350804.html|title=Two held in MP nuns rape case|publisher=The Indian Express}}</ref> \n\n[[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) leader [[Uma Bharathi]] claimed that 12 of those who raped the Christian nuns were themselves tribal Christians, later [[L. K. Advani]] made the same statement in the Parliament.<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19981216/35050064.html Don't give communal colour to atrocities, warn ministers] Indian Express - 16 December 1998</ref> However, five days after the incident, the local [[Superintendent of police (India)|Superintendent of police]](SP) arrested 15 men and the nuns identified all of them. The SP reported that none of the arrested tribals were Christian.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=The politics behind anti Christian violence : a compilation of investigation committee reports into acts of violence against the Christian minorities|date=2006|publisher=Media House|others=Puniyani, Ram.|isbn=81-7495-237-3|location=Delhi|pages=486|oclc=182969294}}</ref> It is also reported that only 6 families in the two villages are Christians.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Investigations ==\nThe most widely spoken theory among the tribals is that a tribal man named Samna had problem with the nuns, paid two local gangs for the assault on the mission. Locals claimed that the man had fallen in love with one of the nuns and was upset when she repulsed him.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nThe crime reportedly obtained communal and political color after the former BJP [[Member of parliament|Member of the Parliament]] and VHP leader, [[Baikunth Lal Sharma|Baikunt Lal Sharma]] justified the gang-rape as the result of \"the anger of patriotic, angry Hindus\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/1998/oct/12jhab.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT: NCW demands judicial inquiry into nuns' rape|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Bauman|first=Chad M.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DoFxBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|title=Pentecostals, Proselytization, and Anti-Christian Violence in Contemporary India|date=2015-02-02|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-026631-8|location=|pages=170|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA fact-finding team of the [[National Commission for Women]] (NCW) visited the district and said that the episode is not just a case of rape, robbery and molestation, but points to a larger conspiracy. The NCW pointed out that the tribals were never known to rape women. They came across a report of a man owing the nuns some money and getting angry when asked to pay. The NCW also reported that the villagers depended on the nuns for informal education and medical help because of the lack of government services in the area.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nCongress MP, [[Kantilal Bhuria|KantiLal Bhuriya]] accused the BJP for aiding communal elements infiltrating Jhabua from Gujarat and Maharashtra.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/rape-of-the-innocents/206323|title=Rape Of The Innocents {{!}} Outlook India Magazine|last=|first=|date=|website=outlookindia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThe President of the Madhya Pradesh Christians Association, Indra Iyengar said that another catholic mission was attacked by vandals just miles away from the Nawapura village and Bajrang Dal members attacked another mission and uprooted it's fence. She also said that \"3 attacks within a span of 5 days shows that someone has a hidden agenda.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/states/story/19981012-political-parties-politicise-attacks-on-christian-community-in-madhya-pradesh-827175-1998-10-12|title=Political parties politicise attacks on Christian community in Madhya Pradesh|last=October 12|first=N. K. Singh|last2=October 12|first2=1998 ISSUE DATE|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05|last3=April 5|first3=1998UPDATED|last4=Ist|first4=2013 13:04}}</ref>\n\n== Convictions ==\nOn April 2001, Seventeen men were convicted of the crimes and sentenced to life imprisonment by the district and sessions court. The men sentenced were  Daru Mansingh,\u00a0Khemraj,\u00a0Pidiya,\u00a0Pappu,\u00a0Kenu,\u00a0 Chatra, Badra,\u00a0Ruma,\u00a0Kesaria,\u00a0Kamji,\u00a0Bhurji,\u00a0Daru Dhanna,\u00a0Ramesh,\u00a0Chamna\u00a0and Bhitra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2001/apr/28rape.htm|title=rediff.com: Gang rape of nuns in MP|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/jhabua-gangrape-convict-who-jumped-parole-held-after-11-yrs-910510-2017-04-18|title=Jhabua gangrape: Convict who jumped parole held after 11 yrs|last=April 18|first=Press Trust of India|last2=April 18|first2=2017UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05|last3=Ist|first3=2017 19:10}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2017, the police re-arrested Pidia Singaria, after he escaped his [[parole]] in 2006 and escaped from police ever since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrangindia.in/article/it-took-11-years-man-who-raped-nun-finally-arrested-jhabua|title=It took 11 Years, But Man who Raped Nun Finally Arrested: Jhabua|date=2017-04-21|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=IANS|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/nun-rape-case-convict-re-arrested-after-11-years-in-mp-117041801372_1.html|title=Nun rape case convict re-arrested after 11 years in MP|date=2017-04-18|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2019, an escaped accused Kalu Limji was arrested by the police after 21 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/National/2019/03/05213245/1109283/21-years-after-Jhabua-nuns-gangrape-accused-arrested.vpf|title=21 years after Jhabua nuns' gang-rape, accused arrested|last=|first=|date=2019-03-05|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The Police reported that, of the 26 accused, 24 were arrested immediately after the incident and 13 were acquitted, while 9 were sentenced to life imprisonment by a local court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/21-years-after-jhabua-nuns-gang-rape-accused-arrested-police-2003248|title=21 Years After Jhabua Nuns' Gang-Rape, Accused Arrested: Police|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nThe militant organisation Vishwa Hindu Parishad(VHP) accused the nuns of Conversion and the organisation's secretary B. L. Sharma claimed that the incident reflected the \"anger of patriotic Hindu youth against the anti\u2011national forces\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Hindu militants justify attacks on nuns|date=September 29, 1998|work=Agence France-Presse|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=xFw6aBjJOKsC|title=Dalits and Human Rights: Dalits: the broken future|date=2005|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-8205-274-1|location=|pages=233|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe spokesperson for the Bhartiya Janata Party and the editor of ''BJP Today,'' Kanchan Gupta said, \"It's only a rape.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/indiachr/christians8-05.htm|title=V. ATTACKS ACROSS THE COUNTRY|last=|first=|date=|website=www.hrw.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nHead of the militant organization [[Bajrang Dal]], deputy head of the VHP and a former BJP member of parliament, [[Baikunth Lal Sharma|Baikunt Lal Sharma]] said that the nuns \"were asking for it.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nRajya Sabha MP [[Mabel Rebello]] said it is not a minority issue and only a women's issue.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Rape in India}}\n[[Category:Rape in India]]\n[[Category:History of Madhya Pradesh (1947\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Crime in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1998 crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in India]]\n\n\n{{crime-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Jhabua nuns rape case''' refers to the [[gang rape]] of four [[nuns]] in the [[Jhabua district]] of [[Madhya Pradesh]] in India on September 23, 1998 by tribal men.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6a84b4.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Politics by Other Means: Attacks Against Christians in India|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Around 18-26 men barged their way into the Ashram where the nuns lived and ransacked the entire ashram and some of the men gang raped the nuns.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.rediff.com/news/1998/sep/28jhab.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT: Syed Firdaus Ashraf reports from the MP village where three nuns were raped last week|website=m.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mahmood, Tahir, 1941-|title=Minorities Commission : minor role in major affairs|date=2001|publisher=Pharos Media & Pub|isbn=81-7221-018-3|edition=1st|location=New Delhi|pages=119|oclc=48508180}}</ref> \n\n== Incident ==\nThe nuns came from [[Tamil Nadu]] came to the Nawapura village in the predominantly tribal, Jhabua District at October 11,1997 to set up a Medical Clinic at the Preetisharan Ashram. Three of them were aged between 25-30 and the fourth one was aged over thirty. They soon made the village their home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/mirror-now/crime/article/madhya-pradesh-nuns-rape-case-after-21-years-gang-rape-accused-arrested-by-police/377339|title=Madhya Pradesh nuns' rape case: After 21 years, gang-rape accused arrested by police|website=www.timesnownews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The four nuns lived alone in the ashram which was looked after by two watchmen. The in-charge of the ashram was a priest, who is also their nearest neighbor, lived 500 meters away. The area also lacked street lights and its becomes entirely dark after evening.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt night, about 2 a.m on 23rd September, a group of men came to the ashram and requested the nuns to come with them claiming that a some children at a nearby village were ill. The nuns told them to call the watchmen, who were supposed to guard the ashram were asleep at the residence of the priest in-charge as the priest went to the town of [[Dahod]] for some work. The men started to force their way in by trying to break through the fold-able metal grill outside the main door. Realizing their intentions, the nuns blew whistles to get the attention of the watchmen who were asleep half a kilometer away. The men managed to break through the metal grill, the main door and to the one of the rooms the nuns locked themselves in.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Catholics protest against gang-rape of nuns|date=September 24, 1998|work=The Statesman|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The men vandalized and ransacked the entire premises, gold and silver ornaments including approximately 20,000 rupees cash was reportedly stolen.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWhen the attackers started to leave, some men stayed behind and told the others that they would join them later and later and then dragged the nuns outside the ashram and took turns to rape them. According to the police, the fourth nun was not raped because she appeared older and got beaten up for trying to stop the rape.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> While the runs stated that all four of them were raped.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/rape-of-the-innocents/206323|title=Rape Of The Innocents {{!}} Outlook India Magazine|last=|first=|date=|website=www.outlookindia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\n== Aftermath ==\nThe [[Chief Minister Of Madhya Pradesh|Chief minister of Madhya Pradesh]], [[Digvijaya Singh|Digvijay Singh]] visited the village and hinted that the attack was a plot by [[Hindutva]] groups against the Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/madhya-pradesh-jhabua-nun-rape/|title=MP: After 21 Yrs Of Jhabua Nuns Gang-Rape Case, Police Arrest Absconding Accused|last=Indian|first=The Logical|date=2019-03-06|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> He also related the incident with the chasing away of the muslims in Godhra, Gujarat by the militant organization [[Vishva Hindu Parishad|Vishwa Hindu Parishad]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[Jhabua]] court issued a warrant against [[Digvijay Singh (politician)|Digvijay Singh]] then state chief minister and 14 others for alleged remarks on the 1998 Jhabua nuns rape case accusing Hindutva organisations of being involved in the incident, following a civil defamation suit filed by a local lawyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/sep/28jhab.htm|title=I never thought something like this could happen in our village. The nuns were so good to us|publisher=Rediff}}</ref> A [[Bhopal]] court cancelled the warrant after Digvijay appeared and furnished a surety bond for Rs. 5,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/12/27/stories/2003122711491300.htm|title=Warrant against Digvijay cancelled|publisher=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India|date=27 December 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19980930/27350804.html|title=Two held in MP nuns rape case|publisher=The Indian Express}}</ref> \n\n[[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) leader [[Uma Bharathi]] claimed that 12 of those who raped the Christian nuns were themselves tribal Christians, later [[L. K. Advani]] made the same statement in the Parliament.<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19981216/35050064.html Don't give communal colour to atrocities, warn ministers] Indian Express - 16 December 1998</ref> However, five days after the incident, the local [[Superintendent of police (India)|Superintendent of police]](SP) arrested 15 men and the nuns identified all of them. The SP reported that none of the arrested tribals were Christian.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=The politics behind anti Christian violence : a compilation of investigation committee reports into acts of violence against the Christian minorities|date=2006|publisher=Media House|others=Puniyani, Ram.|isbn=81-7495-237-3|location=Delhi|pages=486|oclc=182969294}}</ref> It is also reported that only 6 families in the two villages are Christians.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Investigations ==\nThe most widely spoken theory among the tribals is that a tribal man named Samna had problem with the nuns, paid two local gangs for the assault on the mission. Locals claimed that the man had fallen in love with one of the nuns and was upset when she repulsed him.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nThe crime reportedly obtained communal and political color after the former BJP [[Member of parliament|Member of the Parliment]] and VHP leader, [[Baikunth Lal Sharma|Baikunt Lal Sharma]] justified the gang-rape as the result of \"the anger of patriotic, angry Hindus\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/1998/oct/12jhab.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT: NCW demands judicial inquiry into nuns' rape|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Bauman|first=Chad M.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DoFxBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|title=Pentecostals, Proselytization, and Anti-Christian Violence in Contemporary India|date=2015-02-02|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-026631-8|location=|pages=170|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA fact-finding team of the [[National Commission for Women]] (NCW) visited the district and said that the episode is not just a case of rape, robbery and molestation, but points to a larger conspiracy. The NCW pointed out that the tribals were never known to rape women. They came across a report of a man owing the nuns some money and getting angry when asked to pay. The NCW also reported that the villagers depended on the nuns for informal education and medical help because of the lack of government services in the area.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nCongress MP, [[Kantilal Bhuria|KantiLal Bhuriya]] accused the BJP for aiding communal elements infiltrating Jhabua from Gujarat and Maharashtra.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/rape-of-the-innocents/206323|title=Rape Of The Innocents {{!}} Outlook India Magazine|last=|first=|date=|website=outlookindia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThe President of the Madhya Pradesh Christians Association, Indra Iyengar said that another catholic mission was attacked by vandals just miles away from the Nawapura village and Bajrang Dal members attacked another mission and uprooted it's fence. She also said that \"3 attacks within a span of 5 days shows that someone has a hidden agenda.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/states/story/19981012-political-parties-politicise-attacks-on-christian-community-in-madhya-pradesh-827175-1998-10-12|title=Political parties politicise attacks on Christian community in Madhya Pradesh|last=October 12|first=N. K. Singh|last2=October 12|first2=1998 ISSUE DATE|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05|last3=April 5|first3=1998UPDATED|last4=Ist|first4=2013 13:04}}</ref>\n\n== Convictions ==\nOn April 2001, Seventeen men were convicted of the crimes and sentenced to life imprisonment by the district and sessions court. The men sentenced were  Daru Mansingh,\u00a0Khemraj,\u00a0Pidiya,\u00a0Pappu,\u00a0Kenu,\u00a0 Chatra, Badra,\u00a0Ruma,\u00a0Kesaria,\u00a0Kamji,\u00a0Bhurji,\u00a0Daru Dhanna,\u00a0Ramesh,\u00a0Chamna\u00a0and Bhitra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2001/apr/28rape.htm|title=rediff.com: Gang rape of nuns in MP|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/jhabua-gangrape-convict-who-jumped-parole-held-after-11-yrs-910510-2017-04-18|title=Jhabua gangrape: Convict who jumped parole held after 11 yrs|last=April 18|first=Press Trust of India|last2=April 18|first2=2017UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05|last3=Ist|first3=2017 19:10}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2017, the police re-arrested Pidia Singaria, after he escaped his [[parole]] in 2006 and escaped from police ever since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrangindia.in/article/it-took-11-years-man-who-raped-nun-finally-arrested-jhabua|title=It took 11 Years, But Man who Raped Nun Finally Arrested: Jhabua|date=2017-04-21|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=IANS|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/nun-rape-case-convict-re-arrested-after-11-years-in-mp-117041801372_1.html|title=Nun rape case convict re-arrested after 11 years in MP|date=2017-04-18|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2019, an escaped accused Kalu Limji was arrested by the police after 21 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/National/2019/03/05213245/1109283/21-years-after-Jhabua-nuns-gangrape-accused-arrested.vpf|title=21 years after Jhabua nuns' gang-rape, accused arrested|last=|first=|date=2019-03-05|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The Police reported that, of the 26 accused, 24 were arrested immediately after the incident and 13 were acquitted, while 9 were sentenced to life imprisonment by a local court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/21-years-after-jhabua-nuns-gang-rape-accused-arrested-police-2003248|title=21 Years After Jhabua Nuns' Gang-Rape, Accused Arrested: Police|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nThe militant organisation Vishwa Hindu Parishad(VHP) accused the nuns of Conversion and the organisation's secretary B. L. Sharma claimed that the incident reflected the \"anger of patriotic Hindu youth against the anti\u2011national forces\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Hindu militants justify attacks on nuns|date=September 29, 1998|work=Agence France-Presse|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=xFw6aBjJOKsC|title=Dalits and Human Rights: Dalits: the broken future|date=2005|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-8205-274-1|location=|pages=233|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe spokesperson for the Bhartiya Janata Party and the editor of ''BJP Today,'' Kanchan Gupta said, \"It's only a rape.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/indiachr/christians8-05.htm|title=V. ATTACKS ACROSS THE COUNTRY|last=|first=|date=|website=www.hrw.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nHead of the militant organization [[Bajrang Dal]], deputy head of the VHP and a former BJP member of parliament, [[Baikunth Lal Sharma|Baikunt Lal Sharma]] said that the nuns \"were asking for it.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nRajya Sabha MP [[Mabel Rebello]] said it is not a minority issue and only a women's issue.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Rape in India}}\n[[Category:Rape in India]]\n[[Category:History of Madhya Pradesh (1947\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Crime in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1998 crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in India]]\n\n\n{{crime-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: muslims \u2192 Muslims, Parliment \u2192 Parliament", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jhabua_nuns_rape_case"}
{"title_page": "Internet homicide", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of killing in which victim and perpetrator met online}}\n{{Homicide}}\n\n'''Internet homicide''' refers to killing in which victim and perpetrator met online, in some cases having known each other previously only through the Internet.<ref>''Psychiatric mental health nursing'', Katherine M. Fortinash, Patricia A. Holoday-Worret, 2007 - Page 509, definition: \"Internet Homicide: Luring a person from a chat room to an actual meeting. Can turn deadly.\"</ref><ref name=\"napavalley.edu\">http://www.napavalley.edu/Projects/189/Chapter_022_4th_ed__handout.pdf{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Napa Valley College teaching text: Chapter 22, definition: \"Internet Homicide: Luring a person from a chat room to an actual meeting. May turn deadly.\"</ref><ref name=dee-morris>''Killers on the Web: True Stories of Internet Cannibals, Murderers and Sex Criminals'' by Christopher Berry-Dee and Steven Morris, John Blake Publishing, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-84454-188-1}}''</ref> Also '''Internet killer''' is an appellation found in media reports for a person who broadcasts the [[crime]] of [[murder]] online or who murders a victim met through the [[Internet]].<ref name=hypercrime/><ref>''Criminal Profiling: An Introduction to Behavioral Evidence Analysis'' by Brent E. Turvey, 2008 (\"... the Internet enables offenders to gain control of their victims.\")</ref> Depending on the venue used, other terms used in the media are '''Internet chat room killer''', '''Craigslist killer''', '''Facebook serial killer.''' Internet homicide can also be part of an [[Internet suicide pact]] or [[consensual homicide]].<ref name=\"hypercrime\">{{cite book|last=McGuire|first=Michael|title=Hypercrime: the new geometry of harm|publisher=Routledge|year=2007|isbn= 9781904385530|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXqIc2HUVmUC&printsec=frontcover#PPA90,M1}}</ref> Some commentators believe that reports on these homicides have overemphasized their connection to the Internet.<ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/leslie-harris/because-classified-ad-kil_b_190965.html|title=Because \"Classified Ad Killer\" Doesn't Have the Same Ring|last=Harris|first=Leslie|date=24 April 2009|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=2009-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== Serial killers ==\n\n[[Serial killer]]s are murderers who target three or more victims sequentially, with a \"cooling off\" period between each murder, and whose motivation for killing is largely based on [[abnormal psychology|psychological]] gratification.<ref>Holmes and Holmes, ''Contemporary'', p. 1</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Burkhalter Chmelir |first=Sandra |editor=Robert Kastenbaum |encyclopedia=Macmillan Encyclopedia of Death and Dying |title=Serial Killers |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_gx5214/is_2003/ai_n19132282?tag=content;col1 |year=2003 |publisher=Macmillan Reference USA/Thomson/Gale |volume=2 |location=New York, New York |pages=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503121235/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_gx5214/is_2003/ai_n19132282/?tag=content;col1 |archivedate=2009-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Such killers have used forms of social networking to attract victims long before the advent of the Internet. For example, between 1900 and 1914, Hungarian serial killer [[B\u00e9la Kiss]] lured his 24 victims by using [[personal ads]] published in newspapers.<ref>Greig, Charlotte (2005). Evil Serial Killers: In the Minds of Monsters. New York: Barnes & Noble. p. 194.</ref>\n\nAccording to Paul Bocj, the author of ''Cyberstalking: Harassment in the Internet Age and How to Protect Your Family'', \"The idea that a serial killer may have operated via the Internet is, understandably, one that has resulted in a great deal of public anxiety.\"<ref name=bocj>''Cyberstalking: Harassment in the Internet Age and How to Protect Your Family'' by Paul Bocj, [[Praeger Publishers]], 2004</ref> In [[Harold Schecter]]'s ''A to Z Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'', the entry for \"Internet\" reads in part: \"If the Internet has become a very useful tool for people interested in serial killers, there's some indication that it may also prove to be a resource for serial killers themselves.\"<ref name=atoz/> Maurice Godwin, a forensic consultant, argued that \"There are some sadistic predators that rely on the Mardi Gras Effect [\"the ability to hide one's identity on the Internet\"] to lure and murder repeatedly.\"<ref name=\"cybermurder\">{{cite web|url=http://lifeloom.com/III1Godwin.htm|title=CyberMurder.com|last=Godwin|first=Maurice|date=Summer 2005|work=Web Mystery Magazine|accessdate=2009-06-10|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103195620/http://lifeloom.com/III1Godwin.htm|archive-date=2013-01-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> The first serial killer known to have used the Internet to find victims was [[John Edward Robinson (serial killer)|John Edward Robinson]], who was arrested in 2000 and was referred to in ''Law Enforcement News'' as the \"USA's first Internet serial killer\" and \"the nation's first documented serial killer to use the Internet as a means of luring victims.\"<ref name=\"len063000\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.lib.jjay.cuny.edu/len/2000/06.30/ |title=Bistate task force thinks it has USA's first Internet serial killer - L.E.N. Vol. XXVI, No. 536\n |publisher=[[John Jay College of Criminal Justice]]/[[CUNY]]\n |date=June 30, 2000\n |accessdate=April 24, 2009\n |quote= John Robinson posed first as a kindly philanthropist eager to help troubled young women out of poverty, then as \"Slavemaster,\" a sadomasochist seeking like-minded partners. Now, investigators assigned to a Kansas-Missouri task force believe they may have in custody the nation's first documented serial killer to use the Internet as a means of luring victims.}}</ref><ref>''Clues from killers: serial murder and crime scene messages''. Dirk Cameron Gibson, 2004</ref>\n\n== Venues ==\n\n[[Online predator]]s, participants in [[Internet suicide|internet suicide and suicide-homicide pacts]], and internet killers may seek out victims through [[internet forum]]s, [[chat rooms]], [[listserv]]s, [[email]], [[bulletin boards]], [[social networking sites]], [[online role playing game]]s, [[online dating service]]s, [[Yahoo group]]s, or [[Usenet]].<ref>[http://www.Microsoft.com/protect/family/guidelines/predators.mspx \"Online Predators: Help minimize the risk\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824220824/http://www.microsoft.com/protect/family/guidelines/predators.mspx |date=2010-08-24 }} Microsoft Corporation, 24 September 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Williams| first = Pete| authorlink = Pete Williams (journalist)| title = MySpace, Facebook attract online predators| publisher = [[NBC News]]| date = 2006-02-03| url = http://www.nbcnews.com/id/11165576| format =| doi =| accessdate = 2006-12-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Burt| first = David| authorlink = David Burt (filtering advocate)| title = Playstation Pedophiles| publisher = Filtering Facts| date = 2009-03-16| url = http://filteringfacts.org/2009/03/16/playstation-pedophiles/| accessdate = 2009-03-16| quote = [G]aming consoles such as PlayStation, Wii, and Xbox have become Internet-enabled, interactive devices. This provides an opportunity for pedophiles to befriend and groom minors.| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090405143950/http://filteringfacts.org/2009/03/16/playstation-pedophiles/| archivedate = 2009-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Chat rooms ===\n{{further|Internet suicide}}\n\nOnline [[chatrooms]] are sometimes used by killers to meet and bait potential victims.<ref name=\"napavalley.edu\"/><ref name=\"dee-morris\"/><ref>''Psychiatric Mental Health Nursing'', Katherine M. Fortinash and Patricia A. Holoday-Worret, 2007 - Page 509, definition: \"Internet Homicide: Luring a person from a chat room to an actual meeting. Can turn deadly.\"</ref> For example, the Japanese serial murderer [[Hiroshi Maeue]] is known to have found victims by using online suicide chat rooms.<ref name=\"Suicidewebsites2005\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/suicide-websites-an-aid-to-murder/2005/08/11/1123353444920.html |title=Suicide websites an aid to murder |publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=August 12, 2005 |accessdate=April 23, 2009 }}</ref> The killer [[Lisa M. Montgomery]] is reported to have met her victim in an online chatroom for [[rat terrier]] lovers called \"Ratter Chatter.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/LAW/12/19/missouri.fetus/index.html |title=Law Center: Couple allegedly showed off kidnapped baby; Dad united with daughter |publisher=[CNN] |date=December 20, 2004 |accessdate=April 27, 2009 |quote=[Montgomery], using a fictitious name, contacted Stinnett on Wednesday through an Internet chat room about looking at rat terriers the Stinnetts sold over the Internet. [...] The Internet chat room \"Ratter Chatter,\" a haven for rat terrier lovers in cyberspace, was overwhelmed with responses from its users, many of whom indicated they knew both the victim and suspect in the case.}}</ref>\n\nOnline chatrooms are also used, in some cases, to plan consensual homicides.  For example, in 1996, a [[Maryland]] woman, [[Sharon Lopatka]], apparently agreed to be killed by [[torture]] and [[strangulation]] in a conversation with a man in an online chatroom.<ref name=\"xent.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xent.com/FoRK-archive/fall96/0523.html|title=FoRK Archive: Networking With Stranger Was Fatal|website=www.xent.com}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |title=Internet Assisted Suicide: The Story of Sharon Lopata by Rachael Bell, at CrimeLibrary.com |access-date=2009-04-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030406115408/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |archive-date=2003-04-06 |url-status=dead }} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050509031520/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |date=2005-05-09 }}\n</ref> Robert Frederick Glass pleaded guilty to killing Lopatka and later died in prison while serving his sentence. In a case that might be regarded as a quasi-consensual homicide, \"John,\" a teenage boy from [[Altrincham, England]], allegedly tricked another teenager into killing him using long conversations in an online chatroom. The other teenager, Mark, apparently believed he was being recruited by some female Secret Service agent. The suicide-by-homicide failed and on May 29, 2004 John pleaded guilty to inciting someone to murder him and was sentenced to three years supervision. Mark pleaded guilty to attempted murder and was sentenced to two years supervision. The boys were forbidden to contact each other.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/29/1085641765286.html |title=Boy used chat room to get himself killed |author=Nigel Bunyan |publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=May 30, 2004 |accessdate= April 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Online advertisements ===\n\n{{further|Lonely hearts killer}}\n\nAs an article in the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' explained in 2009, \"Long before there was a craigslist or dot-com dating, there were places where men and women who were too shy or busy to meet face to face could find romance. Calling themselves \"matrimonial bureaus,\" these organizations were known mostly as the \"lonely hearts clubs,\" and they flourished through the middle of the 20th century.\"<ref name=nydn040509>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny_crime/2009/04/05/2009-04-05_lonely_hearts_murderer.html\n |title=Lonely Hearts Murderer'\n |publisher=[[New York Daily News]]\n |date= April 5, 2009\n |accessdate=April 22, 2009\n |quote=Long before there was a craigslist or dot-com dating, there were places where men and women who were too shy or busy to meet face to face could find romance. Calling themselves \"matrimonial bureaus,\" these organizations were known mostly as the \"lonely hearts clubs,\" and they flourished through the middle of the 20th century. [...] (The article is a sidebar to a story about [[Philip Markoff]], a \"Craigslist killer\" and it describes the murders committed in 1931 by Harry F. Powers, the so-called \"Matrimonial Bureau Murderer,\" also known as \"The West Virginia Bluebeard\" and \"The Butcher of Clarksburg.\")\n| first=Mara\n| last=Bovsun\n}}</ref> It was in venues like these\u2014print media such as [[newspaper]] [[classified ads]] and [[personal ads|personal or lonely hearts club ads]]\u2014that 20th century murderers such as [[Harry Powers]], the so-called \"Matrimonial Bureau Murderer,\"<ref name=nydn040509/> and [[Harvey Carignan]], \"the Want Ad Killer\"<ref>\"The Want Ad Killer\" by Ann Rule, 1983 {{ISBN|0-451-16688-4}}. (This book is about the serial killer [[Harvey Carignan]].)</ref> met their victims.\n\nElectronic advertising has gradually replaced printed ads and the Internet is now a venue where murderers who employ a similar [[modus operandi]] can meet their victims; in Schecter's ''Encyclopedia'', the entry for \"Ads\" mentions Internet dating and the use of Internet ads by the so-called \"Internet Cannibal\" [[Armin Meiwes]].<ref name=atoz>''The A to Z Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'', [[Harold Schechter]], [[Pocket Books]], 1997, Revised Updated edition July 4, 2006 {{ISBN|978-1-4165-2174-7}}</ref> Since 2007, several accused and convicted killers have contacted victims through advertising services such as [[Craigslist]], a popular [[classified advertising]] [[website]]. These killers are sometimes referred to in the media as \"Craigslist killers\";<ref name=\"nydn040209\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2009/04/02/2009-04-02_craigslist_killer_michael_john_anderson_.html\n |title=Craigslist Killer Michael John Anderson\n |publisher=[[New York Daily News]]\n |date=April 2, 2009\n |accessdate=April 21, 2009\n |quote=April 2, 2009: New York Daily News refers to Michael John Anderson as \"Craigslist Killer.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"advocate033009\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid76839.asp \n |title=Alleged Craigslist Killer: 'Cash for Story' \n |publisher=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] \n |date=March 30, 2009 \n |accessdate=April 21, 2009 \n |quote=March 30, 2009: The Advocate refers to John Katehis as \"Craigslist Killer.\" \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403083505/http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid76839.asp \n |archivedate=April 3, 2009 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"nydn042009\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny_crime/2009/04/20/2009-04-20_massachussetts_police_arrest_suspect_in_craigslist_killer_case.html\n |title= Cops have Philip Markoff, suspected 'Craigslist Killer' of model Julissa Brisman, in custody\n |work=[[New York Daily News]]\n |date= April 20, 2009\n |accessdate=April 21, 2009\n |quote=Suspected \"Craigslist killer\" may have robbed his victims to pay off gambling debts.\n |first1=Beverly\n |last1=Ford\n |first2=Erica\n |last2=Pearson\n |first3=Helen\n |last3=Kennedy\n}}</ref> the first use of the term '''Craigslist killings''' may date to October 31, 2007, when the phrase appeared in a headline in the ''[[Saint Paul Pioneer Press]]'' in [[Minnesota]], in reference to the murder of Katherine Olson by Michael John Anderson, who was then dubbed \"the Craigslist killer\".<ref name=\"NYDailyNews_2009-04-02\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2009/04/02/2009-04-02_craigslist_killer_michael_john_anderson_.html\n |title=Craigslist killings: Police say suspect Michael John Anderson left a trail of evidence.\n |publisher=[[Saint Paul Pioneer Press]]\n |date=October 31, 2007\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n |location=New York}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, several suspected and convicted perpetrators have met their victims or solicited murder through Craigslist. Of those cases, two were convicted for crimes in the three-month period encompassing February to April 2009 and a further four were accused of crimes during the 13-month span of March 2008 through April 2009.<ref name=\"nydn040209\"/><ref name=\"advocate033009\"/><ref name=\"nydn042009\"/><ref name=bostonherald041909/> Although, by definition, Craigslist will have been the initial contact point and a killing will have taken place in order for the suspected, accused, or convicted perpetrator to be dubbed a Craigslist killer, the actual motivations of these criminals are varied. The victims' deaths may result from a [[robbery]] or a [[Human sexuality|sexual]] encounter that turned violent. Some of these perpetrators may not have intended to commit murder, but killed their victims during the course of a struggle or to prevent capture. Each case is different.\n\n=== Internet dating ===\n{{See also|Internet relationship}}\n\nAccording to Michael Largo, the author of ''Final Exits: The Illustrated Encyclopedia of How We Die'',<ref>''Final Exits: The Illustrated Encyclopedia of How We Die'' by Michael Largo, [[HarperCollins]], 2006 {{ISBN|0-06-081741-0}}, {{ISBN|978-0-06-081741-1}}</ref> \"Internet dating is becoming very popular, but since 1995, there's been[...] over 400 instances where a homicide has been related to the person that [the victim] met online.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death |title=the original |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012224908/http://videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death |archivedate=12 October 2007 }} archived from {{cite web|url=http://www.videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death#how-dangerous-is-internet-dating|title=the original|access-date=2009-04-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421145814/http://www.videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death#how-dangerous-is-internet-dating|archive-date=2009-04-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2017|reason=Video is no longer available at original or archive, and transcript states 40, not 400, instances.|talk=Internet dating section is problematically sourced}}\n\n==Criticism of the concept==\n\nSeveral legal and technology experts have questioned the idea that there is a phenomenon of Internet killings. A legal theorist pressed for an Internet angle on a murder by a journalist related that \"I asked her whether, if I called her up and asked her out on a blind date and murdered her, she would think it was a \"telephone-related murder\"?\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Turkle|first=Sherry|title=Technological Visions: The Hopes and Fears that Shape New Technologies|editor=Marita Sturken |editor2=Douglas Thomas |editor3=Sandra Ball-Rokeach|publisher=Temple University Press|year=2004 |page=[https://archive.org/details/technologicalvis00stur/page/20 20]|chapter=1: \"Spinning\" Technology|isbn= 9781592132270|url=https://archive.org/details/technologicalvis00stur|url-access=registration}}</ref> [[Leslie Harris (lawyer)|Leslie Harris]], CEO of the [[Center for Democracy and Technology]] said of the term \"Craigslist Killer\" that \"A great many of the tragic incidents that tangentially involve the Internet have little or nothing to do with the Internet itself. The Craigslist case is the latest example of that phenomenon. Craigslist is an innovative and valuable resource, which frankly, is being unfairly smeared because it is an Internet site.\"<ref name=huffpost/> The book ''Hypercrime'' argues that \"The more one looks, the more these widely circulated instances of 'cyberkilling' appear to vanish into the smoke of a 'cyberspace'.\"<ref name=hypercrime/> Susan Brenner, a professor of law and technology wrote that \"Is it a cybercrime for John to meet Mary on the Internet, correspond with her and use e-mail to lure her to a meeting where he kills her? News stories often describe conduct such as this as a cybercrime, or as 'Internet murder.' But why is this anything other than murder? We do not, for example, refer to killings orchestrated over the telephone as 'tele-murder' or by snail mail as 'mail murder.' It seems that this is not a cybercrime, that it is simply a real-world crime the commission of which happens to involve the use of computer technology,\" but she conceded that \"there may be reasons to treat conduct such as this differently and to construe it as something other than a conventional crime.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brenner|first=Susan W.|date=Fall 2004|title=Cybercrime Metrics: Old Wine, New Bottles?|journal=Virginia Journal of Law & Technology|publisher=University of Virginia|volume=9|issue=13|url=http://www.vjolt.net/vol9/issue4/v9i4_a13-Brenner.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Internet homicides ==\n{{dynamic list}}\n\nThe following individuals have been arrested and/or convicted of crimes in which police claimed that Internet services such as chat rooms and Craigslist advertisements were used to contact victims or hire a murderer. Despite sharing a similar method of contacting victims, they apparently have varied motivations. In the list below, the victims' deaths may have been premeditated, especially if the perpetrator is a [[serial killer]], but they may also have resulted from a [[robbery]], [[insurance fraud]], or a [[Human sexuality|sexual]] encounter that turned violent.\n\n* [[Robert Frederick Glass]], a computer analyst from [[North Carolina]] killed [[Sharon Lopatka]] by [[torture]] and [[strangulation]] in a case of apparent [[consensual homicide]] on October 16, 1996. Lopatka used the Internet, where she also advertised [[pornography]] related to unusual [[sexual fetish]]es, to locate Glass, who was later convicted of [[voluntary manslaughter]] for the crime.<ref name=\"xent.com\"/><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |title=Internet Assisted Suicide: The Story of Sharon Lopatka by Rachael Bell, at CrimeLibrary.com |access-date=2009-04-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030406115408/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |archive-date=2003-04-06 |url-status=dead }} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050509031520/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |date=2005-05-09 }}</ref>\n\n*In 1998, Chris Dean, a truck driver from Indiana, was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for the murder of 17-year-old Chris Marquis from Vermont. Marquis operated a [[scam]] in which he would pose as the 27-year-old proprietor of a fictional shop called the CB Shack, and offer to trade merchandise with people online. When people sent Marquis their goods, he would either not send anything back or would send something old or broken. Dean fell victim to this, built a [[pipe bomb]] and mailed it to Marquis, killing him and injuring his mother.<ref>{{cite news| title=Murder By Internet | url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/6.12/murder.html | work=Wired}}</ref>\n\n* The [[Murder of Ofir Rahum]] was a shooting attack which occurred on 17 January 2001, in which Palestinian militants from the [[Tanzim]] faction of [[Fatah]] killed 16-year-old Israeli high school student Ofir Rahum on the outskirts of [[Ramallah]]. The murder was planned and initiated by a [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] collaborator, 24-year-old Mona Jaud Awana from [[Bir Nabala]]. Awana conducted long private conversations in English with Rahum on the internet via [[ICQ]], during which she masqueraded as a Jewish Israeli girl. Awana managed to gain Rahum's confidence and to get him to meet with her in [[Jerusalem]], supposedly for romantic purposes. When he arrived for the meeting, she drove him through the border control into the Palestinian-controlled territory and towards a secluded area on the outskirts of [[Ramallah]] where Palestinian terrorists shot him at close range, with Awana standing aside and watching.<ref name=\"Wired\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/politics/law/news/2001/01/41300 |title=Israel's 'First Internet Murder' |publisher=Wired |date=19 January 2001 |author=Hershman, Tania |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025113122/http://www.wired.com/politics/law/news/2001/01/41300 |archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.gov.il/FirstGov/TopNavEng/EngSubjects/SafeSurfingEng/TeenagersEng/SSETSurfSafetly/SSETSTOphirRachum/ |title=The Murder of Ofir Rahum |access-date=2013-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022111226/http://www.gov.il/FirstGov/TopNavEng/EngSubjects/SafeSurfingEng/TeenagersEng/SSETSurfSafetly/SSETSTOphirRachum/ |archive-date=2007-10-22 |url-status=dead }} \n</ref> Awana was tried and convicted of murder,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-2799917,00.html|title=\u05d0\u05de\u05e0\u05d4 \u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d4\u05d5\u05e8\u05e9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d2\u05e8\u05d9\u05de\u05ea \u05de\u05d5\u05ea\u05d5 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d0\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05e8 \u05e8\u05d7\u05d5\u05dd|date=October 21, 2003|website=ynet}}</ref> she was sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-2813523,00.html|title=\u05de\u05d0\u05e1\u05e8 \u05e2\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd \u05dc\u05d0\u05de\u05e0\u05d4 \u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05e2\u05dc \u05e8\u05e6\u05d7 \u05d4\u05e0\u05e2\u05e8 \u05d0\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05e8 \u05e8\u05d7\u05d5\u05dd|date=November 6, 2003|website=ynet}}</ref>\n\n* The consensual murder of Bernd J\u00fcrgen Brandes by the so-called \"Internet cannibal\" [[Armin Meiwes]]; the two met at a web site called The Cannibal Cafe, where people described their fantasies of cannibalism, and where Meiwes openly advertised for a willing victim.<ref name=dee-morris/><ref name=\"BodyShock\">{{cite episode\n | title = [http://www.channel4.com/science/microsites/S/science/body/bodyshock_cannibal.html The Man Who Ate His Lover]\n | episodelink =\n | series = Body Shock (Channel 4 TV, UK)\n | serieslink =\n | airdate =\n | season =\n | number = }}</ref>\n\n* [[John Edward Robinson (serial killer)|John Edward Robinson]], known in the media as \"The Internet Slave Master\" and \"the first Internet [[serial killer]]\",<ref name=\"len063000\"/> met most of his victims in online chat rooms. He was convicted of murdering five women via blunt force trauma to the head. <ref>'Internet Slave Master' by John Glatt, 2001, St. Martin's Paperbacks. {{ISBN|0-312-97927-4}}</ref><ref>'Anyone You Want Me to Be: A True Story of Sex and Death on the Internet' by John Douglas and Stephen Singular.</ref><ref>Gribben, Mark. \"John E. Robinson, Sr.: The Slavemaster\". Crime Library. truTV.</ref>\n\n* Edward Frank Manuel, arrested in January 2003, was dubbed the \"[[Internet suicide]] [[chat room]] killer\" by [[United Press International]] and other news sources.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-96311230.html\n|title= Internet suicide chat room killer held\n|publisher=United Press International\n|date=January 10, 2003\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n* [[Lisa M. Montgomery]], also known as \"the Womb Robber\", assumed a false persona as an online chat room dog buyer in order to meet with a woman whom she already knew to be pregnant, then killed the woman in order to steal her [[fetus]] on December 17, 2004; she was convicted of murder on October 22, 2007; the baby survived.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-331709/Husband-accused-womb-robber-believed-baby-hers.html\n|title=Husband of accused 'womb robber' believed baby was hers\n|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n|location=London\n|date=December 22, 2004\n}}</ref>\n\n* [[Hiroshi Maeue]] was known as the \"Suicide Website Murderer\". According to an article in the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', this killer utilized \"suicide websites [as] an aid to murder\". Although he posed online as someone who wished to carry out [[internet suicide pact]]s, he choked his victims to death when they met in person.<ref name=\"Suicidewebsites2005\" />\n\n* Garry Francis Newman, a 50-year-old man, was convicted of the murder of 15-year-old [[Carly Ryan]] in 2007. He posed as \"Brandon\", a 20-year-old musician, and began an online relationship through online platforms MySpace and VampireFreaks.com. He eventually lured Carly to a secluded beach in the suburb of [[Port Elliot, South Australia]] where he subsequently murdered her. During his arrest, a search of his house revealed a notebook detailing some 200 online personas. In the wake of the arrest and trial of Newman, a nation wide bill, nicknamed \"Carly's Law\", was introduced to criminalise acts done using a carriage service to prepare or plan to cause harm to, procure, or engage in sexual activity with, a person under the age of 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/extraordinary-scenes-at-start-of-carly-ryan-murder-trial/news-story/b8def169051def97c91c9ad3bd648662 |title=Extraordinary scenes at start of Carly Ryan murder trial - The Advertiser}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/mother-of-murdered-teen-carly-ryan-still-fighting-online-predators-20170224-gul2bx.html |title=Mother of murdered teen Carly Ryan still fighting online predators - Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n* Thomas Montgomery, a 47-year-old married man, was convicted in 2007 of murdering a workmate in a case called the \"Internet Chatroom Murder\". He posed as \"Tommy\", a 21-year-old marine, and began an online relationship with a 17-year-old called Jessi. A workmate of his, 22-year-old Brian Barrett, subsequently began an online relationship with the same girl after Montgomery's deception was revealed, and Montgomery shot him in their work [[car park]]. \"Jessi\" was actually a middle-aged woman who had been using pictures of her daughter. A police officer said of Montgomery: \"he became a completely different person online\". Another commented that: \"It's very odd that someone would take another's life over jealousy of a person you've never laid your eyes on\".<ref>{{cite episode | title =The internet chatroom murder | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1327_assignment_2007/page13.shtml | series = Assignment (BBC World Service) | serieslink = | airdate = November 2007 | season = 2007 | number = |accessdate=10 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/politics/law/magazine/15-09/ff_internetlies|title=An IM Infatuation Turned to Romance. Then the Truth Came Out|last=Labi|first=Nadya|date=21 August 2007|work=Wired|accessdate=2009-06-10}}</ref> A documentary about this case titled ''[[Talhotblond]]'' (Jessi's screen name) was released in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1370889/|title=Talhotblond|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n\n* [[Michael John Anderson]] was convicted of murdering Katherine Olson in [[Minnesota]] in October 2007. According to an article in the Saint Paul Pioneer Press, \"The 19-year-old Savage man used Craigslist to lure Katherine Ann Olson to his home for a fictitious baby-sitting job, then shot her in the back.\"<ref name=\"nydn040209\"/><ref name=\"sppp103107\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-33331976_ITM\n |title=Craigslist Killer Michael John Anderson\n |publisher=[[Saint Paul Pioneer Press]]\n |date=October 31, 2007\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n |quote=The 19-year-old Savage man used Craigslist to lure Katherine Ann Olson to his home for a fictitious baby-sitting job, then shot her in the back, according to the criminal complaint filed Tuesday.}}</ref>\n\n*Bernard George Lamp, a 51-year-old resident of [[Troutman, North Carolina]] was charged with murder and first-degree [[kidnapping]] on March 22, 2008 in the death of a woman from [[Cornelius, North Carolina]]; according to news reports, she had \"agreed to meet the man accused of killing her after encountering him on Craigslist.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CO&s_site=charlotte&p_multi=CO&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11F98090379A4C78&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM\n |title=Warrants detail how murder victim, suspect met online, after e-mailing, they set up a meeting in person, documents say\n |publisher=[[Charlotte Observer]]\n |date= March 22, 2008\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n*Ann Marie Linscott, a 49-year-old Michigan woman, was arrested in January 2008 for soliciting murder on Craigslist, where she offered $5,000 \"for someone willing to kill the unsuspecting wife of a man she'd begun an affair with online\";<ref name=\"wjz\">{{cite web\n |url          = http://wjz.com/watercooler/craigslist.murder.for.2.638791.html\n |title        = California Woman Targeted For Murder On Craigslist\n |publisher    = [[WJZ-TV|WJZ]]\n |date         = January 26, 2008\n |accessdate   = April 23, 2009\n |quote        = Craigslist has gained some level of notoriety for ads posted by prostitutes and the killing of a Minnesota woman last year who responded to an ad for a baby sitter. However, authorities and company officials say the murder-for-hire scheme appears to be the first of its kind.\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503122954/http://wjz.com/watercooler/craigslist.murder.for.2.638791.html\n |archive-date = 2009-05-03\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> in February 2009, she was found guilty of attempted murder-for-hire and sentenced to 12 years and seven months in prison.<ref name=bostonherald041909>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/regional/view.bg?articleid=1166573\n |title=Caught up in a violent Web\n |publisher=[[Boston Herald]]\n |date= April 19, 2009\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n |quote=Law enforcement officials warn that the slaying of Julissa Brisman is far from the only violent crime linked to Craigslist.\n}}</ref>\n\n*In 2008, Hughstan Schlicker, a 15-year-old from [[Mesa, Arizona]], shot and killed his father, Ted Schlicker. Hughstan had threatened suicide in a [[Myspace]] post, and Ted\u2014worried that his son might kill himself\u2014banned Hughstan from the Internet, angering him. Ted also had hidden the family [[shotgun]]. However, after Hughstan [[Truancy|played hooky]] from school, he found the gun hidden in a shed, waited at home for his father, and then shot him in the back of the head as his father entered the house. Hughstan then planned to kill himself but was unable to follow through.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.kpho.com/news/15511792/detail.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-07-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614055615/http://www.kpho.com/news/15511792/detail.html |archive-date=2011-06-14 |url-status=dead }} \n</ref>\n\n*Christian Grotheer, known as \"Germany's First Internet Killer,\" confessed to two murders in 2009. According to an article in the [[Daily Telegraph]], he admitted to \"murdering women he met in online chat rooms.\"<ref>\n{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/15/germanys-first-internet-k_n_158102.html\n|title='Germany's First Internet Killer,' Christian G, Admits Murdering Women He Met Online\n|publisher=Huffington Post\n|date=January 15, 2009\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/4243030/Internet-killer-admits-murdering-women-he-met-in-online-chat-rooms.html\n|title='Internet killer' admits murdering women he met in online chat rooms\n|publisher=[[London Telegraph]]\n|date=January 15, 2009\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n* David Heiss, a 21-year-old German office worker, became infatuated with a British girl, Joanna Witton, 20, who along with her boyfriend [[Matthew Pyke]], 20, was an administrator of the ''[[Advance Wars series]]'' [[fansite]], Wars Central. After his advances were rebuffed, including two visits, Heiss traveled to the UK once more and stabbed Matthew Pyke to death. He was jailed for life in May 2009. A police spokesman noted that, \"While this is an extremely unusual case, one thing is clear and that is that Heiss used the internet to [[harass]] and [[Stalking|stalk]] Joanna and Matthew. He eventually found out where they lived and other information about them that enabled him to carry out his plans. We should all consider the amounts of personal information we share on web systems like MSN and on internet forums.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/5309259/Police-warn-of-internet-danger-after-office-worker-jailed-for-life-for-murder.html|title=Police warn of internet danger after office worker jailed for life for murder |date=11 May 2009|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=2009-05-13 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/8040178.stm|title=Web murderer given life sentence|date=11 May 2009|work=BBC News|accessdate=2009-05-13}}</ref>\n\n* [[John Katehis]], a teenager, was arrested and indicted for the murder of [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC radio]] news reporter [[George Weber (radio personality)|George Weber]] in New York in March 2009. The two had met through Craigslist, and journals such as ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' called the suspect an \"Alleged Craigslist Killer\".<ref name=\"advocate033009\"/><ref name=\"ktla\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ktla.com/landing_topstories/?Police-Slain-Reporter-Met-Teen-Killer-on=1&blockID=248928&feedID=1198\n |title=Police: Slain Reporter Met Teen Killer on Craigslist\n |publisher=[[KTLA]]\n |date=March 25, 2009\n |accessdate=April 20, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n* Korena Roberts was arrested in June 2009 for allegedly killing 21-year-old Heather Snively\u2014who was eight-months pregnant\u2014and her fetus, by cutting open her abdomen. They were reported to have met on through an advertisement by Roberts on Craigslist for the sale of baby clothes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.usatoday.com/ondeadline/2009/06/ore-woman-accused-of-killing-mothertobe-baby-cut-from-womb.html |work=USA Today |date=August 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610224303/http://blogs.usatoday.com/ondeadline/2009/06/ore-woman-accused-of-killing-mothertobe-baby-cut-from-womb.html |archivedate=June 10, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n*In 2009, Anthony Powell, a 28-year-old student at the [[Henry Ford Community College]] in Detroit, shot and killed fellow student, 20-year-old Asia McGowan, before fatally shooting himself. Powell had a history of [[mental illness]] and used his [[YouTube]] account to make hate videos against black women and [[atheist]]s. McGowan also had an account at YouTube. Powell became obsessed with McGowan through her account, and began [[stalking]] her on both YouTube and [[Facebook]]. He had decided that black women like McGowan were naturally [[promiscuous]], and had made videos with titles such as \"Black Women Don't Deserve Respect\", shortly before killing McGowan. Many of Powell's videos were so concerning that many YouTube users contacted the Detroit police about them.<ref>{{cite web |author=Butiwantcake |url=http://www.blogher.com/murder-asia-mcgowan |title=The Murder of Asia McGowan |publisher=BlogHer |date=2009-04-28 |accessdate=2014-04-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322003707/http://www.blogher.com/murder-asia-mcgowan |archive-date=2014-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Monday |url=http://www.whataboutourdaughters.com/2009/04/youtube-facebook-murder-black-woman-slaughtered-by-crazed-fellow-youtuber-and-facebook-stalker-detroit-police-ignored-warnings-by-youtubers/ |title=YouTube Facebook Murder: Black Woman Slaughtered by Crazed Fellow YouTuber and Facebook Stalker-Detroit Police Ignored Warnings by YouTubers |publisher=What About Our Daughters |date=2009-04-13 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mydeathspace.com/article/2009/04/11/Asia_McGowan_(20)_was_shot_and_killed_in_a_murder_suicide |title=Asia McGowan (20) was shot and killed in a murder-suicide |publisher=MyDeathSpace.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\n*[[Philip Markoff]], known as \"The Craigslist killer\" in numerous news reports, was arrested and [[indict]]ed in April 2009 for the murder of Julissa Brisman and for other attacks against women that occurred in [[Massachusetts]] and [[Rhode Island]]; he had met the women through their online advertisements in Craigslist, where they had advertised [[erotic services]].<ref name=\"nydn042009\" /> Markoff committed [[suicide]] in his jail cell on August 15, 2010, several months prior to the scheduled trial.<ref name=suicide>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/08/da_markoff_fash.html |title=DA: Markoff fashioned 'primitive scalpel' to kill himself |date=2010-08-17 |accessdate=2010-08-18 |publisher=Boston Globe |author=Finucane, Martin}}</ref>\n\n* David Russell, a UK McDonald's worker, impersonated [[Bring Me The Horizon]] singer [[Oliver Sykes]] to seduce a California woman he met on Facebook before slitting her throat and repeatedly stabbing her. Russell, 20, has been jailed for life after admitting to the kidnap and attempted murder of Maricar Benedicto, 19, whom he met online in 2010.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.smnnews.com/2011/10/05/uk-man-impersonates-bmths-oliver-sykes-jailed-for-attempted-murder-of-california-woman/ |title=UK Man Impersonates BMTH's Oliver Sykes, Jailed for Attempted Murder of California Woman |publisher=SMNnews.com |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2014-04-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716054943/http://www.smnnews.com/2011/10/05/uk-man-impersonates-bmths-oliver-sykes-jailed-for-attempted-murder-of-california-woman/ |archive-date=2015-07-16 |url-status=dead }}\n</ref>\n\n* In 2013, Richard Beasley, a 53-year-old from [[Summit County, Ohio]], was convicted and sentenced to death for luring three men to their deaths using a [[Craigslist]] ad for a non-existent job in 2011. Beasley was convicted in March of kidnapping and killing David Pauley, 51, of [[Norfolk, Virginia]]; Ralph Geiger, 56, of [[Akron, Ohio]], and Timothy Kern, 47, of [[Massillon, Ohio]]. He was also convicted of the attempted murder of Scott Davis, 49, a [[South Carolina]] man who answered the Craigslist ad and was shot in the arm while escaping after meeting Beasley and his 16 year old accomplice, Brogan Rafferty.<ref>{{cite news|last=Palmer |first=Kim |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/04/us-usa-crime-craigslist-idUSBRE9330LS20130404 |title=Ohio judge sentences convicted Craigslist killer to death |publisher=Reuters |date= April 4, 2013|accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/10/craigslist-killers-murder-story-family-breakdown|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|title=The Craigslist killers|date=10 November 2013|accessdate=10 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110114916/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/10/craigslist-killers-murder-story-family-breakdown|archive-date=2013-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2013/09/advertisement-for-murder/309435/?single_page=true|title=Murder by Craigslist|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=29 December 2013|author=Hannah Rosin|work=[[The Atlantic]]|author-link=Hannah Rosin}}</ref>\n\n*In 2013, newlywed couple [[Miranda and Elytte Barbour]] were arrested and charged with the murder of Troy LaFerrara. The Barbours allegedly met LaFerrara after he answered the couple's [[Craigslist]] ad offering \"companionship\" and conversation in exchange for payment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Draznin, Haley, Welch, Chris|first=Candiotti, Susan|title=Woman accused in Craigslist slaying tells newspaper: I've killed lots of others|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/16/justice/craigslist-thrill-killing-confession/|newspaper=CNN|date=February 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Scant evidence of satanic 'Craigslist killer' Miranda Barbour's claims of mass murder: authorities |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/newlyweds-accused-thrill-kill-craigslist-murder/story?id=21134460|newspaper=ABC News|date=December 7, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Mohney>{{cite news|title=Newlyweds Accused of Thrill-Kill Craigslist Murder|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/scant-evidence-satanic-craigslist-killer-claims-mass-murder-authorities-article-1.1619443|newspaper=NY Daily News|date=February 19, 2014|location=New York}}</ref>\n*In February 2014, [[Murder of Breck Bednar|Breck Brednar]], a 14-year-old boy from [[Redhill, Surrey]] was murdered by Lewis Daynes, an 18-year-old unemployed software engineer who groomed him online on a gaming site. Brednar was found dead in Daynes' flat in [[Grays, Essex]] and had been stabbed multiple times. Lewis Daynes was then sentenced to life imprisonment with a minimum of 25 years,\n\n*In February 2015, attorney David Messerschmitt was murdered in a hotel room in DC. According to police records, he had posted a listing on Craigslist requesting a sexual encounter, but was answered by two women who planned to rob him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/woman-charged-in-slaying-of-lawyer-once-wanted-to-be-a-police-officer/2015/04/02/b16536ea-d944-11e4-ba28-f2a685dc7f89_story.html|title=Police: Woman held in D.C. lawyer's slaying planned only to rob him|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture ==\n{{dynamic list}}\nThe theme of internet homicide has proven popular in fiction, with examples seen in books, television shows, and movies, in a number of which the murderer is referred to as \"the Internet Killer\" by other characters.\n\nThe following examples are listed by date order of publication or broadcast; three of them predate the arrest in 2000 of [[John Edward Robinson (serial killer)|John Edward Robinson]], thought by law enforcement to be \"the first Internet serial killer\":<ref name=\"len063000\"/>\n\n* The third-season episode of ''[[The X-Files]]'' titled \"[[2Shy]]\" featured as its [[monster of the week]] a fat-eating mutant named Virgil Incanto who seduced overweight women online and killed them upon meeting in real life.\n* The second season of the TV series ''[[Millennium (TV series)|Millennium]]'' featured an episode called ''The Mikado'', about a serial killer based loosely upon the [[Zodiac Killer]]. The killer would contact people on internet chat groups, kidnap them and then broadcast their death live via a [[webcam]] once the [[Web counter|site counter]] reached a certain level.\n* The fifth season of the TV series ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' featured two episodes involving Internet serial killers. The first, ''Risky Business'', was about a killer who set up a website encouraging teenagers to engage in [[auto-erotic asphyxiation]] in a particularly dangerous manner, tricking them into committing suicide. The second, ''The Internet Is Forever'', is about a serial killer who sets up hidden cameras in women's homes and strangles them to death while the whole act is being broadcast live on the web for his \"fans\" to see.\n* ''[[Strangeland (film)|Strangeland]]'' was a 1998 film written by [[Dee Snider]] about a schizophrenic sexual sadist who lures victims via the Internet, forcing them to submit to ancient tribal rituals. \"I came up with the idea of Internet crime before anybody had ever committed Internet crime,\" Snider has said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deesnider.com/index.php/news/210-strangeland-disciple-casting-call |title=Strangeland: Disciple Casting Call |publisher=Deesnider.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n* ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'', a [[television series]] [[police drama]], featured an extended multi-week storyline in May 1999 in which a character named Luke Ryland was known as \"The Internet Killer.\"\n* ''[[FeardotCom]]'' was a 2002 movie about a killer internet web site.<ref>''\"It looks like it's going to be a cheesy, senseless 'Internet killer' flick, when in reality 'Feardotcom' is a very cinematic, smart, only slightly senseless 'Internet killer' flick.\"'' {{cite web|url=http://media.www.theonlinerocket.com/media/storage/paper601/news/2002/09/06/Entertainment/Feardotcom.Dotbad-267853.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503191210/http://media.www.theonlinerocket.com/media/storage/paper601/news/2002/09/06/Entertainment/Feardotcom.Dotbad-267853.shtml |archivedate=2009-05-03 }}</ref>\n*''[[The Card Player|The Card Player (Il cartaio)]]'' was a 2004 film made in [[Italy]]; written and directed by [[Dario Argento]], it tells the story of a policewoman from [[Rome, Italy|Rome]] who teams up with a British [[Interpol]] agent to track down an internet serial killer who abducts and kills young women and broadcasts the crimes via Internet [[web cam]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0330691/plotsummary Plot summary for Il cartaio (2004) at [[IMDb]].</ref>\n* ''[[Untraceable]]'' was a 2008 [[Sony Pictures]] [[film]] starring [[Diane Lane]] in which [[FBI agent]] Jennifer Marsh was tasked with hunting down a seemingly untraceable serial killer who posted live videos of his victims on the Internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sonypictures.com/movies/untraceable/|title=Untraceable &#124; Sony Pictures|website=www.sonypictures.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.katu.com/entertainment/14237257.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504142347/http://www.katu.com/entertainment/14237257.html |archivedate=2009-05-04 }} ''The idea of the internet killer has been done before ([[Feardotcom]], [[The Card Player]])''</ref>\n* ''[[Downloading Nancy]]'' was a 2008 [[film]] starring [[Maria Bello]] in which unhappy wife Nancy Stockwell decides to end her life by meeting a man over the internet and forming a consensual agreement that he will kill her.\n* In March 2015, during the first week of ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'', host [[James Corden]] listed several dozen ways to connect with the show via social media. The list started with \"Follow me on [[Twitter]], Like me on [[Facebook]], ...\" and ended with \"or murder me on [[Craigslist]].\"\n* American Monster an [[Investigation Discovery]] television series documentary-drama episode titled: ''The Craigslist Killer'' aired: September 2017, dramatizes the serial killer Richard Beasley's online enticing of multiple men to their deaths.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Craigslist Killer {{!}} American Monster |url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/american-monster/full-episodes/the-craigslist-killer |website=www.investigationdiscovery.com |publisher=Discovery Communications, LLC. |accessdate=29 September 2018 |language=en-us |date=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=American Monster ''The Craigslist Killer'' (TV Episode 2017) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7151356/ |publisher=IMDb.com Incorporated |accessdate=29 September 2018 |date=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Assisted suicide]]\n* [[Computer crime]]\n* [[Consensual homicide]]\n* [[Internet suicide pact]]\n* [[Lonely hearts killer|Lonely hearts killer (or want-ad killer)]]\n* [[Online predator]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|journal=Slate|title=The Longform Guide to Craigslist Crime|author=Max Linsky|date=August 24, 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Internet Homicide}}\n[[Category:Internet safety]]\n[[Category:Cybercrime]]\n[[Category:Killings by type]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Type of killing in which victim and perpetrator met online}}\n{{Homicide}}\n\n'''Internet homicide''' refers to killing in which victim and perpetrator met online, in some cases having known each other previously only through the Internet.<ref>''Psychiatric mental health nursing'', Katherine M. Fortinash, Patricia A. Holoday-Worret, 2007 - Page 509, definition: \"Internet Homicide: Luring a person from a chat room to an actual meeting. Can turn deadly.\"</ref><ref name=\"napavalley.edu\">http://www.napavalley.edu/Projects/189/Chapter_022_4th_ed__handout.pdf{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Napa Valley College teaching text: Chapter 22, definition: \"Internet Homicide: Luring a person from a chat room to an actual meeting. May turn deadly.\"</ref><ref name=dee-morris>''Killers on the Web: True Stories of Internet Cannibals, Murderers and Sex Criminals'' by Christopher Berry-Dee and Steven Morris, John Blake Publishing, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-84454-188-1}}''</ref> Also '''Internet killer''' is an appellation found in media reports for a person who broadcasts the [[crime]] of [[murder]] online or who murders a victim met through the [[Internet]].<ref name=hypercrime/><ref>''Criminal Profiling: An Introduction to Behavioral Evidence Analysis'' by Brent E. Turvey, 2008 (\"... the Internet enables offenders to gain control of their victims.\")</ref> Depending on the venue used, other terms used in the media are '''Internet chat room killer''', '''Craigslist killer''', '''Facebook serial killer.''' Internet homicide can also be part of an [[Internet suicide pact]] or [[consensual homicide]].<ref name=\"hypercrime\">{{cite book|last=McGuire|first=Michael|title=Hypercrime: the new geometry of harm|publisher=Routledge|year=2007|isbn= 9781904385530|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXqIc2HUVmUC&printsec=frontcover#PPA90,M1}}</ref> Some commentators believe that reports on these homicides have overemphasized their connection to the Internet.<ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/leslie-harris/because-classified-ad-kil_b_190965.html|title=Because \"Classified Ad Killer\" Doesn't Have the Same Ring|last=Harris|first=Leslie|date=24 April 2009|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=2009-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== Serial killers ==\n\n[[Serial killer]]s are murderers who target three or more victims sequentially, with a \"cooling off\" period between each murder, and whose motivation for killing is largely based on [[abnormal psychology|psychological]] gratification.<ref>Holmes and Holmes, ''Contemporary'', p. 1</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Burkhalter Chmelir |first=Sandra |editor=Robert Kastenbaum |encyclopedia=Macmillan Encyclopedia of Death and Dying |title=Serial Killers |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_gx5214/is_2003/ai_n19132282?tag=content;col1 |year=2003 |publisher=Macmillan Reference USA/Thomson/Gale |volume=2 |location=New York, New York |pages=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503121235/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_gx5214/is_2003/ai_n19132282/?tag=content;col1 |archivedate=2009-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Such killers have used forms of social networking to attract victims long before the advent of the Internet. For example, between 1900 and 1914, Hungarian serial killer [[B\u00e9la Kiss]] lured his 24 victims by using [[personal ads]] published in newspapers.<ref>Greig, Charlotte (2005). Evil Serial Killers: In the Minds of Monsters. New York: Barnes & Noble. p. 194.</ref>\n\nAccording to Paul Bocj, the author of ''Cyberstalking: Harassment in the Internet Age and How to Protect Your Family'', \"The idea that a serial killer may have operated via the Internet is, understandably, one that has resulted in a great deal of public anxiety.\"<ref name=bocj>''Cyberstalking: Harassment in the Internet Age and How to Protect Your Family'' by Paul Bocj, [[Praeger Publishers]], 2004</ref> In [[Harold Schecter]]'s ''A to Z Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'', the entry for \"Internet\" reads in part: \"If the Internet has become a very useful tool for people interested in serial killers, there's some indication that it may also prove to be a resource for serial killers themselves.\"<ref name=atoz/> Maurice Godwin, a forensic consultant, argued that \"There are some sadistic predators that rely on the Mardi Gras Effect [\"the ability to hide one's identity on the Internet\"] to lure and murder repeatedly.\"<ref name=\"cybermurder\">{{cite web|url=http://lifeloom.com/III1Godwin.htm|title=CyberMurder.com|last=Godwin|first=Maurice|date=Summer 2005|work=Web Mystery Magazine|accessdate=2009-06-10|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103195620/http://lifeloom.com/III1Godwin.htm|archive-date=2013-01-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> The first serial killer known to have used the Internet to find victims was [[John Edward Robinson (serial killer)|John Edward Robinson]], who was arrested in 2000 and was referred to in ''Law Enforcement News'' as the \"USA's first Internet serial killer\" and \"the nation's first documented serial killer to use the Internet as a means of luring victims.\"<ref name=\"len063000\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.lib.jjay.cuny.edu/len/2000/06.30/ |title=Bistate task force thinks it has USA's first Internet serial killer - L.E.N. Vol. XXVI, No. 536\n |publisher=[[John Jay College of Criminal Justice]]/[[CUNY]]\n |date=June 30, 2000\n |accessdate=April 24, 2009\n |quote= John Robinson posed first as a kindly philanthropist eager to help troubled young women out of poverty, then as \"Slavemaster,\" a sadomasochist seeking like-minded partners. Now, investigators assigned to a Kansas-Missouri task force believe they may have in custody the nation's first documented serial killer to use the Internet as a means of luring victims.}}</ref><ref>''Clues from killers: serial murder and crime scene messages''. Dirk Cameron Gibson, 2004</ref>\n\n== Venues ==\n\n[[Online predator]]s, participants in [[Internet suicide|internet suicide and suicide-homicide pacts]], and internet killers may seek out victims through [[internet forum]]s, [[chat rooms]], [[listserv]]s, [[email]], [[bulletin boards]], [[social networking sites]], [[online role playing game]]s, [[online dating service]]s, [[Yahoo group]]s, or [[Usenet]].<ref>[http://www.Microsoft.com/protect/family/guidelines/predators.mspx \"Online Predators: Help minimize the risk\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824220824/http://www.microsoft.com/protect/family/guidelines/predators.mspx |date=2010-08-24 }} Microsoft Corporation, 24 September 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Williams| first = Pete| authorlink = Pete Williams (journalist)| title = MySpace, Facebook attract online predators| publisher = [[NBC News]]| date = 2006-02-03| url = http://www.nbcnews.com/id/11165576| format =| doi =| accessdate = 2006-12-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Burt| first = David| authorlink = David Burt (filtering advocate)| title = Playstation Pedophiles| publisher = Filtering Facts| date = 2009-03-16| url = http://filteringfacts.org/2009/03/16/playstation-pedophiles/| accessdate = 2009-03-16| quote = [G]aming consoles such as PlayStation, Wii, and Xbox have become Internet-enabled, interactive devices. This provides an opportunity for pedophiles to befriend and groom minors.| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090405143950/http://filteringfacts.org/2009/03/16/playstation-pedophiles/| archivedate = 2009-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Chat rooms ===\n{{further|Internet suicide}}\n\nOnline [[chatrooms]] are sometimes used by killers to meet and bait potential victims.<ref name=\"napavalley.edu\"/><ref name=\"dee-morris\"/><ref>''Psychiatric Mental Health Nursing'', Katherine M. Fortinash and Patricia A. Holoday-Worret, 2007 - Page 509, definition: \"Internet Homicide: Luring a person from a chat room to an actual meeting. Can turn deadly.\"</ref> For example, the Japanese serial murderer [[Hiroshi Maeue]] is known to have found victims by using online suicide chat rooms.<ref name=\"Suicidewebsites2005\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/suicide-websites-an-aid-to-murder/2005/08/11/1123353444920.html |title=Suicide websites an aid to murder |publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=August 12, 2005 |accessdate=April 23, 2009 }}</ref> The killer [[Lisa M. Montgomery]] is reported to have met her victim in an online chatroom for [[rat terrier]] lovers called \"Ratter Chatter.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/LAW/12/19/missouri.fetus/index.html |title=Law Center: Couple allegedly showed off kidnapped baby; Dad united with daughter |publisher=[CNN] |date=December 20, 2004 |accessdate=April 27, 2009 |quote=[Montgomery], using a fictitious name, contacted Stinnett on Wednesday through an Internet chat room about looking at rat terriers the Stinnetts sold over the Internet. [...] The Internet chat room \"Ratter Chatter,\" a haven for rat terrier lovers in cyberspace, was overwhelmed with responses from its users, many of whom indicated they knew both the victim and suspect in the case.}}</ref>\n\nOnline chatrooms are also used, in some cases, to plan consensual homicides.  For example, in 1996, a [[Maryland]] woman, [[Sharon Lopatka]], apparently agreed to be killed by [[torture]] and [[strangulation]] in a conversation with a man in an online chatroom.<ref name=\"xent.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xent.com/FoRK-archive/fall96/0523.html|title=FoRK Archive: Networking With Stranger Was Fatal|website=www.xent.com}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |title=Internet Assisted Suicide: The Story of Sharon Lopata by Rachael Bell, at CrimeLibrary.com |access-date=2009-04-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030406115408/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |archive-date=2003-04-06 |url-status=dead }} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050509031520/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |date=2005-05-09 }}\n</ref> Robert Frederick Glass pleaded guilty to killing Lopatka and later died in prison while serving his sentence. In a case that might be regarded as a quasi-consensual homicide, \"John,\" a teenage boy from [[Altrincham, England]], allegedly tricked another teenager into killing him using long conversations in an online chatroom. The other teenager, Mark, apparently believed he was being recruited by some female Secret Service agent. The suicide-by-homicide failed and on May 29, 2004 John pleaded guilty to inciting someone to murder him and was sentenced to three years supervision. Mark pleaded guilty to attempted murder and was sentenced to two years supervision. The boys were forbidden to contact each other.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/29/1085641765286.html |title=Boy used chat room to get himself killed |author=Nigel Bunyan |publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=May 30, 2004 |accessdate= April 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Online advertisements ===\n\n{{further|Lonely hearts killer}}\n\nAs an article in the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' explained in 2009, \"Long before there was a craigslist or dot-com dating, there were places where men and women who were too shy or busy to meet face to face could find romance. Calling themselves \"matrimonial bureaus,\" these organizations were known mostly as the \"lonely hearts clubs,\" and they flourished through the middle of the 20th century.\"<ref name=nydn040509>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny_crime/2009/04/05/2009-04-05_lonely_hearts_murderer.html\n |title=Lonely Hearts Murderer'\n |publisher=[[New York Daily News]]\n |date= April 5, 2009\n |accessdate=April 22, 2009\n |quote=Long before there was a craigslist or dot-com dating, there were places where men and women who were too shy or busy to meet face to face could find romance. Calling themselves \"matrimonial bureaus,\" these organizations were known mostly as the \"lonely hearts clubs,\" and they flourished through the middle of the 20th century. [...] (The article is a sidebar to a story about [[Philip Markoff]], a \"Craigslist killer\" and it describes the murders committed in 1931 by Harry F. Powers, the so-called \"Matrimonial Bureau Murderer,\" also known as \"The West Virginia Bluebeard\" and \"The Butcher of Clarksburg.\")\n| first=Mara\n| last=Bovsun\n}}</ref> It was in venues like these\u2014print media such as [[newspaper]] [[classified ads]] and [[personal ads|personal or lonely hearts club ads]]\u2014that 20th century murderers such as [[Harry Powers]], the so-called \"Matrimonial Bureau Murderer,\"<ref name=nydn040509/> and [[Harvey Carignan]], \"the Want Ad Killer\"<ref>\"The Want Ad Killer\" by Ann Rule, 1983 {{ISBN|0-451-16688-4}}. (This book is about the serial killer [[Harvey Carignan]].)</ref> met their victims.\n\nElectronic advertising has gradually replaced printed ads and the Internet is now a venue where murderers who employ a similar [[modus operandi]] can meet their victims; in Schecter's ''Encyclopedia'', the entry for \"Ads\" mentions Internet dating and the use of Internet ads by the so-called \"Internet Cannibal\" [[Armin Meiwes]].<ref name=atoz>''The A to Z Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'', [[Harold Schechter]], [[Pocket Books]], 1997, Revised Updated edition July 4, 2006 {{ISBN|978-1-4165-2174-7}}</ref> Since 2007, several accused and convicted killers have contacted victims through advertising services such as [[Craigslist]], a popular [[classified advertising]] [[website]]. These killers are sometimes referred to in the media as \"Craigslist killers\";<ref name=\"nydn040209\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2009/04/02/2009-04-02_craigslist_killer_michael_john_anderson_.html\n |title=Craigslist Killer Michael John Anderson\n |publisher=[[New York Daily News]]\n |date=April 2, 2009\n |accessdate=April 21, 2009\n |quote=April 2, 2009: New York Daily News refers to Michael John Anderson as \"Craigslist Killer.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"advocate033009\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid76839.asp \n |title=Alleged Craigslist Killer: 'Cash for Story' \n |publisher=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] \n |date=March 30, 2009 \n |accessdate=April 21, 2009 \n |quote=March 30, 2009: The Advocate refers to John Katehis as \"Craigslist Killer.\" \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403083505/http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid76839.asp \n |archivedate=April 3, 2009 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"nydn042009\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny_crime/2009/04/20/2009-04-20_massachussetts_police_arrest_suspect_in_craigslist_killer_case.html\n |title= Cops have Philip Markoff, suspected 'Craigslist Killer' of model Julissa Brisman, in custody\n |work=[[New York Daily News]]\n |date= April 20, 2009\n |accessdate=April 21, 2009\n |quote=Suspected \"Craigslist killer\" may have robbed his victims to pay off gambling debts.\n |first1=Beverly\n |last1=Ford\n |first2=Erica\n |last2=Pearson\n |first3=Helen\n |last3=Kennedy\n}}</ref> the first use of the term '''Craigslist killings''' may date to October 31, 2007, when the phrase appeared in a headline in the ''[[Saint Paul Pioneer Press]]'' in [[Minnesota]], in reference to the murder of Katherine Olson by Michael John Anderson, who was then dubbed \"the Craigslist killer\".<ref name=\"NYDailyNews_2009-04-02\">\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/us_world/2009/04/02/2009-04-02_craigslist_killer_michael_john_anderson_.html\n |title=Craigslist killings: Police say suspect Michael John Anderson left a trail of evidence.\n |publisher=[[Saint Paul Pioneer Press]]\n |date=October 31, 2007\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n |location=New York}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, several suspected and convicted perpetrators have met their victims or solicited murder through Craigslist. Of those cases, two were convicted for crimes in the three-month period encompassing February to April 2009 and a further four were accused of crimes during the 13-month span of March 2008 through April 2009.<ref name=\"nydn040209\"/><ref name=\"advocate033009\"/><ref name=\"nydn042009\"/><ref name=bostonherald041909/> Although, by definition, Craigslist will have been the initial contact point and a killing will have taken place in order for the suspected, accused, or convicted perpetrator to be dubbed a Craigslist killer, the actual motivations of these criminals are varied. The victims' deaths may result from a [[robbery]] or a [[Human sexuality|sexual]] encounter that turned violent. Some of these perpetrators may not have intended to commit murder, but killed their victims during the course of a struggle or to prevent capture. Each case is different.\n\n=== Internet dating ===\n{{See also|Internet relationship}}\n\nAccording to Michael Largo, the author of ''Final Exits: The Illustrated Encyclopedia of How We Die'',<ref>''Final Exits: The Illustrated Encyclopedia of How We Die'' by Michael Largo, [[HarperCollins]], 2006 {{ISBN|0-06-081741-0}}, {{ISBN|978-0-06-081741-1}}</ref> \"Internet dating is becoming very popular, but since 1995, there's been[...] over 400 instances where a homicide has been related to the person that [the victim] met online.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death |title=the original |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012224908/http://videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death |archivedate=12 October 2007 }} archived from {{cite web|url=http://www.videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death#how-dangerous-is-internet-dating|title=the original|access-date=2009-04-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421145814/http://www.videojug.com/interview/loved-to-death#how-dangerous-is-internet-dating|archive-date=2009-04-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2017|reason=Video is no longer available at original or archive, and transcript states 40, not 400, instances.|talk=Internet dating section is problematically sourced}}\n\n==Criticism of the concept==\n\nSeveral legal and technology experts have questioned the idea that there is a phenomenon of Internet killings. A legal theorist pressed for an Internet angle on a murder by a journalist related that \"I asked her whether, if I called her up and asked her out on a blind date and murdered her, she would think it was a \"telephone-related murder\"?\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Turkle|first=Sherry|title=Technological Visions: The Hopes and Fears that Shape New Technologies|editor=Marita Sturken |editor2=Douglas Thomas |editor3=Sandra Ball-Rokeach|publisher=Temple University Press|year=2004 |page=[https://archive.org/details/technologicalvis00stur/page/20 20]|chapter=1: \"Spinning\" Technology|isbn= 9781592132270|url=https://archive.org/details/technologicalvis00stur|url-access=registration}}</ref> [[Leslie Harris (lawyer)|Leslie Harris]], CEO of the [[Center for Democracy and Technology]] said of the term \"Craigslist Killer\" that \"A great many of the tragic incidents that tangentially involve the Internet have little or nothing to do with the Internet itself. The Craigslist case is the latest example of that phenomenon. Craigslist is an innovative and valuable resource, which frankly, is being unfairly smeared because it is an Internet site.\"<ref name=huffpost/> The book ''Hypercrime'' argues that \"The more one looks, the more these widely circulated instances of 'cyberkilling' appear to vanish into the smoke of a 'cyberspace'.\"<ref name=hypercrime/> Susan Brenner, a professor of law and technology wrote that \"Is it a cybercrime for John to meet Mary on the Internet, correspond with her and use e-mail to lure her to a meeting where he kills her? News stories often describe conduct such as this as a cybercrime, or as 'Internet murder.' But why is this anything other than murder? We do not, for example, refer to killings orchestrated over the telephone as 'tele-murder' or by snail mail as 'mail murder.' It seems that this is not a cybercrime, that it is simply a real-world crime the commission of which happens to involve the use of computer technology,\" but she conceded that \"there may be reasons to treat conduct such as this differently and to construe it as something other than a conventional crime.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brenner|first=Susan W.|date=Fall 2004|title=Cybercrime Metrics: Old Wine, New Bottles?|journal=Virginia Journal of Law & Technology|publisher=University of Virginia|volume=9|issue=13|url=http://www.vjolt.net/vol9/issue4/v9i4_a13-Brenner.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Internet homicides ==\n{{dynamic list}}\n\nThe following individuals have been arrested and/or convicted of crimes in which police claimed that Internet services such as chat rooms and Craigslist advertisements were used to contact victims or hire a murderer. Despite sharing a similar method of contacting victims, they apparently have varied motivations. In the list below, the victims' deaths may have been premeditated, especially if the perpetrator is a [[serial killer]], but they may also have resulted from a [[robbery]], [[insurance fraud]], or a [[Human sexuality|sexual]] encounter that turned violent.\n\n* [[Robert Frederick Glass]], a computer analyst from [[North Carolina]] killed [[Sharon Lopatka]] by [[torture]] and [[strangulation]] in a case of apparent [[consensual homicide]] on October 16, 1996. Lopatka used the Internet, where she also advertised [[pornography]] related to unusual [[sexual fetish]]es, to locate Glass, who was later convicted of [[voluntary manslaughter]] for the crime.<ref name=\"xent.com\"/><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |title=Internet Assisted Suicide: The Story of Sharon Lopatka by Rachael Bell, at CrimeLibrary.com |access-date=2009-04-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030406115408/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |archive-date=2003-04-06 |url-status=dead }} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050509031520/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/sharon_lopatka/1.html?sect=13 |date=2005-05-09 }}</ref>\n\n*In 1998, Chris Dean, a truck driver from Indiana, was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for the murder of 17-year-old Chris Marquis from Vermont. Marquis operated a [[scam]] in which he would pose as the 27-year-old proprietor of a fictional shop called the CB Shack, and offer to trade merchandise with people online. When people sent Marquis their goods, he would either not send anything back or would send something old or broken. Dean fell victim to this, built a [[pipe bomb]] and mailed it to Marquis, killing him and injuring his mother.<ref>{{cite news| title=Murder By Internet | url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/6.12/murder.html | work=Wired}}</ref>\n\n* The [[Murder of Ofir Rahum]] was a shooting attack which occurred on 17 January 2001, in which Palestinian militants from the [[Tanzim]] faction of [[Fatah]] killed 16-year-old Israeli high school student Ofir Rahum on the outskirts of [[Ramallah]]. The murder was planned and initiated by a [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] collaborator, 24-year-old Mona Jaud Awana from [[Bir Nabala]]. Awana conducted long private conversations in English with Rahum on the internet via [[ICQ]], during which she masqueraded as a Jewish Israeli girl. Awana managed to gain Rahum's confidence and to get him to meet with her in [[Jerusalem]], supposedly for romantic purposes. When he arrived for the meeting, she drove him through the border control into the Palestinian-controlled territory and towards a secluded area on the outskirts of [[Ramallah]] where Palestinian terrorists shot him at close range, with Awana standing aside and watching.<ref name=\"Wired\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/politics/law/news/2001/01/41300 |title=Israel's 'First Internet Murder' |publisher=Wired |date=19 January 2001 |author=Hershman, Tania |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025113122/http://www.wired.com/politics/law/news/2001/01/41300 |archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.gov.il/FirstGov/TopNavEng/EngSubjects/SafeSurfingEng/TeenagersEng/SSETSurfSafetly/SSETSTOphirRachum/ |title=The Murder of Ofir Rahum |access-date=2013-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022111226/http://www.gov.il/FirstGov/TopNavEng/EngSubjects/SafeSurfingEng/TeenagersEng/SSETSurfSafetly/SSETSTOphirRachum/ |archive-date=2007-10-22 |url-status=dead }} \n</ref> Awana was tried and convicted of murder,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-2799917,00.html|title=\u05d0\u05de\u05e0\u05d4 \u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d4\u05d5\u05e8\u05e9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d2\u05e8\u05d9\u05de\u05ea \u05de\u05d5\u05ea\u05d5 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d0\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05e8 \u05e8\u05d7\u05d5\u05dd|date=October 21, 2003|website=ynet}}</ref> she was sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-2813523,00.html|title=\u05de\u05d0\u05e1\u05e8 \u05e2\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd \u05dc\u05d0\u05de\u05e0\u05d4 \u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05e2\u05dc \u05e8\u05e6\u05d7 \u05d4\u05e0\u05e2\u05e8 \u05d0\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05e8 \u05e8\u05d7\u05d5\u05dd|date=November 6, 2003|website=ynet}}</ref>\n\n* The consensual murder of Bernd J\u00fcrgen Brandes by the so-called \"Internet cannibal\" [[Armin Meiwes]]; the two met at a web site called The Cannibal Cafe, where people described their fantasies of cannibalism, and where Meiwes openly advertised for a willing victim.<ref name=dee-morris/><ref name=\"BodyShock\">{{cite episode\n | title = [http://www.channel4.com/science/microsites/S/science/body/bodyshock_cannibal.html The Man Who Ate His Lover]\n | episodelink =\n | series = Body Shock (Channel 4 TV, UK)\n | serieslink =\n | airdate =\n | season =\n | number = }}</ref>\n\n* [[John Edward Robinson (serial killer)|John Edward Robinson]], known in the media as \"The Internet Slave Master\" and \"the first Internet [[serial killer]]\",<ref name=\"len063000\"/> met most of his victims in online chat rooms. He was convicted of murdering five women via blunt force trauma to the head. <ref>'Internet Slave Master' by John Glatt, 2001, St. Martin's Paperbacks. {{ISBN|0-312-97927-4}}</ref><ref>'Anyone You Want Me to Be: A True Story of Sex and Death on the Internet' by John Douglas and Stephen Singular.</ref><ref>Gribben, Mark. \"John E. Robinson, Sr.: The Slavemaster\". Crime Library. truTV.</ref>\n\n* Edward Frank Manuel, arrested in January 2003, was dubbed the \"[[Internet suicide]] [[chat room]] killer\" by [[United Press International]] and other news sources.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-96311230.html\n|title= Internet suicide chat room killer held\n|publisher=United Press International\n|date=January 10, 2003\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n* [[Lisa M. Montgomery]], also known as \"the Womb Robber\", assumed a false persona as an online chat room dog buyer in order to meet with a woman whom she already knew to be pregnant, then killed the woman in order to steal her [[fetus]] on December 17, 2004; she was convicted of murder on October 22, 2007; the baby survived.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-331709/Husband-accused-womb-robber-believed-baby-hers.html\n|title=Husband of accused 'womb robber' believed baby was hers\n|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n|location=London\n|date=December 22, 2004\n}}</ref>\n\n* [[Hiroshi Maeue]] was known as the \"Suicide Website Murderer\". According to an article in the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', this killer utilized \"suicide websites [as] an aid to murder\". Although he posed online as someone who wished to carry out [[internet suicide pact]]s, he choked his victims to death when they met in person.<ref name=\"Suicidewebsites2005\" />\n\n* Garry Francis Newman, a 50-year-old man, was convicted of the murder of 15-year-old [[Carly Ryan]] in 2007. He posed as \"Brandon\", a 20-year-old musician, and began an online relationship through online platforms MySpace and VampireFreaks.com. He eventually lured Carly to a secluded beach in the suburb of [[Port Elliot, South Australia]] where he subsequently murdered her. During his arrest, a search of his house revealed a notebook detailing some 200 online personas. In the wake of the arrest and trial of Newman, a nation wide bill, nicknamed \"Carly's Law\", was introduced to criminalise acts done using a carriage service to prepare or plan to cause harm to, procure, or engage in sexual activity with, a person under the age of 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/extraordinary-scenes-at-start-of-carly-ryan-murder-trial/news-story/b8def169051def97c91c9ad3bd648662 |title=Extraordinary scenes at start of Carly Ryan murder trial - The Advertiser}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/mother-of-murdered-teen-carly-ryan-still-fighting-online-predators-20170224-gul2bx.html |title=Mother of murdered teen Carly Ryan still fighting online predators - Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n* Thomas Montgomery, a 47-year-old married man, was convicted in 2007 of murdering a workmate in a case called the \"Internet Chatroom Murder\". He posed as \"Tommy\", a 21-year-old marine, and began an online relationship with a 17-year-old called Jessi. A workmate of his, 22-year-old Brian Barrett, subsequently began an online relationship with the same girl after Montgomery's deception was revealed, and Montgomery shot him in their work [[car park]]. \"Jessi\" was actually a middle-aged woman who had been using pictures of her daughter. A police officer said of Montgomery: \"he became a completely different person online\". Another commented that: \"It's very odd that someone would take another's life over jealousy of a person you've never laid your eyes on\".<ref>{{cite episode | title =The internet chatroom murder | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1327_assignment_2007/page13.shtml | series = Assignment (BBC World Service) | serieslink = | airdate = November 2007 | season = 2007 | number = |accessdate=10 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/politics/law/magazine/15-09/ff_internetlies|title=An IM Infatuation Turned to Romance. Then the Truth Came Out|last=Labi|first=Nadya|date=21 August 2007|work=Wired|accessdate=2009-06-10}}</ref> A documentary about this case titled ''[[Talhotblond]]'' (Jessi's screen name) was released in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1370889/|title=Talhotblond|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n\n* [[Michael John Anderson]] was convicted of murdering Katherine Olson in [[Minnesota]] in October 2007. According to an article in the Saint Paul Pioneer Press, \"The 19-year-old Savage man used Craigslist to lure Katherine Ann Olson to his home for a fictitious baby-sitting job, then shot her in the back.\"<ref name=\"nydn040209\"/><ref name=\"sppp103107\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-33331976_ITM\n |title=Craigslist Killer Michael John Anderson\n |publisher=[[Saint Paul Pioneer Press]]\n |date=October 31, 2007\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n |quote=The 19-year-old Savage man used Craigslist to lure Katherine Ann Olson to his home for a fictitious baby-sitting job, then shot her in the back, according to the criminal complaint filed Tuesday.}}</ref>\n\n*Bernard George Lamp, a 51-year-old resident of [[Troutman, North Carolina]] was charged with murder and first-degree [[kidnapping]] on March 22, 2008 in the death of a woman from [[Cornelius, North Carolina]]; according to news reports, she had \"agreed to meet the man accused of killing her after encountering him on Craigslist.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CO&s_site=charlotte&p_multi=CO&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11F98090379A4C78&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM\n |title=Warrants detail how murder victim, suspect met online, after e-mailing, they set up a meeting in person, documents say\n |publisher=[[Charlotte Observer]]\n |date= March 22, 2008\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n*Ann Marie Linscott, a 49-year-old Michigan woman, was arrested in January 2008 for soliciting murder on Craigslist, where she offered $5,000 \"for someone willing to kill the unsuspecting wife of a man she'd begun an affair with online\";<ref name=\"wjz\">{{cite web\n |url          = http://wjz.com/watercooler/craigslist.murder.for.2.638791.html\n |title        = California Woman Targeted For Murder On Craigslist\n |publisher    = [[WJZ-TV|WJZ]]\n |date         = January 26, 2008\n |accessdate   = April 23, 2009\n |quote        = Craigslist has gained some level of notoriety for ads posted by prostitutes and the killing of a Minnesota woman last year who responded to an ad for a baby sitter. However, authorities and company officials say the murder-for-hire scheme appears to be the first of its kind.\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503122954/http://wjz.com/watercooler/craigslist.murder.for.2.638791.html\n |archive-date = 2009-05-03\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> in February 2009, she was found guilty of attempted murder-for-hire and sentenced to 12 years and seven months in prison.<ref name=bostonherald041909>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/regional/view.bg?articleid=1166573\n |title=Caught up in a violent Web\n |publisher=[[Boston Herald]]\n |date= April 19, 2009\n |accessdate=April 23, 2009\n |quote=Law enforcement officials warn that the slaying of Julissa Brisman is far from the only violent crime linked to Craigslist.\n}}</ref>\n\n*In 2008, Hughstan Schlicker, a 15-year-old from [[Mesa, Arizona]], shot and killed his father, Ted Schlicker. Hughstan had threatened suicide in a [[Myspace]] post, and Ted\u2014worried that his son might kill himself\u2014banned Hughstan from the Internet, angering him. Ted also had hidden the family [[shotgun]]. However, after Hughstan [[Truancy|played hooky]] from school, he found the gun hidden in a shed, waited at home for his father, and then shot him in the back of the head as his father entered the house. Hughstan then planned to kill himself but was unable to follow through.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.kpho.com/news/15511792/detail.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-07-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614055615/http://www.kpho.com/news/15511792/detail.html |archive-date=2011-06-14 |url-status=dead }} \n</ref>\n\n*Christian Grotheer, known as \"Germany's First Internet Killer,\" confessed to two murders in 2009. According to an article in the [[Daily Telegraph]], he admitted to \"murdering women he met in online chat rooms.\"<ref>\n{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/15/germanys-first-internet-k_n_158102.html\n|title='Germany's First Internet Killer,' Christian G, Admits Murdering Women He Met Online\n|publisher=Huffington Post\n|date=January 15, 2009\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/4243030/Internet-killer-admits-murdering-women-he-met-in-online-chat-rooms.html\n|title='Internet killer' admits murdering women he met in online chat rooms\n|publisher=[[London Telegraph]]\n|date=January 15, 2009\n|accessdate=April 23, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n* David Heiss, a 21-year-old German office worker, became infatuated with a British girl, Joanna Witton, 20, who along with her boyfriend [[Matthew Pyke]], 20, was an administrator of the ''[[Advance Wars series]]'' [[fansite]], Wars Central. After his advances were rebuffed, including two visits, Heiss traveled to the UK once more and stabbed Matthew Pyke to death. He was jailed for life in May 2009. A police spokesman noted that, \"While this is an extremely unusual case, one thing is clear and that is that Heiss used the internet to [[harass]] and [[Stalking|stalk]] Joanna and Matthew. He eventually found out where they lived and other information about them that enabled him to carry out his plans. We should all consider the amounts of personal information we share on web systems like MSN and on internet forums.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/5309259/Police-warn-of-internet-danger-after-office-worker-jailed-for-life-for-murder.html|title=Police warn of internet danger after office worker jailed for life for murder |date=11 May 2009|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=2009-05-13 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/8040178.stm|title=Web murderer given life sentence|date=11 May 2009|work=BBC News|accessdate=2009-05-13}}</ref>\n\n* [[John Katehis]], a teenager, was arrested and indicted for the murder of [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC radio]] news reporter [[George Weber (radio personality)|George Weber]] in New York in March 2009. The two had met through Craigslist, and journals such as ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' called the suspect an \"Alleged Craigslist Killer\".<ref name=\"advocate033009\"/><ref name=\"ktla\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ktla.com/landing_topstories/?Police-Slain-Reporter-Met-Teen-Killer-on=1&blockID=248928&feedID=1198\n |title=Police: Slain Reporter Met Teen Killer on Craigslist\n |publisher=[[KTLA]]\n |date=March 25, 2009\n |accessdate=April 20, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n* Korena Roberts was arrested in June 2009 for allegedly killing 21-year-old Heather Snively\u2014who was eight-months pregnant\u2014and her fetus, by cutting open her abdomen. They were reported to have met on through an advertisement by Roberts on Craigslist for the sale of baby clothes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.usatoday.com/ondeadline/2009/06/ore-woman-accused-of-killing-mothertobe-baby-cut-from-womb.html |work=USA Today |date=August 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610224303/http://blogs.usatoday.com/ondeadline/2009/06/ore-woman-accused-of-killing-mothertobe-baby-cut-from-womb.html |archivedate=June 10, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n*In 2009, Anthony Powell, a 28-year-old student at the [[Henry Ford Community College]] in Detroit, shot and killed fellow student, 20-year-old Asia McGowan, before fatally shooting himself. Powell had a history of [[mental illness]] and used his [[YouTube]] account to make hate videos against black women and [[atheist]]s. McGowan also had an account at YouTube. Powell became obsessed with McGowan through her account, and began [[stalking]] her on both YouTube and [[Facebook]]. He had decided that black women like McGowan were naturally [[promiscuous]], and had made videos with titles such as \"Black Women Don't Deserve Respect\", shortly before killing McGowan. Many of Powell's videos were so concerning that many YouTube users contacted the Detroit police about them.<ref>{{cite web |author=Butiwantcake |url=http://www.blogher.com/murder-asia-mcgowan |title=The Murder of Asia McGowan |publisher=BlogHer |date=2009-04-28 |accessdate=2014-04-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322003707/http://www.blogher.com/murder-asia-mcgowan |archive-date=2014-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Monday |url=http://www.whataboutourdaughters.com/2009/04/youtube-facebook-murder-black-woman-slaughtered-by-crazed-fellow-youtuber-and-facebook-stalker-detroit-police-ignored-warnings-by-youtubers/ |title=YouTube Facebook Murder: Black Woman Slaughtered by Crazed Fellow YouTuber and Facebook Stalker-Detroit Police Ignored Warnings by YouTubers |publisher=What About Our Daughters |date=2009-04-13 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mydeathspace.com/article/2009/04/11/Asia_McGowan_(20)_was_shot_and_killed_in_a_murder_suicide |title=Asia McGowan (20) was shot and killed in a murder-suicide |publisher=MyDeathSpace.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\n*[[Philip Markoff]], known as \"The Craigslist killer\" in numerous news reports, was arrested and [[indict]]ed in April 2009 for the murder of Julissa Brisman and for other attacks against women that occurred in [[Massachusetts]] and [[Rhode Island]]; he had met the women through their online advertisements in Craigslist, where they had advertised [[erotic services]].<ref name=\"nydn042009\" /> Markoff committed [[suicide]] in his jail cell on August 15, 2010, several months prior to the scheduled trial.<ref name=suicide>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/08/da_markoff_fash.html |title=DA: Markoff fashioned 'primitive scalpel' to kill himself |date=2010-08-17 |accessdate=2010-08-18 |publisher=Boston Globe |author=Finucane, Martin}}</ref>\n\n* David Russell, a UK McDonald's worker, impersonated [[Bring Me The Horizon]] singer [[Oliver Sykes]] to seduce a California woman he met on Facebook before slitting her throat and repeatedly stabbing her. Russell, 20, has been jailed for life after admitting to the kidnap and attempted murder of Maricar Benedicto, 19, whom he met online in 2010.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.smnnews.com/2011/10/05/uk-man-impersonates-bmths-oliver-sykes-jailed-for-attempted-murder-of-california-woman/ |title=UK Man Impersonates BMTH's Oliver Sykes, Jailed for Attempted Murder of California Woman |publisher=SMNnews.com |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2014-04-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716054943/http://www.smnnews.com/2011/10/05/uk-man-impersonates-bmths-oliver-sykes-jailed-for-attempted-murder-of-california-woman/ |archive-date=2015-07-16 |url-status=dead }}\n</ref>\n\n* In 2013, Richard Beasley, a 53-year-old from [[Summit County, Ohio]], was convicted and sentenced to death for luring three men to their deaths using a [[Craigslist]] ad for a non-existent job in 2011. Beasley was convicted in March of kidnapping and killing David Pauley, 51, of [[Norfolk, Virginia]]; Ralph Geiger, 56, of [[Akron, Ohio]], and Timothy Kern, 47, of [[Massillon, Ohio]]. He was also convicted of the attempted murder of Scott Davis, 49, a [[South Carolina]] man who answered the Craigslist ad and was shot in the arm while escaping after meeting Beasley and his 16 year old accomplice, Brogan Rafferty.<ref>{{cite news|last=Palmer |first=Kim |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/04/us-usa-crime-craigslist-idUSBRE9330LS20130404 |title=Ohio judge sentences convicted Craigslist killer to death |publisher=Reuters |date= April 4, 2013|accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/10/craigslist-killers-murder-story-family-breakdown|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|title=The Craigslist killers|date=10 November 2013|accessdate=10 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110114916/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/10/craigslist-killers-murder-story-family-breakdown|archive-date=2013-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2013/09/advertisement-for-murder/309435/?single_page=true|title=Murder by Craigslist|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=29 December 2013|author=Hannah Rosin|work=[[The Atlantic]]|author-link=Hannah Rosin}}</ref>\n\n*In 2013, newlywed couple [[Miranda and Elytte Barbour]] were arrested and charged with the murder of Troy LaFerrara. The Barbours allegedly met LaFerrara after he answered the couple's [[Craigslist]] ad offering \"companionship\" and conversation in exchange for payment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Draznin, Haley, Welch, Chris|first=Candiotti, Susan|title=Woman accused in Craigslist slaying tells newspaper: I've killed lots of others|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/16/justice/craigslist-thrill-killing-confession/|newspaper=CNN|date=February 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Scant evidence of satanic 'Craigslist killer' Miranda Barbour's claims of mass murder: authorities |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/newlyweds-accused-thrill-kill-craigslist-murder/story?id=21134460|newspaper=ABC News|date=December 7, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Mohney>{{cite news|title=Newlyweds Accused of Thrill-Kill Craigslist Murder|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/scant-evidence-satanic-craigslist-killer-claims-mass-murder-authorities-article-1.1619443|newspaper=NY Daily News|date=February 19, 2014|location=New York}}</ref>\n*In February 2014, [[Murder of Breck Bednar|Breck Brednar]], a 14-year-old boy from [[Redhill, Surrey]] was murdered by Lewis Daynes, an 18-year-old unemployed software engineer who groomed him online on a gaming site. Brednar was found dead in Daynes' flat in [[Grays|Grays, Essex]] and had been stabbed multiple times. Lewis Daynes was then sentenced to life imprisonment with a minimum of 25 years,\n\n*In February 2015, attorney David Messerschmitt was murdered in a hotel room in DC. According to police records, he had posted a listing on Craigslist requesting a sexual encounter, but was answered by two women who planned to rob him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/woman-charged-in-slaying-of-lawyer-once-wanted-to-be-a-police-officer/2015/04/02/b16536ea-d944-11e4-ba28-f2a685dc7f89_story.html|title=Police: Woman held in D.C. lawyer's slaying planned only to rob him|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture ==\n{{dynamic list}}\nThe theme of internet homicide has proven popular in fiction, with examples seen in books, television shows, and movies, in a number of which the murderer is referred to as \"the Internet Killer\" by other characters.\n\nThe following examples are listed by date order of publication or broadcast; three of them predate the arrest in 2000 of [[John Edward Robinson (serial killer)|John Edward Robinson]], thought by law enforcement to be \"the first Internet serial killer\":<ref name=\"len063000\"/>\n\n* The third-season episode of ''[[The X-Files]]'' titled \"[[2Shy]]\" featured as its [[monster of the week]] a fat-eating mutant named Virgil Incanto who seduced overweight women online and killed them upon meeting in real life.\n* The second season of the TV series ''[[Millennium (TV series)|Millennium]]'' featured an episode called ''The Mikado'', about a serial killer based loosely upon the [[Zodiac Killer]]. The killer would contact people on internet chat groups, kidnap them and then broadcast their death live via a [[webcam]] once the [[Web counter|site counter]] reached a certain level.\n* The fifth season of the TV series ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' featured two episodes involving Internet serial killers. The first, ''Risky Business'', was about a killer who set up a website encouraging teenagers to engage in [[auto-erotic asphyxiation]] in a particularly dangerous manner, tricking them into committing suicide. The second, ''The Internet Is Forever'', is about a serial killer who sets up hidden cameras in women's homes and strangles them to death while the whole act is being broadcast live on the web for his \"fans\" to see.\n* ''[[Strangeland (film)|Strangeland]]'' was a 1998 film written by [[Dee Snider]] about a schizophrenic sexual sadist who lures victims via the Internet, forcing them to submit to ancient tribal rituals. \"I came up with the idea of Internet crime before anybody had ever committed Internet crime,\" Snider has said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deesnider.com/index.php/news/210-strangeland-disciple-casting-call |title=Strangeland: Disciple Casting Call |publisher=Deesnider.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n* ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'', a [[television series]] [[police drama]], featured an extended multi-week storyline in May 1999 in which a character named Luke Ryland was known as \"The Internet Killer.\"\n* ''[[FeardotCom]]'' was a 2002 movie about a killer internet web site.<ref>''\"It looks like it's going to be a cheesy, senseless 'Internet killer' flick, when in reality 'Feardotcom' is a very cinematic, smart, only slightly senseless 'Internet killer' flick.\"'' {{cite web|url=http://media.www.theonlinerocket.com/media/storage/paper601/news/2002/09/06/Entertainment/Feardotcom.Dotbad-267853.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503191210/http://media.www.theonlinerocket.com/media/storage/paper601/news/2002/09/06/Entertainment/Feardotcom.Dotbad-267853.shtml |archivedate=2009-05-03 }}</ref>\n*''[[The Card Player|The Card Player (Il cartaio)]]'' was a 2004 film made in [[Italy]]; written and directed by [[Dario Argento]], it tells the story of a policewoman from [[Rome, Italy|Rome]] who teams up with a British [[Interpol]] agent to track down an internet serial killer who abducts and kills young women and broadcasts the crimes via Internet [[web cam]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0330691/plotsummary Plot summary for Il cartaio (2004) at [[IMDb]].</ref>\n* ''[[Untraceable]]'' was a 2008 [[Sony Pictures]] [[film]] starring [[Diane Lane]] in which [[FBI agent]] Jennifer Marsh was tasked with hunting down a seemingly untraceable serial killer who posted live videos of his victims on the Internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sonypictures.com/movies/untraceable/|title=Untraceable &#124; Sony Pictures|website=www.sonypictures.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.katu.com/entertainment/14237257.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504142347/http://www.katu.com/entertainment/14237257.html |archivedate=2009-05-04 }} ''The idea of the internet killer has been done before ([[Feardotcom]], [[The Card Player]])''</ref>\n* ''[[Downloading Nancy]]'' was a 2008 [[film]] starring [[Maria Bello]] in which unhappy wife Nancy Stockwell decides to end her life by meeting a man over the internet and forming a consensual agreement that he will kill her.\n* In March 2015, during the first week of ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'', host [[James Corden]] listed several dozen ways to connect with the show via social media. The list started with \"Follow me on [[Twitter]], Like me on [[Facebook]], ...\" and ended with \"or murder me on [[Craigslist]].\"\n* American Monster an [[Investigation Discovery]] television series documentary-drama episode titled: ''The Craigslist Killer'' aired: September 2017, dramatizes the serial killer Richard Beasley's online enticing of multiple men to their deaths.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Craigslist Killer {{!}} American Monster |url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/american-monster/full-episodes/the-craigslist-killer |website=www.investigationdiscovery.com |publisher=Discovery Communications, LLC. |accessdate=29 September 2018 |language=en-us |date=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=American Monster ''The Craigslist Killer'' (TV Episode 2017) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7151356/ |publisher=IMDb.com Incorporated |accessdate=29 September 2018 |date=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Assisted suicide]]\n* [[Computer crime]]\n* [[Consensual homicide]]\n* [[Internet suicide pact]]\n* [[Lonely hearts killer|Lonely hearts killer (or want-ad killer)]]\n* [[Online predator]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|journal=Slate|title=The Longform Guide to Craigslist Crime|author=Max Linsky|date=August 24, 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Internet Homicide}}\n[[Category:Internet safety]]\n[[Category:Cybercrime]]\n[[Category:Killings by type]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrays(link changed toGrays, Essex) usingDisamAssist.", "